<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Activities and Publications of the National Lawyer's Guild</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../gifs/servbut.gif" ALT="SERVICES" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../gifs/nlgban.gif" ALT="THE NATIONAL LAWYERS GUILD" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Activities and Publications of the National Lawyer's Guild</H3><BLOCKQUOTE>			The National Lawyers Guild is an association dedicated to the needfor basic change in the structure of our political and economic system.  We seek to unite the lawyers, law students, legal workers and jailhouse lawyers of America in an organization which shall function as an effective political and social force in the service of the people, to the end that human rights shall be regarded as more sacred than property interests.<P>The Guild's most important resource: the legal, personal, and political support network that exists among its members.  For more than half a century, the Guild has been the legal organization most relied upon by activists seeking social change within the United States.  It is the nation's oldest and largest public interest law organization.<H4>Legal Skills Development</H4><P>The New York City Charter holds regular forums on legal and political issues of concern to our community, such as police brutality, the housing crisis, homelessness, legal rights of domestic partners, international human rights, political surveillance, judicial diversity, domestic violence, and refugee rights.<P>The Guild sponsors national, regional, and city-wide conferences and seminars dealing with legal skills and noteworthy legal issues.  Recent seminars have focused on trial advocacy and the evaluation and preparation of civil rights suits.  In addition, groups meet periodically to develop and coordinate litigation and legislation strategies.<H4>Publications</H4><P>Members receive the national organization's quarterly -Guild Notes- and the chapter's monthly newsletter covering current legal issues and activities.<P>Practice manuals written by Guild members treating police misconduct law and litigation, AIDS issues, jury selection, immigration law and defense, women and the law, labor law, military and draft law, and representations of witnesses before federal grand juries are now available to the membership at discount rates.<P>A bibliography of all National Lawyers Guild publications is available from the New York City Chapter office.<H4>Committees</H4><P>New York City Chapter members participate in the following committees and projects: Mass Defense Committee, Labor Project, Immigration Committee, Lesbian/Gay Rights Committee, NY Metropolitan Student and New practitioner Group, the Faculty Network, Continuing Legal Education Committee, Members of the Judiciary Committee, and Amicus Brief Committee.<P>The staff in some Guild-sponsored projects can provide access to National brief banks, referral, and back-up services.  National projects include the Maurice Sugar Law Center and the National Immigration Project.  Together with The Center for Constitutional Rights, the Guild sponsors the Movement Support Network.<P>For Law Students<P>There are National Lawyers Guild chapters in over 105 law schools in the United States.  About 1,000 law students are full members of the Guild and participate in the programmatic committees, attend skills seminars, join Guild international delegations, and serve on the chapters executive committee.  Students are involved in every aspect of the work or our organization.<P>The Guild's National Law Students in Action Committee maintains a nation-wide network of law students who favor social change.  The committee publishes &quot;The Disorientation Guide,&quot; a survival manual for first- year students that offers advice on coping with the demands and pressures of law school, and support for those who would, financial problems notwithstanding, avoid the lure of large law firms.<P>Law students put their nascent legal skills to use in Guild committees, project, and internships.  The Summer Projects Program places law students all over the country.  Most recently, Guild law students have helped represent hundreds of detained Haitians in preparing asylum applications and have investigated the highly suspicious number of supposed inmate in Mississippi's prisons and jails.<P>The chapter has a summer jobs match-up program that assists in placing Guild students with Guild attorneys.  The chapter's Metropolitan Student and New Practitioner Group sponsors an annual People's Law Conference on alternative practice of law, as well as educational forums on issues,  police misconduct, and developing loan and forgiveness programs for graduates who choose public service employment.  Parties and receptions for students members, including an annual reception for students given by school faculty and members of the judiciary, help students survive law school and foster Guild principles.<P><A HREF="contnlg.html">Contact the Guild</A> to inquire further about it's activities and publications.</BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="nlg.html"><IMG SRC="../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
