<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Champion Paper Unwanted in Tennessee</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Champion Paper Made Unwanted in Tennessee</H3>
<PRE>Champion: SOCM Organizes (Un)Welcoming Ceremony

Contact:  Jerry Bone, SOCM
         tel. (423)426-9455  email - socm@conc.tdsnet.com

Campbell County, TN.:  Over 100 people gathered at the entrance to
Champion Paper's new chipmill this evening to protest the arrival of
large-scale clearcutting in East Tennessee.  The unwelcoming ceremony,
organized by the Campbell/Anderson Chapter of Save Our Cumberland
Mountains, brought out scores of locals.  They were joined by people from
middle Tennessee, Kentucky, North Carolina, and as far away as Indiana
who are also concerned about the fate of Southeastern forests.

As timber stocks are depleted in the Northwest, multinational timber and
paper interests are increasingly turning their attention back East.  These
companies are attracted to the millions of acres of forests which by now
have recovered from over-logging that occurred at the turn of the century.
They are also enticed by the lack of timbering regulation in most
Southeastern states.  Alabama and Mississippi's local logging industries
have already bottomed out as the large, outside companies end years of
clearcutting there and move to neighboring regions.  Several chipmills
have opened in Arkansas, Kentucky, and North Carolina over the past
year, and more are planned.  Champion's Campbell County mill is
Tennessee's first, but applications for more are currently in the works.

Members of Save Our Cumberland Mountains and allied groups, however,
are working hard to keep local economies based on sustainable logging
alive.  The message to big timber interests was loud and clear: citizens are
not prepared to sit by and let their forests be cleared and chipped up by a
company that will pull out in ten years without a fight.  They are getting
together in the rural areas where they live and, increasingly, they are
getting together with people from other areas as well.

But the SOCM protest was not a violent one.  People of all ages came out
and enjoyed Dr. Seuss-like poetry and street theater.  Fifteen-year-old
Anthony Lay read the tale of Champ-I-Am, the monster who stole the
Cumberland Mountains.  After a black ribbon was cut by a chainsaw, the
ceremony wound down and the crowd began to leave as songs written for
Champion and the Pigeon River were sung.  The strong show of support
from neighboring states tonight should not be misinterpreted by Champion
and other companies: people are going to be watching them, and fighting
them, wherever they go.

For copies of the Champ-I-Am story and more information, please contact
Jerry Bone at Save Our Cumberland Mountains, tel. 423/426-9455.

                         #   #   #

