<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Reports of Workers Around the World</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Reports of Workers Around the World</H3>
<PRE>-------------------------
Via Workers World News Service
Reprinted from the July 25, 1996
issue of Workers World newspaper
-------------------------

PUERTO RICO: U.S. CUSTOMS STAMPS P.R. PASSPORT

For the first time the U.S. government has had to
recognize Puerto Rican citizenship.

Juan Mari Br s, a long-time leader of the struggle for
Puerto Rican independence, renounced his U.S. citizenship in
1994 for Puerto Rican citizenship. While past treaties allow
Puerto Ricans to have Puerto Rican citizenship, they are
granted U.S. citizenship at birth. Until now, the U.S. has
never recognized Puerto Rican citizenship.

In order to assert his Puerto Rican citizenship, Mari Br s
traveled to Cuba to meet with President Fidel Castro on the
30th anniversary of the Puerto Rican Mission in Havana. When
he returned on June 30, he presented U.S. customs officials
with his Puerto Rican passport.

"I entered my country without problems," he said upon
returning to Puerto Rico. When the Immigration and
Naturalization Service agent asked him whether he was a U.S.
citizen or a foreigner, he responded that he was neither--
that he was Puerto Rican.

CZECH REPUBLIC: STEEL WORKERS APPEAL TO STOP PLANT CLOSING

The Trade Union Council at the Poldi steel works at
Kladno, near Prague, has appealed to the Czech Parliament to
stop the plant's closing. The 6,000 steel workers at Poldi
have been sent home for July and August. They have only
received part of their pay for May and June, according to a
July 9 Postmark Praha bulletin.

After the 1990 counter-revolution in Czechoslovakia ,
Poldi was one of the industries privatized by the new pro-
capitalist government.

In parliament, Communist Party Chairperson and Deputy
Miroslav Grebenicek called the workers' demands "wholly
justified." He said the privatization had been "ill-
conceived, hasty, and incorrect" from the beginning. He said
Poldi had been denied support by its Western competitors,
who have an interest in its failure, and that the state
should have retained a majority interest in the plant.

NEPAL: TELECOM WORKERS FIGHT PRIVATIZATION

When the Nepalese Ministry of Communications announced
last year that it would allow private companies to compete
against state-owned Nepal Telecom Corporation, workers vowed
to fight back. In June, the NTC Workers' Association
appealed to the ministry to reconsider its decision.

On July 2, the workers sent a warning--a temporary strike
in Katmandu, which shut down all telecommunication services
except automated ones for three hours, according to the
Xinhua news service.

On July 14, having made no progress, all 4,000 NTC workers
walked out indefinitely. They left phones unattended for
seven hours, allowing customers to use phones free of
charge. The union threatened to extend the strike to 12
hours beginning on July 17.

The center-right coalition government is presenting a bill
in the current session of parliament to allow private
companies to compete in telecommunications. The communist
opposition in parliament has vowed to fight the bill.

Workers say the move will raise current fees fourfold.
They also say the private companies will concentrate on the
urban centers to the exclusion of rural Nepalese.

KENYA: WORKERS BATTLE COPS, FIGHT FOR BACK PAY

The Nairobi City Council owes 17,000 city workers close to
$9 million for back wages dating back to 1993. On July 10,
thousands left their jobs and took to the streets, marching
through Nairobi's main commercial district.

Sewer cleaning, health services, schools, and all
government services were completely shut down, according to
a July 11 Reuter report.

As the marchers set up barricades on the main road, riot
police attacked the workers with tear gas and batons. Dozens
were reported injured.

The government has taken a particularly anti-worker
posture in the dispute. "If they complain that they are not
paid, I am complaining that they do not work," Nairobi Mayor
John King'ori quipped. The government has offered to pay
workers a tenth of their back wages.

 UKRAINE: COAL MINERS' STRIKE WIDENS

Mine workers across the Ukraine entered their second week
on strike to win back pay July 10. The strike, which began
on July 3 with 100,000 workers, now includes some 180,000
miners in 90 mines. That amounts to over 40 percent of
Ukraine's 227 mines.

"The strike has no deadline," Yuri Berdnyk said. Berdnyk
is the head of public relations for the Independent Miners'
Union of Ukraine. "We will only end the strike if we are
offered clear guarantees that government officials will pay
miners' wages," he said.

The government owes coal workers an estimated 110 trillion
karbonets ($611 million), according to Reuter.

On July 11, thousands of the strikers sat down on
railroads and highways for the third consecutive day,
blocking transportation for three hours. "Before lying down
on the track we tried to negotiate, but nobody listened,"
said Yuri Telnoi, a member of the Independent Miners' Union
executive committee.

The Ukrainian government has said that it will offer a
partial payment to the workers if they go back to work. In
February, the government settled a two-week strike by paying
the workers 13.5 trillion karbonets in back wages.

But there are no signs that the miners' conditions will
improve soon. The capitalist-oriented government has plans
to shut 100 mines over the next five years, Reuter reports.

The World Bank is currently considering a $250-million
loan to Ukraine--on the condition that it reorganize the
coal industry and close 40 mines.

 NICARAGUA: TRANSPORT WORKERS WIN 2-DAY STRIKE

International lenders, trying to reverse "populist"
legislation in Nicaragua's parliament, hoped to have
transportation workers shoulder more of the public debt in
that country. Their hopes were dashed against a solid wall
of workers' resistance.

On July 9, a bill was introduced into the Nicaraguan
parliament that would have ended import duty exemptions for
vehicles, engines, spare parts, and other goods essential to
the transportation industry. That would have meant higher
operating costs and bus and taxi fares, according to Jose
Guerra, the president of the transportation union in
Managua.

So the day the bill was introduced, workers shut down
30,000 buses and taxis. The workers parked hundreds of
buses, taxis and trucks in front of the National Assembly. A
July 11 UPI report called the strike "crippling."

After two days, the National Assembly voted to maintain
the current import exemptions. "We have won a civic battle,"
said Antonio Betanco, vice president of the Nicaraguan
Public Transport Federation.

Advisers to the government of President Violetta Chamorro,
beholden to the International Monetary Fund and the World
Bank, condemned the vote. Chamorro has threatened to veto
the legislation. But union leaders threatened to fight to
the end.

"If the president vetoes the bill, we are going to prepare
for a new strike, because we are not going to retreat one
step on this issue," said taxi union leader Nicolas Mendoza.

 INDIA: TAXI DRIVERS ROLL BACK FUEL PRICES

Facing the contradictions inherent in a center-left
coalition government, Indian Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda
approved a 30-percent increase in the price of diesel fuel
during the first week of July--only to be forced to cut the
increase to 15 percent under heavy political pressure.

But for taxi drivers, whose livelihood is tied to the
price of fuel, the rollback wasn't enough. Over 50,000
drivers in Bombay, India's financial capital, stayed off the
roads for a five-day strike beginning on July 8 in response
to the price hike.

On July 12, city officials capitulated. They approved a
22-percent increase in taxi fares, and promised to look into
the 35-percent raise the drivers demanded.

"Officials have assured us that they will look into our
demand within three months," Bombay Taximen Union
spokesperson Louis Valerrian told UPI July 12.

                         - END -

