<H3>Nigerians Protest at Olympic Games</H3>
<PRE>Wednesday July 17, 1996
excerpted from Atlanta Journal & Constitution

Members of the Nigerian Alliance for Democracy protested against their
country's involvement in the Centennial Games during their country's
reception for the Olympic athletes [downtown Atlanta].. Protesters are
against the military dictatorship of Gen. Sami Abacha. But barring the
althletes from competition would be a devastating blow to athletes and
coaching staff, said Amelia Edet, head coach of Nigeria's track and field
team.

        **************************END***********************************

STATE FLAG ISSUE GRABS THE SPOTLIGHT
By Christina Headrick, Staff Writer
Atlanta Journal & Constitution, 7/17/96

Today the fight to change the Gerogia state flag moves daramatically to
an international battleground. At a news conference this morning, the
Coalition to Change the Flag will kick off its Olympic project: hourlong
demonstrations starting at noon everyday of the Games beneath state flags
flying in the Olympic Ring. And that's just the beginning of
demonstrations and bags of mail that flag opponents say state officials
can expect during the Olympics. Opponents consider the flag a symbol of
racism, modified in 1956 to include the Confederate St. Andrws cross in
order to express state defiance and desegregation.

        "We will tell people that this is the Georgia Swastika", said
state Rep. Tyrone Brooks [D-Atlanta], leader of the Coalition to Change
the Flag. "It stands for segregation. It stands for everthing that is bad
about this country". Coalition protests will occur at the state Capitol
and state-owned Gerogia Dome, as well as private buildings at 101
Marietta St. and the Sun Trust Bank and 25 Park Place where the flag
flies. The coalition, composed of 25 civil rights groups, is asking
athletes to protest individually and businesses to avoid Georgia until
the flag is changed said Joe Beasley, regional director of the Rainbow
Coalition.

The controversy flared a month ago, when the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games announced the flag would be banned from within Olympic
venues because of an International Olympic Committee guideline that
permits only national flags. Supporters of the flag say changing or
banning the flag from the Olympics is an affront to Georgians. Among
those coming to the flag's defense are the Sons of Confederate Veterans,
led by Georgia chapter ommander Scott Gilbert, the group, which preserves
Confederate history, also will provide flag facts at venues. On Friday
and Saturday, more than 30 national and local groups will hold the
International Speakout Against the Olympics at the Capitol. The flag will
be a major theme on Saturday, said organizer Lorenzo Komboa Ervin of
Black Autonomy International.

Americans from other states have added their voices too. Youth at the
not-for-profit City Kids Foundation in New York mailed 2,000 letters from
their peers Tuesday to Governor Zell Miller, asking him to lower the flag
at venues. Teenagers at the leadership institute also plan to send 3,000
e-mail letters from all over the country to ACOG.

***********************************************END*************************
********
AS FLAME HEADS INTO TOWN, GEORGIA FLAG WILL BURN.
By Michelle Hiskey, Staff Writer
7/18/96 Atlanta Journal-Constituton

A coalition opposin the Georgia flag plans to burn one on the steps of
the state Capitol on Friday night. Former Dekalb County Commissioner
Hosea Williams an State Rep. Tyrone Brooks [D-Atlanta] plan to lead a
march from the King Center as the Olympic Torch passes. But while the
torch heads to City Hall and the Opening Cermonies, the demonstrators
plan to stop at the Capitol and burn the flag, which they consider a
symbol of racism and oppression.

The Coalition to Change the Georgia Flag--made up of black, jewish,
student, civil rights and homeless rights organizations--also plans a
series of noon anti-flag demonstrations to begin Monday and continue
throughout the Games. Sites include the Capitol again Monday and th
Georgia Dome, an Oympic venue, on Thursday. Others are SunTrust Bank
downtown, which flies the flag, on Tuesday and the 101 Marietta buildin,
which houses several federal offices, Wednesday. "We are not
demonstrating against the Olympics, which are about harmony an peace,"
state Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III [D-Atlanta] said at a news
conference Wednesday in front of the Capitol. We are doemonstrating
against this racist Swastika. It's out of place in our Olympics. "

Williams said civil rights abuses have run rampant under the current
flag. Anita Beaty of the Task Force for the Homeless sai she had records
of 9,500 homeless African-American men arrested during the year ending in
May.

