<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: SF Indonesian Consulate-22 Arresed</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>SF Indonesian Consulate-22 Arrested</H3>
<PRE>Supporters of East Timor from throughout the San Francisco Bay area
converged on the Indonesian consulate yesterday, joining people from around
the world in protesting the 20th anniversary of the illegal annexation of
East Timor by Indonesian and standing in solidarity with the brave women
and men of East Timor.
Organized by East Timor Religious Outreach, the demonstration attracted
more than 90 people, including ministers from Presbyterian, Lutheran and
Methodist denominations and several Catholic priests.  Many other
organizations lent their support, including ETAN/SF, Pax Christi,
Plowshares West, Catholic Worker House, Global Exchange, Ecumenical Peace
Institute and Overseas Development Network.  Also on hand were a dozen
students from Youth for Justice, who had come down from Eugene, Oregon.
Chalk was distributed to the demonstrators, who covered the sidewalk around
the consulate with messages of solidarity for the people of East Timor and
messages of anger and condemnation for the Indonesian government and their
allies.
After several moving speeches by members of ETRO, ETAN and others, the
demonstrators went on a procession from the consulate to Fisherman's Wharf,
the heart of San Francisco's tourist district.  Carrying numerous large
banners and placards, along with several coffins with flowers on them, the
procession marched to the Wharf, handing out almost a thousand flyers to
interested passers-by, particularly those at a Nike store.  Throughout the
demonstration, there was a heavy police presence, with nearly one policeman
for every three demonstrators.
When the procession returned, an attempt was made to meet with the
consulate officials, who had long since closed the consulate, turned off
the lights and retreated to the second floor.  However, the Indonesian
officials did not answer the repeated ringing of their buzzer.  At that
point, 22 demonstrators occupied the consulate grounds, clapping and
chanting slogans.  They remained there, some of them for quite a while,
until they were arrested by the SFPD and charged with trespassing.  The
arrestees ranged in age from 77 to 16, with two high school students
deciding to be arrested (their first time, too) to show their support for
the people of East Timor.  Those arrested were released shortly afterward.

The demonstration showed once again that San Francisco is no safe haven for
those guilty of the genocide in East Timor, and that the pressure here, and
around the world, will only continue to increase until Indonesia recognizes
its crime, withdraws from East Timor and agrees to a UN supervised
referendum.
On Monday, Plowshares West will stage a vigil in front of the consulate,
marking the beginning of the Seeds of Hope/East Timor Ploughshares trial in
Liverpool, England. On Thursday, Global Exchange is hosting a talk by Cicih
Sukaesih, a former Nike factory worker from Indonesia who was unfairly
dismissed from Nike for organizing fellow workers for better working
conditions and livable wages.

