<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Story of a Trial</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Story of an Activist's Trial</H3>
<PRE>NOTE: This posting is the first in a series of three postings related to
Tim Ream's recent arrest for protesting the Red 90 salvage sale in the
Willamette National Forest. The following two postings contain the text
of legal documents filed in Tim's court case.  These postings are
important for anyone interested in this subject as they set forth the
facts of Tim's case and lay out the constitutional arguments Tim is
advancing in court.

* * * * * * * * *


TIM REAM ON TRIAL FOR PEACEFUL PROTEST ON PUBLIC LANDS:  Earlier this
month well known forest activist and hunger striker Tim Ream  (last
winter Tim fasted for 75 days in front of the Federal Courthouse in
Eugene, Oregon, to protest the Salvage Logging Rider) found himself
pitted against three Linn County Sheriffs and four Forest Rangers, all in
full uniform and carrying side arms.  This dramatic confrontation
occurred not in the national forests, but in the courtroom as Tim Ream
represented himself against charges of criminal trespass for allegedly
violating a special closure order in the Willamette National Forest.  The
details of Tim's arrest and of his courtroom exploits are set out below.

On April 26, 1996, the Willamette National Forest Supervisor issued
Special Closure Order No. 192 to prevent members of the public from
venturing near the "Red 90" timber sale.  The Red 90 sale is in the
Detroit District of the Willamette National Forest and is one of the many
old growth timber sales being cut as a result of the Salvage Logging
Rider ("Logging Without Laws").

The next day, Tim Ream and numerous other concerned citizens traveled to
the Red 90 sale for a peaceful protest of the sale and of the rider which
authorized it.  Tim's protest activities consisted of public speaking,
chanting, walking, shouting, singing, prayer and an interview with a
reporter.  The protest was entirely peaceful and non-violent.  It was
conducted away from the logging sale area, and no logging was being done
at the time.

During the course of the protest, Tim and several other protesters were
arrested and charged with criminal trespass under state law for allegedly
violating the closure order.  Tim was later subjected to a strip search
and threatened with a 23 hour per day lockdown.  The lockdown would
continue until Tim's arraignment unless he paid a bond and agreed to
certain "special" conditions which included a prohibition on all contacts
with the Forest Service.

Tim pleaded not guilty at his arraignment, and a trial date was set for
June 13, 1996.  Prior to his trial, Tim filed a motion to dismiss his
charges on the grounds that the closure order violated his First
Amendment rights to freedom of speech, freedom of association, freedom of
religion and right to petition government for redress of grievances.

Tim's motion was based on pleadings filed by attorney Helga Kahr in the
case of U.S.A. vs. Benjamin White.  Like Tim's case, the White case
involved the arrest of a forest activist for alleged violation of a
special closure order (in the Olympic National Forest in Washington).  In
the White case, attorney Helga Kahr argued that because the closure order
was much larger than necessary to protect public safety it unnecessarily
burdened free speech activities and was therefore unconstitutional.
Federal Magistrate J. Kelley Arnold agreed with Kahr and dismissed the
charges against White.

On the day of Tim's trial, law enforcement vehicles were lined up for
nearly a block outside the tiny Lebanon-Sweet Home Justice Court.  Inside
the courtroom, it was equally clear the Linn County Sheriff's Department
and the Forest Service had come loaded for bear.  No fewer than seven
officers were present, all in full uniform and all carrying side arms.

Despite their initial show of force (quite literally), it soon became
clear that even a small army of law enforcement personnel would be no
match for Tim.  Although a non-lawyer, Tim quickly took control of the
courtroom procedure and managed to exclude several key pieces of the
prosecution's evidence.  Among the evidence Tim managed to have excluded
was the closure order itself.  Although Tim had repeatedly requested this
key piece of evidence from the prosecution, and was legally entitled to
it under Oregon law, the prosecution apparently "misplaced" it until 15
minutes before trial.  Ruling that the state's failure to produce this
document in a timely fashion violated Tim's rights, the judge excluded it
from evidence

On cross-examination, Tim was merciless and unerring in his quest for the
truth.  Among the more remarkable, and damaging, testimony extracted by
Tim's cross-examination was that of Forest District Supervisor Bill Funk.
 Under Tim's questioning, Funk admitted that part of his motivation for
signing the closure order was "economic" and to protect the progress of
the sale -- even though under federal regulations such reasons are not
valid bases for a closure order.  When asked about public safety, which
is a legally valid reason for a closure order, Funk suggested that he was
concerned that loose logs might roll down the hillside and injure
protesters.  When asked by Tim to indicate the location of the "loose
logs" on a map, Funk pointed to a location more than a half-mile away
from the protest and in another county.  Funk claimed, and then later
retracted, that a log could roll a quarter of a mile down a logging road
and injure a protester.   The significance of this exchange was not lost
on the judge

Near the end of the trial, the prosecution attempted to rebut the
constitutional arguments in Tim's earlier motion by filing its own
written response.  Tim strenuously objected to the state's response,
pointing out that the state had violated procedural rules by waiting
until the last minute to file this document, not to mention principles of
fairness and due process.  The judge agreed and refused to even consider
the state's written arguments.

Tim concluded his defense with a forceful legal argument challenging the
constitutionality of the closure order itself.  What the Sheriff's
Department and the Forest Service had expected to be a brief and easy
trial had by now evolved into a five hour marathon in which they were met
with complete resistance at every step of the way.  So forceful were
Tim's arguments that the judge declined to give a ruling and instead
informed the parties that he would take the matter under advisement for
further consideration.  A final decision is due in the next thirty days.


** End of text from cdp:headlines **

