<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Forest Activist Seize Road to Stop Logging</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Oregon Activists Seize Road to Stop Logging</H3>
<PRE>CHINA LEFT BLOCKADED! SISKIYOU FOREST DEFENDERS OCCUPY ROAD
        COME TO PUBLIC DEMONSTRATION ON MONDAY, JULY 8 AT 10:00AM

Forest protection activists from the Siskiyou bioregion have taken the law
into their own hands to prevent further clearcut logging of ancient
forests at the China Left Timber Sale, in the Siskiyou National Forest
near Cave Junction, Oregon. Using their own bodies and a number of
blockades and lockdown devices, the Siskiyou Forest Defenders (SFD) have
taken over the logging road leading to the controversial China Left sale,
beginning a sustained Warner Creek-style occupation of the area. On Monday
July 8th at 10a.m. there will be a large demo at the blockade on Forest
Service Road 080. Many people from all walks of life will be attending
this demonstration against Rough and Ready Lumber Co. and the Siskiyou
National Forest.

The China Left sale would clearcut hundreds of acres of ancient forest in
and adjacent to the Kangaroo Roadless area, a critical wildlife corridor
in southwest Oregon. This section 318 sale lies within the headwaters of
the Sucker Creek drainage, and has one of the healthiest steelhead runs in
the upper Illinois River basin. There is also a spawning population of
threatened coho salmon in Sucker Creek just below the sale units; these
salmon are in imminent danger of extinction due to the erosion and loss of
canopy cover caused by the proposed China Left clearcuts. This 12.7
million board foot sale consists of 16, so called "units" that total 530
acres. 274 of these acres are clearcuts.

In 1993, the Siskiyou National Forest withdrew China Left from
consultation with the US Fish and Wildlife Service because: "We judged the
impact from the sale on Critical Habitat to be unacceptable, and the sale
could not be easily modified to eliminate the negative impacts.
[Therefore, the Siskiyou National Forest assumed the China Left Timber
Sale could not be awarded.]" (from "Supplemental Biological Assessment
for China Left Timber Sale", USFS, February 28, 1995.) But China Left,
along with Sugarloaf, was reinstated in the Record of Decision for
Clinton's "Option Nine" Forest Plan, as a political concession to the
timber industry. The "Salvage Rider" of 1995 ensured that China Left and
Sugarloaf could proceed without being subject to environmental laws.

To get to the site: From Hwy 199, in Cave Junction, drive east on Caves
Hwy (Hwy 46) nine miles to FS road 4612. Follow 4612 for another eight
miles until reaching FS road 080 on the left. Walk 1/2 mile up 080.

For more information, call: (541)732-3101

--
Karen Wood
"Nonviolence is love in action."


