<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Protesters Sneak Into Nuclear Reactor</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Protesters Sneak Into Nuclear Reactor</H3>
<PRE>PRAGUE, July 9 (Reuter) - Environmentalists blockading a Czech nuclear 
power station sneaked into the half-completed plant on Tuesday in a protest 
which they said showed gaps in the site's security. 

One group of demonstrators hung a protest banner on the Soviet-designed 
Temelin plant while another got hold of two plans of the construction site, 
said Vojtech Kotecky, one of the protest organisers. 

``The whole plant should be sufficiently guarded against penetration by 
anybody, and it is not,'' Kotecky told Reuters. 

``One group fixed a banner saying ``Stop Temelin' and another one...managed 
to remove documents without any resistance. We will, of course, give them 
back,'' he added in a telephone interview from the south Bohemian site. 

But another organiser, Jan Beranek, said some of those who got into the 
guarded area had been detained by security guards and police, although they 
were later released. 

Construction of Temelin, about 120 km (70 miles) south of Prague, is strongly 
opposed by environmental groups in the Czech Republic and neighbouring Austria, 
who say it is dangerous, expensive and unnecessary. 

Work began before the 1989 fall of communism but was halted temporarily before 
resuming under a plan to complete the plant using U.S.-supplied technology. 

Temelin has been the site of repeated protests and the latest began on Sunday 
when about 200 people put up barricades and chained themselves to barrels filled 
with concrete in front of the plant's gates. 

Police removed some of them by force when workers started arriving at the plant 
on Monday morning. 

Kotecky said that the protesters were still blocking several of the power station's 
gates in the protest which they said might end on Wednesday afternoon. 

Temelin, which might open in 1998 after many delays, is equipped with two 
Soviet-designed VVER-1000 reactors. Its control system is supplied by Westinghouse 
Electric Corp of the United States. 

The plant's owner, power firm CEZ a.s., argues that opening Temelin will allow it 
to close some of its heavily polluting coal-fuelled plants in the northern Czech 
Republic. 

But the protesters are demanding a halt to work on Temelin and the creation of a 
parliamentary commission to investigate contracts between CEZ and Westinghouse, 
including repeated cost increases of the project. </PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
