<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Georgia Protest in Sympathy with Detroit News Strike</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Georgians Storm "Telograph" in Support of Detroit News Strikers</H3>
<PRE>By Stephanie Jordan Johnson, The Macon Telegraph, Ga.

Knight-Ridder/Tribune Business News

MACON, Ga.--Jun. 25--Union demonstrators rushed into The Macon Telegraph
building Monday afternoon shoving past newspaper employees and yelling chants
as a show of support for workers at a Detroit newspaper who went on strike
nearly a year ago.

About 150 people representing the AFL-CIO, Communications Workers of
America, Georgia State Employees Union, and Graphic Printers International
Union walked into the newspaper's lobby, chanting loudly and shaking soda-can
rattles.

The protesters blocked entry into the newspaper building and jostled
several workers coming and going from the Telegraph. They refused to leave
when asked to by Telegraph security personnel.

The crowd was eventually forced back outside the building, where a
member with a bullhorn led the group in chants of "Georgia workers ain't
gonna take it more," "We're fired up" and "We want justice."

"This is not our workers' issue," said Carol Hudler, publisher of The
Macon Telegraph. Hudler said it wouldn't be appropriate for the newspaper in
Macon to take a position on another Knight-Ridder newspaper.

The Free Press and The Macon Telegraph are owned by Knight-Ridder and
the Detroit News is owned by Gannett Co., which also owns Macon's WMAZ-TV
Channel 13. The two Detroit newspapers have a joint operating agreement which
combines many business operations, but the editorial staffs are separate.

Most of the union members were wearing red and black T-shirts with "New
Day for Georgia Workers" on the front and "I'm Backing Acuff" on the back,
referring to Stewart Acuff, who is president of the Atlanta Labor Council.

Acuff said if Knight-Ridder Inc. executives want to fight with union
members of the Detroit Free Press and Detroit News, they'll have to fight
with members in Macon, too. He defended the group's action by saying the
picket is an old tradition in the labor movement.

"The real issue is the way workers are treated in America," Acuff said.

During the protest, Acuff was led away in handcuffs by Macon police who
were called after the picketers got rowdy. He was charged with criminal
trespass and was released on a $550 bond later Monday, a jail spokesman said.

A local labor leader who asked not to be identified said Monday's
protest at the Telegraph was "not an organized event from the local labor
council."

He suggested that the picket was a political ploy. Acuff is running for
the posi tion of the president of the Georgia AFL-CIO.

"Now he's a martyr," he said after Acuff's was arrested at the
Telegraph.

The Atlanta organizers of the picket sent a flyer to Macon last week
about the event, but it was not given approval locally, the local labor
leader said.

-----

     ON THE INTERNET:

     Visit The Macon Telegraph Online, the World Wide Web site of The Macon
Telegraph. Point your browser to <a href="http://www.macontel.com">http://www.macontel.com</a>

     -----

</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
