<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Account of Indiana Flag-Burning Arrest</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Account of Flag-Burning Arrest</H3>
<PRE>THE STRUGGLE CONTINUES FOR ZIYON YISRAYAH!

Mmoja Ajabu was arrested during an Indianapolis protest on behalf of Ziyon.
This was reported in the mainstream press, but here is the story according
to Brother Ajabu himself:  The goal was to burn an American flag at the
Olympic torch procession.  Protesters, who included members of the Back
Panther Militia, were attempting to burn their OWN American flag, which is
a PEACEFUL and LEGAL form of protest.  They planned to do this to highlight
the hypocrisy of carrying the olympic torch to Indiana at the same time
that the clemency board was holding a hearing and then voting to kill
Ziyon.  The official words at the torch procession were all about democracy
and goodwill, but the official government actions that same day were all
about racism, corruption, and legal lynching.

When the protesters tried to set their own flag on fire, the police said
they could not burn the flag.  Ajabu asked why not? -- it's a first
amendment right to protest this way.  Then the police grabbed the flag and
maced Ajabu when he tried to grab it back.  Ajabu, like many men of African
descent, has a record from other incidents, and was on release under bond.
In this flag burning attempt he reports that he was charged with reckless
endangerment with a deadly weapon (the cigarette lighter? -- give us a
break!!!) and is now threatened with having his bond revoked, which would
result in his incarceration.

BRO. AJABU FACES A BOND REVOCATION HEARING on
JULY 1, 1996, at 1:30 pm., Courtroom 9 in the City County Building in
Indianapolis.  DEMAND AN END TO THE PERSECUTION OF
THESE BROTHERS!

Political activism around Ziyon's murder has led to the repression of other
people.  The prison is on lockdown, and some prisoners were shipped to the
control unit in Westville.  Ajabu now risks losing his freedom because he
participated in a legal, non-violent protest.  He says it was not his
intent to be in any altercation over the flag, but simply to join with
others to burn the flag as a symbol of their peaceful, yet strong, protest
on behalf of Ziyon.  The altercation resulted from police actions to stop a
non-violent, civil protest.

WRITE LETTERS DEMANDING that Mmoja Ajabu not be persecuted
for exercising his constitutional right to protest.  Send letters to:
        Scott Newman
        Marion County Prosecutor
        City County Building (Room 560)
        200 East Washington Street
        Indianapolis, IN 46204
        phone:  317/327-3522
=================================</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
