<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Four Arrested at Toronto Military Subcontracting Expo</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Four Arrested at Toronto Military Subcontracting Expo</H3>
<PRE>Press Release
Canadian Voice of Women for Peace
National Office
736 Bathurst St.
Toronto, ON  M5S 2R4

Tel: (416) 537-9343
Fax: (416) 531-6214


SUBCON VIII EXHIBITION PROTEST:
4 WOMEN ARRESTED DURING PROTEST AGAINST CANADIAN MILITARY
EXPORTS

When:  Thursday, June 13, 9 am
Where:    Toronto Congress Centre, 650 Dixon Rd.

Four women were arrested last week during a protest organized by Canadian
Voice of Women for Peace against the SUBCON VIII Exhibition taking place
today at the Toronto Congress Centre.  The four were charged with trespass
and then released.

The protest was aimed at the subcontracting for the sale of military support
systems by companies attending the exhibition.  These support systems include
weapons systems and sub-systems that use technologies such as robotics,
electronics, simulation and aerospace.

The exhibition is sponsored by the Canadian Defence Preparedness Association
(CDPA) and the Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade.
Contrary to its Red Book promise of conversion, the Liberal government is
actively promoting the export of military technologies such as those being
sold at SUBCON VIII.

About 30 protestors picketed and handed out leaflets to conference goers.
Four women refused to move from a gate where they were preventing cars from
driving to the exhibition site and were arrested by police officers.

Voice of Women calls upon the Government of Canada to live up to its Red Book
promise and stop promoting the export of technologies which are used for
military purposes.  VOW deplores the priorities of our current government
which cuts social programs under the guise of restraint while continuing to
spend billions of our tax dollars on the military.

                              -30-

** End of text from cdp:headlines **

