<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Second Vigil for E. Timor in Darwin</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Second Vigil for E. Timor in Darwin</H3>
<PRE>Darwin Expo: A demonstration of solidarity with ET & WP

Protesters held their second vigil for the week outside Darwin's
Indonesian consulate today. The protesters were taking advantage
of the record presence of Indonesian, West Papuan and especially,
East Timorese business people attending Darwin's Business Expo.

The protesters were in an excellent position to promote a free East
Timor and West Papua and denounce INTEL and ABRI before the
constant stream of visitors to the consulate to the annoyance of
Indonesian government officials.

The expo guests have also found it impossible to miss the huge
number of posters covering the city centre. The posters range in
content from "Free East Timor" to those promoting Falantil or
featuring atrocities committed by ABRI. Many of the guests seem
bewildered by the strength of support in the city for East Timor and
West Papua. A spokes-person for Australians for a Free East Timor
said that with such a large presence of Timorese business people
in town, it was crucial to demonstrate solidarity and support in an
unmistakable way.

During the demonstration, federal protection officers confiscated two
anti-Suharto banners. When the guards refused to return the
banners at the end of the vigil, the protesters entered the grounds
of the consulate and confronted the guards and consular officials
who took photos and closed the gates effectively preventing any
exit.

However, police failed to arrive and make arrests and the scene
was becoming an embarrassment for the consulate as guests
looked on in wonder. Eventually, after some minutes, the protesters
were allowed to leave with their banners.

Darwin's Expo begins on Friday and runs until Sunday. The
solidarity community will set up an information stall outside the
entrance which will demonstrate strong support for East Timor and
West Papua and help discredit the Suharto regime.

** End of text from cdp:reg.easttimor **

