<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Reports of Nationwide Actions on Guatemala</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Reports of Nationwide Actions on Guatemala on June 19th</H3>
<PRE>Summary of Activities by Grassroots Groups --
These are the actions that have come to our attention.  Additional
prayer services may have been held that we have not gotten word of
yet.

Many calls were made to the White House Comments Line on Wednesday
and continue to be made.  Protests/vigils were held on Wednesday,
June 19, in 11 cities.  Many were creative and attracted media
attention.  Faith-based groups played a key role.  Two groups
placed ads in their local papers.

Vigil Sites (6/19/96):

Boston, MA:  40 people attended a rally in front of the Federal
Building that featured a "washing of the American flag."  Sponsored
by the Citizens Action Team.  The presence lasted from 12 to 6pm.
Post cards were handed out.  A Pacifica radio reporter covered the
event.  Activists are working to prepare the local media for the
IOB report release.

Washington, DC:  From 5:30 to 6:30 pm 40 people attended a rally in
front of the Old Executive Office Building, where the Intelligence
Oversight Board offices are located.  Protesters carried large
posters made using the sketches of Sister Dianna's torturers, which
read "WANTED for torture" at the bottom.  Carlos Salinas of Amnesty
International spoke.  Marie Dennis, of the Maryknoll Office of
Justice and Peace, and Rev. Joe Nangle read from a prayer service.

Baltimore, MD:  Jonah House, a Catholic Worker community, and
others staged a rally in front of the Federal Building.  20 people
attended.  Flyers were handed out.

Raleigh, NC:  a local church sponsored a prayer service (details
are still sketchy)

Knoxville, TN:  local group placed an advertisement in the local
Sentinel News appealing for full declassification

Louisville, KY:  A noon rally was staged at a busy intersection,
attracting 25 protesters.  Sponsored by the Kentucky Interfaith
Task Force on Central America.  750 flyers were handed out -- there
were many supportive passersby.  The same day the group purchased
an advertisement which ran in the local paper calling for complete
declassification.  An evening prayer service at an Ursuline
motherhouse attracted 100 people.  A number of Guatemalans who live
locally offered their testimonies.

Chicago, IL:  A vigil was staged in front of the federal building
from 12 to 1 by the Chicago Religious Leadership Network.  At least
60 people attended.  Sister Suzanne Sims, an Ursuline sister who
has supported Sister Dianna's efforts, spoke.  A Spanish language
newspaper covered the event, as did a local English language TV
station.  The TV station aired a report on the evening news.  Every
day at noon time local activists are handing out postcards at the
Federal Building.

Cleveland, OH:  the Cleveland Interreligious Task Force on Central
America staged a rally at the Federal Building that attracted a
good size crowd and garnered excellent media coverage including a
story in the Cleveland Plain Dealer.  Guatemalans who live locally
offered moving testimony.  Protesters demanded action by Sens.
DeWine and Glenn (both on the Senate Intelligence Committee).  This
prompted the Plain Dealer reporter to call Glenn's office for a
response, which was included in the article!

Cincinnati, OH:  About 50 people attended a prayer service at the
Federal Building organized by the Intercommunity Justice and Peace
Center.  Local religious communities also sponsored prayer services
at their communities.  Coverage by local Catholic paper, as well as
one local TV station.  Got agreement by Rep. Rob Portman to write
a letter about the issue to Clinton.

McAllen, TX:  Local activists handed out postcards and leaflets in
front of the Federal Building.  Local coordinator was interviewed
by a border area Spanish language newspaper.

Eugene, OR:  60 to 70 people attended a rally at the Federal
Building sponsored by CISCAP.  The event included music, a
responsive reading, and testimonials from recent visitors to
Guatemala.  There was some local TV coverage as well as radio.

Phoenix, AZ:  Approximately 15 people attended a rally in 110
degree heat in front of the Federal Building.  Sponsored by CAMBIO.

Numerous flyers were passed out.  Activists will be working to get
message to local media contacts.

ACTION ALERT:  Groups are now preparing for the release of the
Intelligence Oversight Board report, expected on Friday, June 28.
Some are planning vigils for Friday.

SUGGESTED ACTION:  Contact your local paper and notify them they
will likely be receiving a wire story about the release of the
Intelligence Oversight Board report on Friday.  Ask them to please
run the wire story when they get it.

Then ask to speak to the editorial desk.  Let them know that you
will be sending them information about the release that would help
provide background for an editorial by the paper.  This information
will be posted in peacenet (or emailed to you) for you to download
and then drop off at the offices of your local paper.

Also let the editorial desk know that you will be submitting an
opinion piece in response to the release of the report by the
Clinton administration.  To write the piece refer to the analysis
of the report we will be putting out.  Consider asking a local
faith leader to sign or co-author the piece.

The following cities will have vigils/rallies this coming Friday:

Cleveland, OH
Houston, TX
San Antonio, TX

For more information contact 202-462-3935.

==============================================================

Here is a copy of the article the Cleveland protest led to:


Copyright 1996 Plain Dealer Publishing Co.
The Plain Dealer
June 20, 1996 Thursday, FINAL / ALL
SECTION: SCENE & HEARD; Pg. 7B
HEADLINE: PROTESTERS CRY FOR U.S. HELP IN GUATEMALA
BYLINE: By KAREN R. LONG; PLAIN DEALER REPORTER
DATELINE: CLEVELAND

   Mirna Carias Corrigan, a registered nurse at McCafferty Health
Center in Cleveland, faced a few curious strangers yesterday on
Public Square to explain why she is unhealed.

   "My two brothers, 13 and 16, were kidnapped by the government of
Guatemala," Corrigan said into a faulty, hand-held microphone.
"They didn't get a chance. They were disappeared ...

   "It's very important we hold people accountable in our
government to put a stop to the crimes committed in Central
America," she said, her lower lip trembling. "I am very emotional.
We need to demand that the CIA make the documents public so we can
get on with our lives."

   Mirna Carias Corrigan's brothers, Herbert and Cesar, were
snatched off the streets of Guatemala City where they had kicked
soccer balls and walked back and forth to school. It was 1983. The
surviving family, scattered in Cleveland and Toronto, has not seen
them since.

   "It's still very painful to live with it day and night," said
Corrigan, who was 20 when her brothers disappeared. She married a
Clevelander three years later and came north.

   Her story was part of a larger protest staged simultaneously in
Chicago, Houston, Washington, Baltimore, Louisville, Ky., and
Eugene, Ore. The protesters want the U.S. government to fully
disclose what they allege is complicity in human rights abuses
throughout Central America.

   "You know that book MacNamara wrote about Vietnam? We're waiting
for someone to write that book about Central America, about Cuba,
Haiti and Panama," said Steve Cagan, a Cleveland Heights
photographer and Latin American activist.

   Guatemala, a nation of about 10 million people roughly the size
of Tennessee, has been in civil war for 35 years, costing an
estimated 100,000 lives. Tens of thousands have been kidnapped and
tortured by government security forces in its battle to eliminate
rebel insurgents.

   Although Cleveland is 1,928 miles north of Guatemala City as the
crow flies, it has been an important focus of Central American
protest since the 1980 slayings of four local Catholic churchwomen
in El Salvador, said Paula A.

Miller.

   She is an activist with the Cleveland InterReligious Task Force
on Central America, which gathered about 30 protesters for the
Public Square demonstration yesterday.

   "It does us good. It gives us a little more energy in the
struggle for justice," said William H. Corrigan, a visiting
Cleveland Municipal Court judge and father-in-law of Mirna Carias
Corrigan. "In a small way, the protest gets the story out. Most
people don't have any idea about the Guatemalan-U.S. connection."

   The protesters called on Ohio Sens. Mike DeWine and John Glenn
to use their positions on the Senate Intelligence Committee to
uncover the truth.

   The committee "is currently conducting an inquiry into the whole
Guatemalan issue," said Bryan E. McCleary, Glenn's press secretary.
"The senator is obviously concerned about the allegations out of
Guatemala."

   These include the accusations of Ursuline nun Diana Ortiz, who
says she was kidnapped, raped and tortured while in Guatemala to
teach religion and reading to kindergartners. She says one of her
tormentors was an American.

   In March last year, President Clinton ordered the independent
Investigative Oversight Board to review U.S. intelligence on
right-wing violence in Guatemala since 1987. That report, McCleary
said, should be out within a month.

   "There are hundreds of thousands of people in Central America
who have gone through what my family went through," Carias Corrigan
said. "They are voiceless. We have to be their voice."

GRAPHIC: PHOTOS BY: CHUCK CROW / PLAIN DEALER PHOTOGRAPHER; PHOTO

1; Mirna Carias Corrigan recounts her family's suffering in
Guatemala.; PHOTO 2; Call for help in Guatemala; Protesters Mary
Sutphin and Vivian Balester of Cleveland Heights and Rosina Horvath
of Painesville wear sketched masks yesterday on Public Square of
men who allegedly raped and tortured Sister Dianna Ortiz in
Guatemala in 1989.

