<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Native Forest Network Protests Champion</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Native Forest Network Protests Champion</H3>
<PRE>Early this morning, activists from the Native Forest Network
(NFN) hung a banner reading "CHAMPION SPRAYS DEATH--NO
HERBICIDES" on Champion International's regional headquarters in
West Stewartstown, NH, where decisions regarding Champion's
Vermont forestlands are made.  The action was taken to protest
Champion's plans to spray toxic herbicides on Vermont forests in the
Northeast Kingdom and to call attention to hearings that will take
place in Island Pond, VT on June 26 and 27 at 9am at the Brighton
Town Hall.
        Champion International, the largest private landholder in
Vermont, intends to spray the herbicide Accord, whose primary
ingredient is glyphosate, a toxic chemical; and other ingredients that
are unknown because they are considered "trade secrets".  They
want to spray to convert their mixed forest lands into pine
plantations, killing off all of the hardwood and broad leaf species,
including the very fall foliage trees that have made Vermont famous.
        On June 26, Champion International and Monsanto Chemical
Company (the company producing the glyphosate herbicide to be
used) will testify to defend their herbicide plans.  On the 27th, the
Vermont Citizen's Forestry Roundtable will testify as to the reasons
why herbicide spraying is a bad idea for Vermont's forests.

information from:

Native Forest Network
Eastern North American Resource Center
POB 57
Burlington, VT  05402
(802)863-0571
(802)863-2532 (Fax)
email:  nfnena@igc.apc.org

