<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Greenpeace Chases Off Industrial Fishers</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Greenpeace Chases Off Industrial Fisher</H3>
<PRE>BERGEN, Norway, June 13, 1996 - Greenpeace vessel mv Sirius
has chased two Danish industrial fisheries vessels out of an
ecologically sensitive area near the Scottish coast, acting to
protect the North Sea from overfishing where environment
ministers have failed to act.

Today, environment and fisheries officials meet in Bergen,
Norway, to decide on a draft declaration for an "emergency"
meeting on North Sea fish stocks.
However, environment ministers have so far failed to challenge
the fisheries ministers on reducing fishing catches and
protecting the marine environment.
At last year's 4th International Conference on Protection of
the North Sea, environment ministers vowed to press fisheries
ministers to achieve a 16 point action plan to safeguard fish
stocks and marine life.  They have yet to meet this
commitment.

"The environment ministers are failing across the board," said
Greenpeace's Chris Rose from the mv Sirius.  "They are
surrendering the fate of North Sea fisheries and the marine
environment to the nationalistic infighting of the fisheries
ministers, which is a recipe for disaster."

Yesterday, the Sirius took the lead when its crew found and
chased away two industrial fishing vessels east of Scotland's
Firth of Forth.  Industrial fishing is virtually unregulated
and accounts for over half the weight of fish landed from the
North Sea.  The vessels found were searching for shoals of
sandeels, which are at the hub of the North Sea foodweb.  Once
fished, the sandeels are ground up into oil and meal for use
in margerine and cakes and animal feed.  Greenpeace has
repeatedly asked the Danish industrial fishers and their
representatives to stay out of areas likely to be sensitive to
industrial fishing.

A ban on industrial fishing in sensitive areas is one of the
first steps of an emergency recovery plan that must be adopted
by environment and fisheries if the North Sea fisheries crisis
is to turned around.

"We are defending key wildlife areas from industrial, or
`hoover', fishing -it's time for ministers to act, otherwise
the North Sea Conference will be a waste of time," said
MacGarvin.

At their meeting on Monday, EU fisheries ministers at the EU
Fisheries Council failed to reach agreement to cut herring
quotas despite scientific advice for a 50% cut in 1996 and
1997.  Fisheries ministers also took no action on industrial
fishing.

ends


For more information contact:  Malcolm MacGarvin in Bergen on
(mobile) ++47 94128531, or
Chris Rose (UK) Diederik Samsom (Holland), Peter Pueschel
(Germany)  on MV Sirius   +44 402 605187;  or
Jon Walter, Greenpeace Communications ++44 171 833 0600


** End of text from cdp:headlines **

