<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Program Features Firsthand Report of E. Timor Massacre</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Program Features Firsthand Report of E. Timor Massacre</H3>
<PRE>The City Sun, New York's Most Authoritative Black Alternative
Weekly June 5-June 11, 1996

On May 21, Park Slope Methodist Church hosted an evening devoted
to the tragic plight of East Timor. An island nation the size of
Massachusetts, East Timor lies several hundred miles north of
Australia. It has been illegally occupied by the notoriously
brutal Indonesian army for the past 20 years. By the late 1980s,
the human rights group Asia Watch, estimated that 200,000 Timorese
-- approximately one third of the population -- had been killed by
the Indonesian military.

The keynote speaker at the church, which was filled to capacity,
was Jose Ramos Horta, special representative of the National
Council of Maubere Resistance (CNRM), the umbrella organization of
groups supporting East Timorese independence. Also appearing were
Allan Nairn, investigative journalist with the Nation magazine,
and Amy Goodman, news director of WBAI and host of Pacifica
Radio's daily political program "Democracy Now."

After its longtime colonial ruler Portugal began decolonization in
1975, Ramos Horta left the island with a mandate to represent the
newly formed Democratic Republic of East Timor. Several days
later, the Indonesians, under the command of the military dictator
Suharto, invaded. Since then Ramos Horta has been tirelessly
arguing the case for his homeland at the United Nations and at
political forums around the world, explaining that East Timor
never posed a threat (other than what scholar Noam Chomsky calls
"the threat of a good example") to Indonesia. In fact, Indonesia,
the fourth most populous country in the world, has 200 times the
population of East Timor.

Architects of Invasion

Ramos Horta, a personable and articulate speaker, began on a mock
self-deprecating note, apologizing for his thick accent. It might
be due to a low IQ, he dead-panned, but it was difficult for him
to understand the complexities of the U.S. position on East Timor.
How is it that the U.S.  can intone piously about human rights
when it supports Suharto, a general who came to power in a 1965
coup that -- according to Amnesty International -- resulted in up
to a million deaths? Placing support for the invasion of East
Timor in the context of the "ignominious American retreat" from
Vietnam in 1975, Ramos Horta described how President Ford and
Secretary of State Kissinger visited Suharto shortly before the
invasion and gave the Indonesian dictator the green light to
invade Timor: Kissinger told reporters at the time that "the
United States understands Indonesia's position."

Ramos Horta recalled that as a youth he was a booster of the
United States, citing the resignation of Richard Nixon as proof
that democracy was all-powerful in the U.S. But, asked Ramos
Horta, how could be reconcile this perspective with the killing of
his sister by a U.S.-supplied Bronco jet? Or the U.S.-supplied
M-16s and Bell Helicopter that killed his brothers?

Ramos Horta stressed that the architects of the 1975 invasion
didn't foresee an active resistance 20 years later and that many
in the upper echelons of the Suharto regime are growing tired of
the ever increasing embarrassment East Timor causes them. He
credited international solidarity with being essential in making
certain that former Portuguese colonies have been especially
supportive: Mozambique, Sao Tome and Principe, Guinea-Bissau, Cape
Verde and Angola.

Though his talk was laced with understandable disgust at the
levels of "great  power" support Suharto has been able  to curry,
Ramos-Horta maintains a  tough optimism about future
possibilities. He rightly points to the example of Nelson Mandela
-- 10 years ago, few  expected him to become the president of
South Africa. Ramos-Horta insists that a day will come when the
jailed resistance leader Xanana Gusmao, East  Timor's Mandela,
will also be freed to  help forge a new future of peaceful
self-determination for his country. And he  pledged East Timor's
solidarity with West Papua and Aceh, other areas under the boot of
the Suharto gestapo.

 Protest Become A Bloodbath

   Amy Goodman and Allan Nairn were  in East Timor in November
1991 when a  peaceful protest march turned into a  bloodbath. A
large crowd had gathered outside a parish church after a memorial
mass for a young Timorese killed by  Indonesian soldiers several
weeks earlier. The young man had been seeking  sanctuary when the
soldiers stormed the  church; his crime was a resolve to contact a
U.N. delegation that was scheduled to visit the island. The
Indonesian  army had warned people throughout the East Timor that
anyone attempting to  speak to the visitors would be killed.

As the Timorese began marching,  they unfurled banners demanding
independence. When they reached the  walled-in cemetery where the
young man was buried, the crowd had grown to several thousand.
Suddenly those inside the burial grounds were trapped by a column
of soldiers. Goodman explained that when the troops began moving
toward the unarmed demonstrators, she and Nairn attempted to  head
off any violence by standing in  front of the Timorese. But the
soldiers marched by the two reporters and, without warning, began
shooting. In all, 270 men, women and children were killed that
day. Goodman observed that  the reason she and Nairn were spared
was probably because they came from the same country as the M-16s
the Indonesians were firing.

Allan Nairn spoke about political pressure in the U.S. since the
1991 massacre. The official Indonesian explanation for the
bloodletting showed a characteristic lack of concern for the loss
of Timorese lives. Try Sutrisno, who has  since become the
Indonesian vice president, opined that "such people must be shot,
and we will shoot them." General  Herman Mantiri, who was
subsequently promoted to regional commander for East Timor, said
the mass killing was "quite proper" since "they were opposing us,
demonstrating, even yelling  things against the government."

The State Department was less blase, didn't see a need to cut back
always profitable arms sales to Indonesia. On the other end of the
spectrum, a grassroots movement developed that became the East
Timor Action Network (ETAN). Joining forces with human rights and
church groups, including East Timor Religious Outreach, ETAN
mobilized popular support to change U.S. policy on East Timor.
Nairn noted that in 1992 these volunteer forces won a major battle
against the Pentagon and big corporate boosters of Indonesia like
GE and AT&T; that year Congress cut off military training aid to
Indonesia. Then in 1993, ETAN and other groups were able to block
a transfer of U.S. F-5 fighter planes to Indonesia.

Nairn called the United States "the external linchpin to the
apparatus of terror keeping down the Timorese" and cited a Jakarta
Post editorial that said the derailing of the F-5 deal "resounded
like [a] sonic boom" in Indonesia. President Clinton called
Indonesian repression in East Timor "unconscionable" when he was
campaigning against Bush. In office, however, Clinton has been
more interested in promoting trade deals favorable to U.S.-based
multinational than in helping the Timorese.

Clearly, Nairn said, the administration should not be allowed to
get away with describing General Suharto as "our kind of guy," as
a senior State Department official recently did. Nairn described
the sorts of torture and random terror that face any Timorese who
expresses unhappiness with the Indonesian military occupation. He
pointed out that in the U.S., demanding justice for the Timorese
does not involve such horrific risks.

Nairn said that an impending sale of F-16s to Indonesia "adds
insult to injury" since the Suharto regime wants 30 percent of the
cost of the fighter jets come from the purchase of Indonesian-made
parts. He asked the audience to tell their members of Congress to
oppose the F-16 deal and to push for a complete cut off on all
arms sales to Indonesia.

To find out what you can do, or for more, information contact
ETAN/NY at (718)788-6071 or fbp@igc.apc.org.
** End of text from cdp:reg.easttimor **

