<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Chicago Police Prepare for Convention</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Democratic Convention-Police Face Reputation</H3>
<PRE>Democrats: Shades of 68 in 96

Followup on the Atlanta story, here's the goods on Chicago.  the
same is true in San Diego, as well, where the republicans have
locked up every venue in town and are trying to make it impossible
for protesters to even gather. People are suing the Republican
National Committee to regain a gathering place directly across from
the convention, and the city to try to obtain marching permits.

        NEW YORK, June 9 (UPI) -- U.S. agencies are pressing British,
French and former Soviet-bloc spy networks for word of any
international plots that might jeopardize the Democratic Party's
National Convention in August, a published report said Sunday.
        The collection of foreign intelligence is just one way federal
and local authorities are attempting to avert terrorist attacks
at the convention, Newsweek magazine reported.
        To be safe, organizers of the convention site, the United
Center, are
erecting the stage away from sides of the building that might be
vulnerable to truck bombs. Another fear, Newsweek said, is that
terrorists could strike at less-protected targets elsewhere in
Chicago.        Demonstrators present a different challenge to
convention planners. There are so many activists planning
protests in the city that they're comparing notes on a World Wide
Web page.
        Police know that they're a volatile part of the mix and are
undergoing special training to prepare for the protesters. ``We
have a reputation as thugs in uniform,'' Sgt. Jim Devereaux told
one training class.
        Organizers are trying to strike a balance between vigilance
and overreaction to avoid any comparisons to the infamous 1968
convention, when Americans watched grainy footage of helmeted
cops beating anti-war demonstrators on Michigan Avenue.
        A training course for officers assigned to this August's
convention opens with ``Chicago 1968,'' a PBS documentary that
shows officers clubbing kids. However, there is also a list
hanging in the classroom with the names of 198 officers injured
in the melee.
        Most police officers say their side of the 1968 convention has
never been told, Newsweek said. Ill-trained and poorly equipped
officers had done their best to contain rioting and arson after
Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination in April of that year,
only to be slammed by city hall for going soft on angry blacks.
At the convention, many officers were still smarting from the
slight, Newsweek said.
        Skirmishes with protesters at the convention were as much
about class

warfare as about Vietnam: a predominantly blue-collar force heavy
with patronage hires and military veterans collided with children
of privilege, many of whom had ducked the draft. Some sprayed the
faces of policemen with oven cleaner.
        ``There was so much fear,'' recalled Officer Tom Baroini. ``I
thought, 'God, am I going to survive this?''
        The cops who work the 1996 convention aren't as likely to lose
their cool. Barely 7 percent of today's officers were on the job
in 1968. They're also more representative of Chicago itself: 25
percent black, 10 percent Hispanic and 18 percent female; 61
percent have attended college or earned degrees.
        The heaviest responsibility falls on 2,500 select members of
tactical

teams and special units. The department will reinforce its front
lines with 25 Immediate Reactionary Forces, flying squads of 10
officers each that can swoop down on disturbances. More reserves
can come from the rest of the 13,200-member police force.
        Police know the 15,000 reporters covering the convention will
be watching for the first raised police baton, but playing the
cops for patsies may be a mistake. At their training academy,
recruits eat lunch near a statue that commemorates seven officers
killed by an anarchist's bomb during the Haymarket Square riot
of 1886. Police want to reverse the image formed in 1968, but say
it isn't worth dying for.

Posted in pol-abuse@igc.apc.org
To subscribe, send this message: subscribe pol-abuse
To this address: majordomo@igc.apc.org

</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
