<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Court Victory for Mumia Demonstrators</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Court Victory for Mumia Demonstrators</H3>
<PRE>VERMONT COURT RULES THAT MUMIA SUPPORTERS CHARGED WITH UNLAWFUL TRESPASS CAN
USE THE NECESSITY DEFENSE TO JUSTIFY THEIR PROTEST ACTIONS.

     A Vermont District Court judge has ruled that six Mumia supporters
arrested last July at the National Governor's Association (NGA) Conference in
South Burlington, Vermont, can use the necessity defense at trial.  The six
activists are charged with Unlawful Trespass, a misdemeanor which carries a
maximum penalty of three months in prison and/or $500 fine.

      On July 30, 1995, police arrested the six individuals for crossing a
police-line blocking access to the Sheraton Hotel property where the nation's
governors were holding their annual meeting.  Among those attending the
conference was Governor Thomas Ridge of Pennsylvania.  The six defendants
were taking part in a protest of the then-scheduled execution of Mumia
Abu-Jamal, set for August 17.

       The six were arrested along with nine others during the July 30
actions.  Eight of those arrested, also charged with Unlawful Trespass, pled
guilty at arraignments the following day and were fined $75.00.  One other
protester was charged with Disorderly Conduct, but the charge was thrown out
for lack of probable cause.

     The six defendants are Roseanne Avakian of Cambridge, Mass., Monica Shay
of New York City, Andre Bratu, Renee Comesotti and Brad Waugh all of
Kingston, Ontario, and Caroline Hall of Battersea, Ontario.

     The recent court ruling stems from a motion filed by the State's
Attorneys seeking to prevent the protesters from using the necessity defense
at trial.  The State argued that the defendants could not meet the four
required elements of the necessity defense.

     To raise the necessity defense, the defendants must show 1) that there
was an emergency not of their own making, 2) that the emergency was so
imminent and compelling as to raise a reasonable expectation of harm, 3) that
there was no reasonable opportunity to avoid the harm without commiting the
criminal act, and 4) that the harm to be avoided outweighs the criminal
wrong.  Additionally, one must show that the defense has not been
"legislatively precluded" under the circumstances.

     Vermont law holds that the trial court should make a pre-trial ruling on
the admissibility of the necessity defense.  The applicable standard for
admissibility states that the court should permit the defense unless, taking
the facts in defendants' offer of proof as true, no reasonable juror could
find that the requirements of the defense were met.

     In response to the State's motion to exclude the defense, defendants'
attorneys presented an offer of proof (the evidence defendants claim they
will submit at trial to justify their actions) and legal arguments as to why
they should be permitted to use the necessity defense.  Following the State's
reply and oral arguments in the case, the court issued the recent decision
holding that "defendants' offer of proof meets the elements of the necessity
defense. . . . It will, of course, be for the jury to decide whether
defendants' actions were justified."

     In applying the four-part test, Vermont District Court Judge Dean
Pineles first held that "the impending state execution of a man whom
defendants believed to be wrongfully convicted constitutes an emergency."
 Likewise, the court held that such emergency was created through no fault of
the defendants.

      Second, the court noted that the "compelling and imminent" element
focuses on defendants' belief which must be reasonable.  The court then
stated that "a scheduled state execution is certainly sufficiently compelling
to raise a reasonable expectation of harm to Mr. Abu-Jamal."  The court went
on to note that:  "Although Mr. Abu-Jamal's counsel had filed a petition for
post-conviction relief seeking a new trial, Judge Sabo had thus far denied a
stay of execution which would allow full appeal of an adverse decision on the
motion.  Given the apparent certainty of the execution date, its proximity in
time, and the amount of time that one could expect to be required for a
protest to result in an executive decision halting the execution, the court
concludes that the emergency was sufficiently imminent to meet the second
element of the test."

     Next, the court considered whether there were any reasonable
alternatives to avoid the harm without doing the criminal act.  The court
first noted defendants' stated belief that "the criminal process in this case
was so infused with bias against Mr. Abu-Jamal as a result of his Black
activist affiliations that he could not receive fair treatment in the
courts," thus concluding that "their sole recourse was to stage a protest at
the National Governor's Conference which would gain national media
attention."  While the court rejected the protesters' claim that they also
sought to influence Judge Sabo's legal decision with respect to granting a
stay of execution or new trial, since "political activism and public outrage
may not reasonably be expected to influence judicial decision-making," the
court accepted that "under certain circumstances, however, protest activities
might reasonably be expected to influence executive decision-making."  The
court then noted that "although many other protest efforts were underway,
defendants claim that the only way they could influence Governor Ridge to
change his avowedly firm stance in favor of proceeding with the execution was
to gain his attention in the harsh light of a nation forum.  In the very
limited timespan leading up the planned execution date, that opportunity
presented itself during the National Governor's Conference in Burlington,
Vermont."  Finally, as the court recognized, the defendants claimed in their
offer of proof that repeated attempts were made to speak with Governor Ridge
outside the Sheraton to voice their concerns, which attempts included
shouting for him and telephoning him at the Sheraton.  "It was only after
these efforts failed, so they claim, that they resorted to trespass in order
to gain the Governor's direct attention and to attract a national media
spotlight."  The court thus concluded that taking their offer of proof as
true, "defendants could reasonably believe that they had no other opportunity
in which to influence Governor Ridge to intervene."

     Third, the Court found that defendants offer of proof also alleged a
"sufficient nexus to satisfy the causation component."  The court stated
"because Governor Ridge was present at the conference and had the executive
authority to intervene, and because the conference had attracted national
media attention, defendants could reasonably believe that their protest
activities outside the Sheraton would result in a stay of execution."

     Finally, the court addressed the fourth element of the defense which
concerns the balance of harms.  The court simply stated that "the planned
execution is sufficiently serious to outweigh a nonviolent criminal trespass
onto the Sheraton property."

     Accordingly, the court found that defendants' offer of proof met each of
the elements of necessity.  The court then went on to address the State's
final argument that the defense is not available here because it has been
"legislatively precluded."  The court rejected such argument, finding that
"because Governor Ridge had continuing discretion to grant clemency or a stay
of execution, there existed no deliberate legislative choice as to the
propriety of enforcing Mr. Abu-Jamal's death sentence on August 17, 1995."

     A pre-trial status conference has been set for July 30, at which time
jury draw and a trial date will probably be scheduled.  A trial is not
expected until at least September.

     "We are very pleased with the court's decision, and we consider this a
major victory in the case," said Michael Cassidy, one the attorneys
representing the six protesters.  "Our clients are very excited and they see
this not only as an opportunity to vindicate themselves, but as a chance to
raise awareness on a number of issues, including Mumia's case and the death
penalty."

     As set forth in the offer of proof, Mumia's attorney, Leonard Weinglass,
has agreed to testify on their behalf.  Ward Churchill has also agreed to
testify about the history of FBI COINTELPRO against the Black Panthers and
other organizations.  Howard Zinn has agreed to testify as well about the
history of social movements for peace and justice.


FOR MORE INFORMATION, you can contact
Michael Cassidy at Cassidym3@aol.com</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
