<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Thousand Protest at Gdansk</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Thousand Protest at Gdansk</H3>
<PRE>      By Robert Bogdanski 

WARSAW, June 21 (Reuter) - Thousands of impassioned workers protested outside 
government headquarters on Friday against the bankruptcy of the debt-ridden 
Gdansk shipyard, where Solidarity launched its fight against communism. 

``Get your red paws off the shipyard,'' workers shouted in protest at the 
ex-communist Privatisation Minister Wieslaw Kaczmarek's bankruptcy plan for 
the yard, as union chiefs submitted a petition demanding talks with the government. 

``We vow here, the whole of Polish Solidarity, that we will not surrender the 
shipyard,'' the union's national leader Marian Krzaklewski told the crowd, which 
later marched to the nearby privatisation ministry and parliament. 

Police stood by with two water cannon in a sidestreet as workers flung red paint 
at the city-centre government building and burned an effigy of Kaczmarek, but 
there were no clashes. 

Apart from workers bussed in by Solidarity from the Baltic coast yard, the crowd 
included miners from the troubled state coal and arms industries and even 
underpaid doctors. 

But witnesses estimated turnout was well below the 10,000 predicted by the union. 

Kaczmarek argues that bankruptcy is the only way to start a turnaround of the 
state-controlled yard, burdened with debts of more than 300 million zlotys 
($115 million) and loss-generating contracts, so that foreign firms are willing 
to invest in it. 

He has used the government's 60 percent shareholding to make the management file 
for bankruptcy, which it did on Thursday, declaring that liabilities exceeded the 
value of its assets by about 100 million zlotys. 

Passions run high partly because Solidarity accuses his co-ruling ex-communist 
Democratic Left Alliance (SLD) of seeking revenge against the yard where 
electrician Lech Walesa formed the Soviet bloc's first free union 16 years ago. 

The yard was a bastion of Solidarity's fight that won the downfall of communism 
in 1989, allowing Walesa to become Poland's first freely-elected president. 

But it has failed to thrive in the market reforms it helped to bring about and on 
which Kaczmarek bases his arguments. 

Aleksander Kwasniewski, an ex-communist who beat Walesa in presidential elections 
last year, appealed on Friday for calm. 

``I don't like the way that we are talking about such painful subjects in political 
terms,'' he told public radio. 

The union, seeking talks with the government on help for the shipbuilding sector 
and saving jobs, has announced pickets and protests around the country but so far 
ruled out strikes. 

Kaczmarek said on Thursday the future of the Gdansk yard and its 7,200 workers 
hinged on whether a receiver struck a debt-rescheduling deal with creditors, 
renegotiated unprofitable contracts and found finance for new projects. 

``We do not want the shipyard to cease to exist,'' he said. 

To keep the yard as it stands the government would have to spend millions of 
dollars covering its debts and on modernisation, he added. 

The yard's management has tried to hang on by creating a new company leasing 60 
percent of the yard's assets, which will finish five or six ships out of the 18 
outstanding contracts. 

But shipyard president Ryszard Goluch said the new company would need a 
government-guaranteed loan of 50 million zlotys. 

Controversy over the yard has focused tension within the ruling coalition of 
Kaczmarek's ex-communists and a Peasant party, some members of which back an opposition 
motion to dismiss him, which parliament will vote on next week. 

Poland has five shipyards but only one, in Szczecin, has undergone successful 
restructuring and become profitable. </PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
