<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: IRS Sells War Protesters' Property</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>IRS Sells War Protesters' Property</H3>
<PRE>HARTFORD, Maine (Reuter) - The Internal Revenue Service fell short Wednesday 
in an attempt to auction the land and home of a Maine couple who have refused to 
pay income tax to protest military spending. 

IRS agents sold off a blueberry field and woodlot belonging to Elizabeth Gravalos 
and Arthur Harvey, but received no bids for the couple's central Maine house in an 
auction crowded with reporters and nearly two dozen war-tax protesters. 

An IRS official declined to say if they would attempt another auction, but the 
couple, who operate an organic blueberry farm with their children, told reporters 
they expected the IRS would move again next month. 

Gravalos and Harvey, who do pay state and local taxes, admit that neither of them 
has filed a federal income tax return in the past two decades. The IRS claims they 
owe $60,000 in taxes and fines. 

Harvey said he stopped paying federal income tax in the 1950s to protest nuclear 
weapons research. Gravalos said she stopped paying federal tax in 1972 to protest 
the Vietnam War. The couple married and moved to Maine 10 years ago. 

Gravalos told a reporter last week she doubted the sagging two-story wood framed 
house would fetch much money. The house lacks indoor plumbing and electricity. The 
30-acre field sold Wednesday for $13,000, while the small woodlot was bought for 
$10,000.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
