<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Protests at Borders Books Stores</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Protests at Borders Books Stores</H3>
<PRE>Fellow Workers,

Below is the text (draft -- we anticipate polishing it up a bit as we go
on) members of the Boston GMB will begin distributing outside the
BordersU downtown Boston store Monday, June 17th.  This store opened
about 2 months ago, and is just a couple blocks from Barnes & Noble,
BordersU chief competition.  We will be leafletting/picketing the store
intermittently as our resources permit, and will also distribute
leaflets at a talk Tuesday night by AFL-CIO secretary-treasurer Richard
Trumka.  If FW Fried has not been re-instated by that time, we will be
picketing talks next Wednesday (6/26) and Thursday (6/27) evening (5:30)
by authors of books on slavery and gays coming out in the workplace,
respectively.  There are Wobblies in many, if not most, of the cit ies
where Borders has its stores.  If there is no Borders in your area,
Borders also owns Waldenbooks and BrentanoUs and Planet Music stores
(though we think it a better idea to keep the main focus on Borders,
where possible, as there are about 900 Walden book stores -- far too
many for the IWW to cover.  There are only about 115 Borders stores).

We'd love to hear what you're doing

       Jon Bekken, for the Boston Area GMB


BORDERS UNFAIR

Worker fired for organizing union

On June 15 the General Manager of the Borders Bookshop in Center City
Philadelphia fired Miriam Fried, a member of the IWW organizing
comittee, claiming she had accepted a customer's check without an
address.  Miriam had never been written up since her employment began;
her firing is a transparent attempt to break the IWW's organizing drive
at Borders in the wake of a narrow defeat in a March 27th NLRB election.
Miriam Fried was one of the most visible and spirited union supporters,
and has continued her efforts to build a union for Borders workers.

Financial analysts point to BordersU well-trained, customer-oriented
staff as the chain's chief asset. But they are paid only $6.50 an hour
and have no say in the conditions of their work. Borders workers across
the country have approached the IWW and oth er unions to organize for
better conditions. Borders management responded with captive meetings,
threats, a notorious union-busting attorney, and now by firing union
supporters. But while Borders' highly skilled staff toil for $13,000 a
year, in 1994 Borders' three top executives received compensation
packages ranging from $247,420 to $861,639, and held stock worth more
than $22 million (excluding long-term stock options). Borders could
easily afford to pay its workers a living wage, but it would rather
illegally fire those workers brave enough to stand up for their rights.

Borders workers need your help. Please let Borders management know you
won't patronize their stores until they re-instate Miriam Fried and
respect workers' right to organize. Call Borders at 1-800-644-7733, or
write them at 311 Maynard St., Ann Arbor MI 4 8104.

Boston Area General Membership Branch
Industrial Workers of the World
P.O. Box 391724, Cambridge MA 02139
iww@igc.apc.org or phillyiww@iww.org


PETITION TO BORDERS MANAGEMENT

As customers of Borders Books, we expect Borders to respect the rights
of its workers. We condemn the Philadelphia Borders for firing Miriam
Fried for union organizing and demand that she be re-instated
immediately.

Signature:          Name (print):           City:



>From bhelms@iww.org  Sat Jun 15 19:11:26 1996
Subject: IWW militant fired at Philly Borders

Dear Sister and Fellow Workers,

This afternoon the General Manager of the Borders Bookshop in Center
City Philadelphia, David Stewart, fired a member of the IWW organizing
comittee, Miriam Fried.  This took place after a short discussion about
her supposedly having failed to enforce a c ompany policy that requires
a costomer's check to have an address on it before it can be accepted at
a cash register.  Miriam had never been written up since her employment
began, and is known for being an excellent bookseller.  During the
campaign at tha t store, which suffered a big setback in a narrow defeat
at NLRB election on March 27th, Miriam Fried was one of the most visible
and spirited union firebrands.

A sister worker of the truest colors has been vindictively fired on the
lamest of ruses, obviously because of her union affiliation.  This is
the time for a response from all of us.  I urge everyone in this union
or friendly to it to apply pressure at th e Borders store in your area,
of any and every nature you see fit, so that this spiteful action can be
clearly read by the Borders Group, inc. as having cost them money, time,
aggravation, and public prestige.  We must make them eat crow.  Don't
feel tha t you need to touch base with anyone here before doing it.
Just go ahead and DO IT.

I will keep all of you posted.  I thank you in advance for your support.

                                        In Solidarity,

                                        Bob Helms
                                        Philadelphia IWW


