<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: China Detains MU Greenpeace Outside Shanghai</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>China Detains MU Greenpeace Outside Shanghai</H3>
<PRE>HONG KONG (Reuter) - The Chinese military behaved in a more civilized manner 
than the French, Greenpeace activists said Sunday after being forced out out of 
Chinese waters. 

Although their anti-nuclear protest ship MV Greenpeace was kept from reaching Shanghai, 
the environmentalists claimed success in carrying their message to China and the world. 

``We can say that the Chinese military and naval authorities behaved in a much more 
civilized and clever way than the French did last year in Mururoa,'' said Xavier Pastor, 
senior campaigner aboard the MV Greenpeace. 

``They were... professional, they were polite, and at the same time they forced us to 
obey the Chinese law,'' he told a news conference in Hong Kong. 

The MV Greenpeace arrived in Hong Kong earlier Sunday after a face-off with Chinese 
authorities off Shanghai last Wednesday. 

Despite warnings from China, the Greenpeace sailed into Chinese waters to protest against 
China's continued nuclear testing and to urge Beijing to commit to a total test ban. 

Last September the MV Greenpeace was seized and its crew was arrested by French commandos 
in international waters off France's nuclear test site of Mururoa atoll in French Polynesia. 

This time the ship, with 32 crew and passengers, anchored at the mouth of the Yangtze river 
off Shanghai and requested a pilot to take it into port. 

The Chinese sent out six vessels, including two gunboats, and 70 uniformed officials boarded 
the protest ship, cutting communications and demanding journalists' film. 

After four hours of negotiations, the Chinese side agreed to take Greenpeace anti-nuclear 
material and the activists agreed to turn their vessel around and leave Chinese waters. 

China, which carried out its latest nuclear explosion earlier this month, has pledged to 
observe a moratorium from September -- after conducting one more test. 

It has also said it would sign the test ban only if the accord promised to reconsider a 
prohibition on ``peaceful nuclear explosions'' after 10 years, a stance Greenpeace says 
could fatally weaken the treaty.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
