<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Continued Rioting in E. Timor</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Continued Rioting in East Timor</H3>
<PRE>Hundreds of youths rioted in Baucau, 115 km east of Dili, for the
second day yesterday, but the Indonesian military denied church
claims that two people had been killed.

A church source and a regional government official said there were
two dead and at least three injured.  But East Timor military
commander Colonel Mahidin Simbolon denied there were any
fatalities.  Col Simbolon said that two military members had been
"stabbed" by youths.  The commander said that 13 youths had been
arrested in Baucau.

The unrest erupted after graffiti was painted on a statue of the
Virgin Mary in a nearby village, the local sources said.

"Hundreds of youths have been on the streets since yesterday. It's
like Palestine here.  The situation is still bad now, and may get
worse later on", a Baucau church source said.  The source claimed
that two people, possibly from the military, had been killed and
at least three residents wounded.  The toll was coonfirmed by an
official from the regional government in Baucau.

The graffiti was found on a statue in Bagilia, a village south of
Baucau. Roman Catholic youths burned the local mosque on Monday
and the riots then spread to the streets of Baucau, the church
source said.  Hundreds of security forces, including a special
"mobile" brigade, have been on the streets since Monday trying to
contain the unrest, another church source said.

However Colonel Simbolon denied the riots were incited by
religious motives.  He said it was "just youths fighting and
rioting" adding that the situation in Baucau was "secure".  "No
mosque was burned, there was no desecration on the Virgin Mary
statue", he said.  He said that 13 youths had been detained by
Baucau police and that several youths were injured, but declined
to give figures.

"They were rioting, throwing stones at the police station. Of
course the security  forces acted", Col Simbolon said.

Baucau was rocked by two days of disturbances in April when
hundreds of youths rioted after the alleged killing of a youth by
security forces.  No injuries were reported.
** End of text from cdp:reg.easttimor **

