<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Smokey Bear Joins Forest Demo</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Smokey Bear Joins Forest Demonstration</H3>
<PRE>
                        Smokey Appeals Shawnee NF Sale

      On June 3, 1996, Monday, at 10:00a.m., environmentalists from a
number of  organizations (RACE, Heartwood, Student Environmental
Center-SIU, Native Forest Network) held a demonstration at the
Vienna Ranger Office in Vienna, Il.. Smokey Bear joined the activists
as he submitted his appeal of the Forest Service, OA6(Opportunity
Area Six), Decision to log 3,270 acreas, (including clearcutting) across
10,000 acreas at Bell Smith Springs in the Shawnee National Forest.
Bell Smith Springs is a National Natural Landmark.
        Smokey stated that the Public is overwhelmingly opposed to
this sale (177 comments in opposition,  4 comments in favor) and the
fact that wildlife will loose their homes and forage. Smokey stated
the FS is losing $459,000.00 (Four hundred and fifty nine thousand
dollars) of taxpayers money on the sale.
        Citizens are encouraged to look at the facts of the current
situation in the Shawnee National Forest!!
        Smokey has asked people to Beware of Biostitutes: Biologists
who prostitute themselves for industry or bureacracy.

Bogus:"pine trees need to be cleared to allow regeneration of
hardwood forest"

Bona fide: All it takes is a walk out among the pines to realize that
there is already a well-established understory of young hardwoods
in these pine stands. Any time our Shawnee Hills are left to
themselves they will, in time, grow hardwoods. Natural processes are
working around the clock--at no cost to the taxpayers-- to restore
hardwoods to these hills. Cutting the pines, burning the needles,
compacting the soil with heavy equipment, eroding the soil by
exposure to the elements, and drastically altering the micro-climate
of our pine stands by opening them up will severly degrade the
existing hardwoods and set back the natural processes by many
years.

Bogus:"the Forest Service calls pine removal 'ecological restoration'"

Bona fide: Just a few years ago the Forest Service called this project a
"below-cost pine timber sale." What they now call "shelterwood
harvesting" used to be called CLEAR CUTTING. Since the taxpaying
public will no longer stand for below-cost clear cutting on public
land, the Forest Service simply re-packaged these timber sales as
"ecological restoration" using the "shelterwood" technique, hoping the
public won't figure the scam out until after the trees are gone, the
money is spent, and Bell Smith Springs is trashed.

Bogus: "On their way to death, the trees likely would become
diseased and infected with insects..."

Bona fide:  Disease and infestation are natural processes in a forest.
Forest soil is made from dead trees. Birds and other animals eat
insects:  they are all links in the food chain, strands in the web of life.
It is ironic that a government agency whose main priority is cutting
trees would suddenly profess such a concern about trees dying
naturally.

BOGUS: "The first two parcels (of pine trees) have been awarded to
Westvaco lumber company in Wickliffe, KY., to be converted into
wood pulp for paper."

Bona Fide: While this statement is true, the reality behind it is bogus:
In the state of West Virginia alone Westvaco owns over 300,000
acres of timber land---more than the entire Shawnee National Forest!
They own a similar amount of land in Southern Illinois and Kentucky.
But Westvaco won't be content cutting their own land or producing
recycled paper as long as taxpayers are willing to subsidize them
with trees cut from public land.

Smokey says "Remember only you can save Bell Smith Springs!"

Call the Forest Service and let them know your feelings in regards to
this issue at 1-800-MY-WOODS. The phone call is obviously free and
direct to the FS supervisors office in Harrisburg, IL. Call your
congressperson! Call your Senators!! Do Something!!! Don't let this
DIRTY DEAL go down! This forest belongs to you just as much as to
any bureaucrat or multi-national corporation!
-------
