<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Faculty Protests Minority Hiring Record at U Tennessee</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>U of Tennessee Faculty Protests Minority Hiring Record</H3>
<PRE>JOHNNY ROYSTER
Daily Beacon Staff Writer
---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
-
Alleged administrative failure to promote minorities to leadership positions
recently initiated staff protests.

A protest letter that carried 39 faculty and staff signatures was sent to
Vice Chancellor of Academic Affairs John Peters, objecting to hiring
practices. The letter was sent following the appointment of Charles Glisson
as interim dean of the College of Social Work.

Glisson, a professor in social work, was appointed by Peters to fill the
vacancy of Eunice Shatz, the retiring dean. Jeanette Jennings, an associate
dean of social work, had expressed interest in the position.

Other news sources have recently reported that Jennings resigned her
position in reaction to this decision. "This is only a rumor," Chancellor
Bill Snyder said. "She has not resigned."

"I don't know what has been done at the university in the past regarding
persons in similar circumstances," Jennings said. She confirmed she had not
resigned.

"I am requesting a leave of absence," she said.

Commenting on the protest letter, Peters said, "I met with a representative
sample of those people and we had a constructive discussion about the issue=
.
I fully understand and appreciate their view.

" I know they don't understand my view, but we walked away with a commitmen=
t
that we must work hard to diversify the campus in terms of students,
faculty, and particularly administration. We are going to work very hard to
continue that work."

"I question the decision-making process, and this is not to take anything
away from the person appointed," Faculty Senate President Dhyana Ziegler
said. " but clearly Dr. Jennings was a person with the experience and she
was already in place. I think she deserved the opportunity."

"There has been a revolving door of African-American faculty and
administrators who have left this institution due to perceived unfair
treatment," Ziegler continued. "Historically, women and African-Americans
have had a difficult time breaking the glass ceiling. Had Dr. Jennings been
appointed to the position of acting dean, it would have raised the ceiling
somewhat."

The position being filled is temporary but will eventually become a
permanent position. There were appointments of interim deans in three
colleges: the Colleges of Social Work, Arts and Sciences, and Education,
Snyder said.

"We would normally begin a search process, but because of the budget, we
decided to go with an acting dean that would be appointed from within. Dr.
Peters got suggestions by consulting with people in each of the colleges an=
d
he consulted with me. I supported his choices," Snyder said.

When there is a vacancy, the university takes applications from all over th=
e
campus.

"We took nominations and interviewed candidates," Peters said. "There were
15 faculty members interested in serving."

"These are such hard choices because we have some really good people.
Jeanette Jennings is one of our very finest scholarly faculty administrator=
s
on campus. We are pleased she is staying with us," Peters said.

The College of Social Work is almost like three colleges -- with a college
at Knoxville, one at Nashville and one at Memphis. There are associate dean=
s
at each site. "To have success in an interim year they must work=20
together. I
wanted to preserve that continuity," Peters said.

The interim deans will serve for the next year. "We are aiming to restart
the search in the fall, about September, and we'll have interviews with the
candidates in the spring," he said. The permanent dean could be hired by Ma=
y
and take office in July 1997. Those filling the temporary interim positions
are given no preference toward being chosen permanent dean.

"It's a level playing field," Peters said.

Since 1989-90 through 1995, 30 African-American faculty have left UT. Durin=
g
that period, 23 African-American faculty have been hired, which leaves a ne=
t
loss of 7, according to Peters.

"This is not uncommon at research universities because African-American
professors are mobile, and we are not producing enough African-American
Ph.D.s fast enough to fulfill the demands that all universities have to
diversify their faculties," Peters said.

"We presently list 44 tenured and tenured-track African-American professors
out of a total of approximately 612. This is not including the College of
Agriculture or the Space Institute at Tullahoma. Among these 44, there are
15 full professors, 17 associate professors and 12 assistant professors,"
Peters said.

People leave for various reasons, he said. "We do exit interviews and have
found that many of those who left weren't satisfied and didn't feel
comfortable in the main community," he said. "Some didn't think they fit in
and some weren't satisfied with their situation. A few weren't given tenure
based upon their research and service records. Many of those who left have
gone on to very good jobs at very good institutions.

"The mark of a good university is the quality of its people. When we lose
any of our outstanding faculty, it's a mark of a good institution that
you'll lose them to good universities," Peters said.

Chancellor Snyder has established the Office of Diversity Resources and
Educational Services (DRES) to provide campus leadership in developing
programs that focus on understanding diversity and he has established
directives toward obtaining this goal.

He cited the institution's vision and mission statement, "that all people
shall be treated with respect, understanding, caring, and fairness ... and
we are committed to the development of individuals and society through
cultivation and enrichment of the human mind and spirit.

"We need more models of success -- more programs that promote diversity on
campus," Snyder said. He offered examples such as the innovative program
developed by Dhyana Ziegler and Camille Hazeur, which uses video to help
individuals explore their own attitudes regarding race, gender, class and
other forms of diversity.

The Office of Minority Student Affairs also has provided programming and
support for minority students on campus as well as the Minority Engineering
Program, which celebrated in the fall of 1993 a 20-year anniversary of
successfully recruiting and graduating African-American engineering
students.

University figures for the 1993-94 school year show that women comprised 49
percent of student enrollment. African-American enrollment was about 5
percent of the student body and almost 3.5 percent of the faculty.

