<H3>Standoff Over Demonstration Site at Republican Convention</H3>
<PRE>>From Copley News Service, June 4, 1996:

A behind-the-scenes campaign is being waged by
the Republican National Committee to relocate the proposed
demonstration site at this summer's GOP convention and put greater
distance between the party and its protesters.

Officials in the San Diego Police Department have steadfastly resisted
the effort, however, creating a stand-off that has forced the city to
continually postpone the issuance of demonstration applications,
originally scheduled to begin in April. The convention opens Aug. 12.

Federal courts have held that protesters must be allowed within sight
and earshot of convention delegates. In 1984, a federal judge used
that standard to make substantial revisions in plans for a
protest site at the GOP convention in Dallas.

The choice -- which is literally across the street from the convention
center -- was tentatively approved by the U.S. Secret Service and
appeared on track.

"This just smells of small-town, back-room politics. San Diego is too
large a community with too many diverse voices to be treated with this
lack of respect," ACLU managing attorney Jordan C. Budd said.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
