<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Demonstrating Youths and Police Clash in E. Timor</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Demonstrating Youths and Police Clash in E. Timor</H3>
<PRE>JAKARTA, June 10 (Reuter) - At least one person was believed killed and six 
people injured in clashes between East Timorese youths and police in Baucau town 
in the troubled Indonesian territory, church sources and residents said on Monday. 

Police and military officers in East Timor were not available for comment. 

``We heard that one person was killed and six other people were injured during the 
clash when the youths took to the streets to protest against an insult to the 
Virgin Mary,'' a pastor told Reuters from Baucau, about 80 km (50 miles) east of 
the East Timor capital of Dili. 

Residents in Baucau also confirmed that clashes between police and youths had occurred. 

The pastor said the youths were angered by reports that Moslems living in the town 
in the predominantly Roman Catholic region had torn a picture of the Virgin Mary on 
Sunday. 

``Thousands of youths took to the streets today (Monday) and they clashed with police 
and pelted them with stones. Police later opened fire. The protest took place in the 
morning and the city is still very tense now,'' he said. 

He said security officers were conducting house-to-house searches and residents were 
afraid to leave their homes. 

In April, hundreds of youths marched through the town in protest against the killing 
of a youth by Indonesian soldiers. 

East Timorese have staged numerous protests against recent arrivals from mainly Moslem 
parts of Indonesia, most of them traders from South Sulawesi. 

Indonesian troops invaded the former Portuguese colony of East Timor in 1975 and 
Jakarta integrated it into Indonesia the following year in a move not recognised by 
the United Nations. </PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
