<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Clinton Protested in San Francisco</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Clinton Protested in San Francisco</H3>
<PRE>Smaller-than-Expected Protest Against Clinton

SAN FRANCISCO (Reuter) - About 200 people noisily protested President Clinton's opposition 
to same-sex marriage during his visit to San Francisco Sunday but predicted large-scale 
demonstrations did not materialize. 

San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown urged Clinton to stay away from the city last week to 
avoid protests by gay activists angered by his decision to sign a Republican-sponsored 
bill before Congress that would allow a state not to recognize same-sex marriages. 

But Clinton rejected the advice and pushed ahead with the visit during a campaign tour 
of three Western states. In fact, no large-scale demonstrations materialized. 

Only about 200 placard-waving, chanting demonstrators gathered near Democratic Sen. Dianne 
Feinstein's house in a wealthy San Francisco suburb where Clinton attended a 
$50,000-per-plate fundraiser Sunday evening. 

Police kept the demonstrators a block away from Feinstein's house and five large postal 
trucks blocked their view of arriving guests, so they could not see the president enter 
the house. 

Most of the demonstrators were angry at Clinton's opposition to same-sex marriage. But 
others were protesting a wide range of issues, ranging from the administration's Cuba 
policy to health care to defense spending. 

``We want a divorce, Bill'' and ``Gay rights now!'', the demonstrators chanted. A woman 
wearing ordinary clothes but with a wedding veil passed out wedding rice for demonstrators 
to throw. A man held up a sign with the word ``traitor.'' 

``We feel like we should have the right to marry,'' said Bob Cathey, 37, standing with his 
partner Joe Kugler. 

The demonstrators left long before the fundraiser was over. The protest was peaceful and 
there were no arrests. 

Clinton did not comment on the same-sex marriage controversy during a speech at the Presidio, 
a former military base being converted to a national park. 

Tom Ammiano, a gay member of San Francisco's governing Board of Supervisors, said last week 
he would attend the Presidio event only if Clinton was willing to sit down with gay and 
lesbian leaders to discuss same-sex marriage. 

Before Clinton arrived Sunday, about 300 people went to the Metropolitan Community Church 
in the Castro District, the heart of the city's gay community, for a service billed as a 
chance to ``worship, pray, sing and demonstrate against President Clinton.'' 

``We gather in this sanctuary where possibly more gay marriages have been celebrated openly, 
publicly and proudly than in any other church in the country and we call upon President 
Clinton to recognize and affirm our marriages,'' said the Rev. Jim Mitulski, pastor of the 
church. 

Clinton won overwhelming support from gays in the 1992 election and many gays in San 
Francisco supported him until now. 

Clinton said Friday he did not think any president had been more sensitive to the 
``fundamental human concerns or the legitimate interests of gay Americans.'' 

Mitulski says at least one gay marriage ceremony a week is performed at the Metropolitan 
Community Church, whose congregation is 95 percent homosexual. 

Gay marriages are not legally recognized in any state, although San Francisco recently 
introduced a civil ceremony for gay couples with ``marriage-like vows'' but without legal 
standing. The bill before Congress was sparked by a court case in Hawaii that could legalize 
homosexual marriage there. </PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
