<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Million Bulgarians Protest "Western" Reforms</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Million Bulgarians Protest "Western" Reforms</H3>
<PRE>By Galina Sabeva 

SOFIA, June 7 (Reuter) - Nearly a million Bulgarians registered their discontent 
with the socialist government's Western-backed reforms on Friday, holding brief 
strikes and wearing symbolic protest ribbons, trade union officials said. 

``Over 640,000 workers went on effective or symbolic strikes all over the 
country at the beginning of the day and by 1500 (1200 GMT) the figure had risen 
to 923,000,'' said Elina Nacheva of the Confederation of Independent Trade Unions. 

``More and more workers are joining the protests,'' she told Reuters. 

The workers, most of whom went on strike for only about an hour, want higher 
salaries to compensate for price and tax increases, officials said. They also 
want the cabinet to resign. 

Zhan Videnov's government is currently closing scores of factories and several 
banks in a campaign to win the confidence of foreign lenders. 

The International Monetary Fund and World Bank have promised badly needed loans 
if Bulgaria perseveres with post-communism reforms. 

The strikers included miners complaining about non-payment of wages and doctors 
worried about health spending cuts. 

About 150 taxi-drivers angry about fuel price hikes staged a protest rally in 
central Sofia and said they would continue on a daily basis until the government 
resigned. 

``It it time to end the rule of the red mafia,'' said Ivan Topalov, a private 
taxi driver, referring to the government of ex-communists. 

Another taxi driver Kircho Atanasov said, ``We are fighting for our bread and 
for our right to work.'' 

Support for the strikes, which are expected to continue in coming weeks, has come 
from diverse groups, including students, pensioners and monarchists who want King 
Simeon II, currently visiting Bulgaria after 50 years of exile, to reclaim his throne. 

Simeon, a Madrid businessman, had a rapturous welcome from Bulgarians using his 
visit to express discontent with their current rulers. 

Opposition parties have submitted a motion of no-confidence in Videnov's cabinet 
that will be debated by parliament early next week. 

The cabinet, in power for 17 months, should survive the no-confidence vote due 
to its absolute parliamentary majority. 

However Videnov is expected to make cabinet changes at a special meeting of his 
Socialist Party at the weekend in a sign of the party's growing unease about the 
economic crisis.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
