<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Tiananmen Anniversary Clash in Hong Kong</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Tiananmen Anniversary Clash in Hong Kong</H3>
<PRE>HONG KONG (Reuter) - Democracy activists scuffled with police in Hong Kong 
Sunday as thousands of demonstrators marked the seventh anniversary of
China's crackdown on the student-led Tiananmen Square protests in 1989. 

Some of the protesters rammed barricades outside the New China News Agency,
 China's defacto embassy in the British colony, in an attempt to place a
black coffin at the entrance. 

The casket, bearing the words ``The people's heroes will be remembered forever,'' 
swayed precariously overhead as demonstrators scuffled with police. One man was 
arrested and the coffin confiscated. 

With less than 400 days before Hong Kong returns to Chinese sovereignty, the 
more than 3,000 protesters vowed to continue their protests until China
admitted it was wrong to crush the demonstrations in Beijing's Tiananmen Square 
and punished the culprits. 

On the frontline were democracy activists who pledged to go to jail rather 
than compromise their demands. ``We will go on until our demands are met,'' said
pro-democracy legislator and activist Tsang Kin-shing. 

After marching through the central city streets, the demonstrators gathered outside 
the New China News Agency, holding aloft big black and white banners, a symbol of 
mourning. 

Bearing placards saying ``Never forget June 4'' and ``Fight for democracy and freedom 
of speech,'' they then joined hands and sang patriotic songs. 

A shrine of incense, photos and People's Liberation Army helmets, stood on the 
pavement outside as a stark reminder of those who died -- civilians and soldiers. 

Several demonstrators waved Taiwan national flags. ``I'm proud of Taiwan,'' said a 
local truck driver. ``They've got democracy.'' 

Exiled mainland dissident Han Dongfang, jailed by China for his role in the Tiananmen 
Square protests, warned of violent clashes after 1997. ``We probably won't be allowed 
to do this.'' 

Hong Kong returns to Chinese sovereignty at midnight on June 30, 1997. 

``We will continue to protest, and if that means breaking the law after 1997, then 
we are prepared to go to prison for it,'' said Albert Ho, a legislator and
spokesman for the Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in 
China. 

Beijing has branded the Alliance subversive for its role in helping many dissidents 
involved in the mainland's democracy movement escape overseas. 

The Alliance was particularly active in securing the safe passage out of China of some 
of the protesters involved in the Tiananmen Square demonstrations. 

The crushing of student-led demonstrations in Tiananmen Square on June 4, 1989 dealt a 
heavy blow to Hong Kong's morale as it prepared for its reversion to Chinese sovereignty. 

About a million people marched on the New China News Agency in the days after the 
bloody crackdown. 

While China has agreed that Hong Kong can retain its capitalist lifestyle for another 
50 years after the handover, it has stipulated that the territory must adhere to laws,
still to be drafted, on sedition and treason. 

Thousands of people are expected to attend a candlelit vigil to be held in Hong Kong 
late Tuesday, June 4. </PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
