<H3>Houston: "No to Toxic Exxon!"</H3>
<PRE>-------------------------
Via Workers World News Service
Reprinted from the May 30, 1996
issue of Workers World newspaper
-------------------------

By Gloria Rubac
Houston

Colorful signs, a demonstration, and informational
leafleting caused a minor disturbance among Exxon officials
and their security operation here in Houston in mid-May.

Protesters descended on Exxon's corporate headquarters to
demand the oil giant cancel plans to pollute the land and
water by constructing a copper-sulfide mine in Wisconsin.
Houston acti vists denounced the company's attempt to win a
permit to build the mine in Crandon, Wis., adjacent to Native
land.

If built and put into operation, the mine would generate
44 million tons of waste that would be highly toxic in
contact with air or water. Exxon plans to dump the poisons
into a waste pond 90 feet deep and covering 355 acres.

The toxic waste would destroy the work of Native people on
Mole Lake Reservation growing wild rice. Mole Lake is next
to the proposed Crandon mine site. Exxon's plans call for
dumping 1,000 gallons of waste a minute into the nearby Wolf
River.

Protesters represented the National People's Campaign, the
Gray Panthers, the Committee in Solidarity with the People
of Mexico, and the Women's International League for Peace and
Freedom.

                         - END -

