<H3>Boston Peltier Demo</H3>
<PRE>-------------------------
Via Workers World News Service
Reprinted from the May 23, 1996
issue of Workers World newspaper
-------------------------

"FREE LEONARD PELTIER NOW!"

More than 100 demonstrators picketed the Boston Federal
Courthouse during rush hour May 10 to demand freedom for
Native political prisoner Leonard Peltier. Peltier, the
victim of an FBI frame-up, has been imprisoned for more than
20 years. Demonstrators also demanded justice for Mumia Abu-
Jamal. The action was sponsored by the National People's
Campaign and United American Indians of New England. The
anti-war organization Food Not Bombs brought a 15-foot-tall
papier-mache image of Peltier that attracted much attention
from passersby. Moonanum James, Sachem of UAINE, called on
"all justice-loving people from the four directions to rise
up and demand the immediate release of Peltier. We must
organize others, and we must take to the streets with our
demand for justice!"

--Mahtowin

                         - END -

