<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Mumia Supporters Descend on Justice Dept.</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Mumia Supporters Descend on Justice Dept.</H3>
<PRE>By Malcolm Cummins
Washington

Five hundred people marched and rallied in sweltering heat
here May 20 in the ongoing struggle to free political
prisoner Mumia Abu-Jamal. Abu-Jamal has been on Pennsylvania's
death row since 1982. A former Black Panther, a radical journalist
and an outspoken foe of racism and police brutality, he was
framed in the 1981 killing of a Philadelphia police officer.
The death penalty is one of the most powerful weapons of
oppression in the arsenal of U.S. capitalism. Death row is
populated entirely by people of color and poor whites.

KNOCKING ON JUSTICE'S DOOR

The bold demonstrators marched right up to the doors of
the Justice Department to deliver hundreds of thousands of
letters demanding that Attorney General Janet Reno open a
civil-rights investigation into Abu-Jamal's case. People all over the
world signed the letters. The campaign was initiated by the New
York Coalition to Free Mumia Abu-Jamal. Most of the letters
were signed by people in the United States. But 4,000 came from
France, where there is strong public interest in the case.

When marchers got to the Justice Department, however,
Clinton administration officials from the department refused
to accept the letters--even though they had earlier agreed
to do so. Forty-five minutes of negotiations followed. Serving
notice on the officials that they'd better not try to
retaliate against the demonstrators, hundreds chanted, "One
arrest, all arrest" throughout this period. Finally, the letters were
accepted. The demonstrators also demanded the Justice Department
officials provide an official receipt acknowledging that they had
accepted the letters. They got the receipt. The protesters were
determined not to let the Clinton administration escape
responsibility for Abu-Jamal's case. They chanted: "Clinton, Reno,
you can't hide. We charge you with genocide!"

REPORT FROM FRANCE

The protesters also made a clear link between the Abu-
Jamal case and all attacks on poor and working people with
the chant "stop the war on the poor--free Mumia!" And they
denounced National Public Radio for canceling Abu-Jamal's
contract to do a series of radio commentaries on the death penalty.
The commentaries were canceled after the Fraternal Order of
Police pressured NPR. Abu-Jamal is currently suing NPR for
canceling his contract.

Speakers at rallies before and after the march pointed out
the injustice of Abu-Jamal's continued imprisonment on death
row. Larry Holmes of Workers World Party and the National
People's Campaign had just returned from France, where he
went on a speaking tour about the Mumia Abu-Jamal case and
the fight against the death penalty and racism in the United
States. Holmes reported: "Progressive people, communists and
revolutionaries in France are very interested in the case of
Mumia Au-Jamal.

"That's not only because of their opposition to the racist
death penalty and their desire to link the struggle against
racism in France, primarily directed against Arab and
African immigrants, with the struggle against racism in the
United States. It's also because Mumia is a revolutionary.
"French revolutionaries see his case as an opportunity to
spread revolutionary ideas and struggle. "It's very appropriate that
we are targeting Janet Reno and the Justice Department at this
demonstration today," Holmes continued. "Our enemies are not
only the authorities in Pennsylvania, the cops, Judge Sabo and the
big ruling-class families in that state. We must also target the
federal government. "Only several weeks ago, President Clinton
signed a so-called anti-terrorist bill, which if enacted will severely
limit the opportunity of condemned prisoners to appeal their
cases. This will mean two to three executions per week of
poor and oppressed people in the very near future."

Holmes had traveled to France at the invitation of the
Erich Honecker Defense Committees. This group, with
affiliates all over France, was organized by communists as a
way to show solidarity with the former officials of the
German Democratic Republic who face persecution by the
German government in the aftermath of the capitalist
takeover of eastern Germany.

The Honecker committee has been looking for ways to extend
its work to the case of other political prisoners, like Abu-
Jamal. Holmes spoke in Paris, and in Rennes, Lyon, Toulon,
Lille and Avion.

NATIVE, CUBAN, PUERTO RICAN SOLIDARITY

Also speaking at the Washington rally was the Rev. Lucius
Walker--who with two others is in the 90th day of a "Fast
for Life" to protest the U.S. blockade of Cuba. He called
Abu-Jamal a "champion of justice." Walker noted that "in Cuba,
one of the central concerns is justice for Mumia Abu-Jamal."
Pam Africa of the International Concerned Family and
Friends of Mumia Abu-Jamal and Safiya Bukhari of the New
York Coalition to Free Mumia Abu-Jamal. Ron Lessard of the
Leonard Peltier Defense Committee read a solidarity statement
from Native freedom fighter Peltier, who is also on death row
because of a government frame-up. The statement read in part, "I
reiterate my stand in solidarity between the African and Native
American communities."

Several speakers commented on the striking injustices of
Mumia Abu-Jamal's case. Lola Short of Trinidad called him "a
symbol of the injustices that happen to all poor, Black and
under-privileged people."

Speaking for the many young people who marched, Sarah
Wolf--a 15-year-old high school student from Takoma Park,
Md.--said she came to protest "the injustice against Mumia
Abu- Jamal and all political prisoners."

Carlos Rovira of Workers World Party and the National
People's Campaign extended solidarity on behalf of the
Puerto Rican people.

The demonstration was called by the New York Coalition to
Free Mumia Abu-Jamal and the International Concerned Family
and Friends of Mumia.

                         - END -

