<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Seattle Protests Sweden Over East Timor</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Seattle Portests Sweden Over East Timor</H3>
<PRE>May 24, 1995

The East Timor Action Network/Seattle today targeted a nation with one of
the most squeaky clean reputations in the world for the respect of human
rights when it picketed outside the Swedish consulate in downtown Seattle.
ETAN accused the Swedish government of hypocrisy in reversing its own
stated position not to supply Indonesia with arms in light of the grave
human rights situation in Indonesian occupied East Timor.

Sweden has circumvented its own policy of not permitting arms sales to
Indonesia by terming an upcoming sale of Bofors cannons to the Indonesian
navy a "follow-up delivery" to a sale made in 1979.

About a dozen protesters, ranging from secondary school students to
seniors, carried signs like "Export Lutefisk not Cannons" and chanted
slogans such as "We won't go for/ Sweden selling Bofors".  They also
passed out leaflets to confused passers by, some of whom wanted to know
why ETAN was demonstrating there and what the relevance was to the United
States.

"When a model national like Sweden begins to follow world-wide trends in
subordinating human rights concerns to profit for the arms industry, it
sets a bad example for less enlightened nations like the United States,"
explained Frank Zucker, an ETAN member. "Right now, the Clinton
administration is itching to sell Indonesia F-16's on concessional terms.
Everyone is looking around saying,'if we don't sell em...'  Someone has to
stick to principles, not the principal," he continued.

When the demonstration began at 12 noon, a representative from ETAN went
up to the one-room consulate on the 10th floor of the Financial Building.
He informed a befuddled consular assistant that the group was protesting
outside the building, since ETAN had yet received no response from the
consul to a letter dated 12 May.

The assistant regarded as "not cool" the proposal that the group come up
for a discussion after the demonstration.  So "uncool" was the idea that
10 minutes later the demonstrators were threatened by the building's
private security with criminal trespass should they dare enter the
building "as protesters" or block the entry.

Yet as the assistant had agreed to contact the consul, Mr. Jahn R.
Hedberg, and to convey his comments to the demonstrators, ETAN decided to
send two more representatives up for the answer.  They were met on the
10th floor by security and once again threatened with arrest.   Back on
the street security conveyed that the assistant had been advised by the
consul to give no comment.

"We consider it a smashing success that a polite group of demonstrators
including junior high students and seniors could so intimidate a consulate
of a European nation that they would not only refuse discussion or comment
but threaten us with arrest," said Mariza Cabral, also of ETAN.

The demo, perhaps the first time the Swedish government has ever been
targeted in the United States, follows in a series of world-wide protests
against the Bofors deal, since Sweden quietly permitted it last April.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------
                           PRESS RELEASE

                           May 13, 1996

                            No embargo


             SWEDEN TO SELL NAVAL CANNONS TO INDONESIA:

     EAST TIMOR ACTION NETWORK/SEATTLE PROTESTS SWEDISH REVERSAL


The East Timor Action Network/Seattle today sent an open letter to the
Swedish consulate in Seattle demanding an explanation for Sweden's
sudden reversal of its policy of prohibiting arms exports to Indonesia on
account of continuing human rights abuses in occupied East Timor.
Sweden intends to permit the export of Bofor naval cannons to the
Indonesian navy.

Before Sweden's 1994 elections, the now-ruling Social Democratic Party
resolved that "an arms embargo against Indonesia is called for, as long as
East Timor's right to self-determination is not guaranteed, and serious
violations of human rights continue... The Swedish Government should,
because of the serious and widespread human rights violations in East
Timor and Indonesia, not issue any permits for new arms exports to
Indonesia."

In the letter ETAN/Seattle said, "we find it truly unfortunate that
Sweden, long known as a model among nations for upholding human rights in
deeds as well as words, now appears to have compromised its principled
position."

ETAN/Seattle emphasized that "the human rights situation in East Timor is
appalling and continues to deteriorate.  It is well-documented that foreign
arms are used regularly in East Timor not only to suppress resistance to
the illegal Indonesian occupation but to intimidate and kill civilians."

Sweden's hypocrisy has been met with severe criticism both within Sweden
and world-wide.  Tom Hyland of the East Timor Ireland Solidarity
Campaign, for example, accused the Swedish Government of "behaving
like turnips."

ETAN/Seattle will sponsor a demonstration at the Swedish consulate at
1215 4th in Seattle on Friday, May 24th, at 12:00 pm in the event that
the consulate fails to satisfactorily respond to ETAN's letter.  A copy of
the letter is enclosed.

Contact:

Charles E. Albertson, (206) 322-1645

----

12 May 1996

Consulate of Sweden
-----------------
1215 4th, Suite 1019
Seattle, WA 98161
(206) 622-5640
Fax: (206) 622-1756


Dear Mr. Jahn R. Hedberg:

We were shocked when we heard of the sudden reversal of Sweden's policy
not to permit arms exports to Indonesia because of ongoing violations of
human rights in occupied East Timor.  As we understand, for more than ten
years Sweden has supplied no arms to Indonesia for this reason.

The Social Democratic Party before the 1994 elections resolved that "an
arms embargo against Indonesia is called for, as long as East Timor's
right to self-determination is not guaranteed, and serious violations of
human rights continue... The Swedish Government should, because of the
serious and widespread human rights violations in East Timor and
Indonesia, not issue any permits for new arms exports to Indonesia."

Now Sweden intends to permit the export of Bofor naval cannons to the
Indonesian navy.  We find it truly unfortunate that Sweden, long known as
a model among nations for upholding human rights in deeds as well as words,
now appears to have compromised its principled position.

The human rights situation in East Timor is appalling and continues to
deteriorate.  It is well-documented that foreign arms are used regularly
in East Timor not only to suppress resistance to the illegal Indonesian
occupation but to intimidate and kill civilians.

We urge Sweden not to permit this or any other arms export to Indonesia as
long as East Timor is denied the right to self-determination which has been
repeatedly upheld by the UN Security Council and General Assembly.

We ask that you provide an explanation for this change in policy and request
a personal meeting.

Awaiting your response,

F.Z.


for East Timor Action Network (ETAN)/Seattle

contact: Charles E. Albertson, tel: (206) 322-1645


** End of text from cdp:reg.easttimor **

