<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: French Police Demonstrate in Paris</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>French Police Demonstrate in Paris</H3>
<PRE>    By Irwin Arieff 

    PARIS, May 29 (Reuter) - Thousands of French police officers marched in 
Paris for the first time in five years on Wednesday in a plain-clothes 
protest against feared job losses, equipment shortages and stress they blame 
for a record suicide rate. 

    ``The national police force is slowly dying off. We cannot accept this,'' 
Jean-Louis Arajol of the Independent Federation of Police Unions told the 
crowd estimated at 30,000 by organisers but at just 7,000 by Paris police 
headquarters. 

    Arajol urged the government quickly to begin recruiting new officers. 

    But in a new sign of tight budgets ahead, President Jacques Chirac reminded 
cabinet members they must make tough decisions to remain within the ceilings 
set for public spending. 

    ``If we do not get satisfaction today, we will pursue our battle and we 
will only grow in numbers,'' Arajol told Reuters. 

    Protest organisers had predicted 10,000 people would turn out for the protest 
march, the first by French police since 1991, when some officers clashed with 
non-union riot police. 

    The demonstration was initially banned because Interior Minister Jean-Louis 
Debre thought it threatened public order. 

    The authorities relented after organisers announced the march had been upgraded 
to a general demonstration by public sector workers against threatened cuts in 
public services. 

    Some teacher, mass transit and other public sector unions joined the police 
protest on Wednesday, reflecting a new wave of union unrest following last 
December's crippling strikes driven by fears of welfare and public service cuts. 

    Police officers gathering for the protest blamed their woes partly on a lack 
of equipment like radios, vehicles and bullet-proof vests as well as on fears of 
job lay-offs. 

    They also expressed concern about young people growing up in urban areas 
plagued by high unemployment, drugs and violent crime and who no longer respected 
the police. 

    Forty-seven French police officers have committed suicide since January 1 this 
year and nearly 500 have been put on light duties without service weapons in Paris 
alone due to growing job stress, union officials say. 

    Numerous officers complained the government was hiring new paramilitary gendarmes 
while holding back growth in the national police force, leading to an increasingly 
militarised force. 

    ``If people are laid off right and left, that's no good,'' said one officer, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. 

    ``Replacing us with gendarmes allows the government to inflate the police jobs 
figures, but gendarmes can't do all that a civilian police force can do. We live 
side by side with the citizens, while they live in barracks.'' 

    Gendarmes also are paid better and barred from joining unions, they noted. 

    The last time police officers marched through the streets of Paris in 1991, some 
clashed with non-union riot police brought in to enforce order during the protest. 

    But there was no violence at this year's march. 

    ``We are peaceful, We haven't come for that,'' said one officer. </PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
