<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Anti-US Protest in South Korea</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Anti-US Protest in South Korea</H3>
<PRE>SEOUL, May 26 (Reuter) - More than 3,000 South Korean students staged 
an anti-American protest in Seoul on Sunday seeking an apology from the 
United States for what they call Washinton's complicity in the 1980 Kwangju 
massacre. 

    Witnesses said riot police fired tear gas canisters to disperse 
demontrators and more than 100 activist students were taken to nearby police 
stations. 

    There were no reports of injuries. 

    ``The United States has never made any apology even after the fact was 
disclosed that it approved the military suppression of Kwangju civilians,'' 
a protesting student was quoted by witnesses as saying. 

    Students accused Washington of allowing South Korean troops to move into 
Kwangju prior to the massacre in which official figures said about 200 people died. 

    In May 1980, South Korean soldiers clubbed and bayoneted to death hundreds 
of citizens demanding an end to military rule and protesting against martial law 
imposed by the military elite. 

    Two former generals Chun Doo Hwan and Roh Tae-woo, who took power in turn 
after the Kwangju suppression, were now on trial on charges of mutiny and homicide. 
</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
