<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Open Fire on Protesters in Bangui</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Open Fire on Protesters in Bangui</H3>
<PRE>By Bernard Edinger 

    PARIS, May 23 (Reuter) - French troops opened fire as protesters tried 
to march on the French embassy in the Central African Republic capital 
Bangui on Thursday to denounce Paris's military intervention in its former 
colony, French radio said. 

    The French Defence Ministry had no immediate confirmation of the Radio 
France Internationale report, which said that French troops had opened fire 
to intimidate the protesters and that rebel African troops had later 
returned fire. 

    Witnesses said the shots had broken up the protest by thousands of 
people shouting anti-French slogans. 

    One demonstrator said it did not appear the troops were aiming at protesters, 
and there were no reports of casualties. Protests were also reported in the northern districts of Bangui. 

    The latest confrontation came as French officials offered conflicting 
explanations for expanding the troops' mission to include propping up 
democratically elected President Ange-Felix Patasse, under threat from a 
six-day-old army mutiny over pay. 

    Defence accords between Paris and Bangui provide for French aid only 
in case of outside attack. 

    Cooperation Minister Jacques Godfrain told French television that the 
troops, whose mission was initially confined simply to protecting expatriates, 
were assuming a broader role because intervention had been requested by 
humanitarian groups and was justified as lives were in danger. 

    Later, the Foreign Ministry said that French intervention followed a 
request from the Central African authorities. 

    ``These authorities are the legitimate authorities, chosen in democratic 
elections and to whom France could not refuse its assistance to help end the 
crisis and restore civil order,'' a ministry statement said. 

    ``We continue to believe that negotiations must continue and that they 
can end the crisis. We are working in this direction,'' the ministry said. 

    Defending sensitive government installations such as the state radio 
station would ``assure that the pursuit of negotiations and the restoration 
of order would not be compromised,'' it said. 

    French forces used a helicopter gunship on Wednesday to repel a rebel 
attack on the radio station, located near the presidential palace. 

    Two French paratroopers had been shot and wounded during the clash, 
the army said. Two other French soldiers were wounded earlier this week as 
they helped lead hundreds of foreigners from their central Bangui homes to 
safety in more secure areas. 

    Only hours before the attack, the rebels had called French soldiers 
``old friends.'' 

    Mutineers do not want to fight against the French army, a rebel spokesman 
said after the confrontation. ``We cannot fight against France,'' Sergeant 
Cyriaque Souke told France 2 television from Bangui. 

    France has urgently flown in armoured vehicles and other heavy equipment 
aboard cargo planes chartered from Ukraine to back up its troops in Bangui, 
military sources said on Thursday. 

    Giant Antonov-22 planes brought in the vehicles on Wednesday to bolster 
French efforts to back Patasse, the sources said. 

    The French military, which has long complained of a lack of heavy-lift 
aircraft, chartered the same Ukrainian planes to move equipment during French 
military intervention in Rwanda in 1994. 

    Officers in Paris said that, with new troops arriving from France and 
from French garrisons in Africa, there were now about 1,700 French soldiers 
in Bangui and a further 600 in the provincial town of Bouar. 

    Paris, which at first said that only those foreigners who wanted to leave 
need go, later acknowledged that most of the 2,000 people under the protection 
of French forces in secure areas around Bangui now wanted to be evacuated and 
return home. 

    A first batch of 138 French nationals arrived early on Wednesday in Paris 
from Bangui, describing scenes of looting and destruction. A second military 
flight carrying some 170 French aid workers arrived in Paris early on Thursday, 
and a third aircraft carrying 310 more was due later in the day. 

    An estimated 2,400 to 2,500 French people live in the former French colony. 

</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
