<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Chernobyl Protest Arrests in the Ukraine</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Chernobyl Protest Arrests in the Ukraine</H3>
<PRE>APRIL 26, 1996 UPDATE! Non-Violent Direct Action at Time Zero

Two simultaneous actions were carried out last night by FOR MOTHER EARTH at
1:23 am near the Chernobyl Zone in Ukraine:

        1) Detyatki check point (Zone entrance on the road from Kiev to
Chernobyl NPP); and
        2) Slavutich, on the railroad track 1.5 km to the west, in the
direction of Chernobyl.

SLAVUTICH, UKRAINE - 26 April, 12:00 noon Kiev time (5:00 am EST 26 April)
According to the Internews Vikna TV crew that was present, this morning
eleven members of the international environmental group FOR MOTHER
EARTH including one freelance journalist shooting video footage were
arrested by local police after the group spent the night chained to the
railroad tracks, blocking the way to Chernobyl from the city of Slavutich.
(Slavutich was specially built following the 1986 accident to replace the
abandoned city of Pripyat that housed Chernobyl plant workers).

        According to a telephone conversation at 10:50 am with Krista Van
Velzen of the Netherlands, spokeswoman and an organizer of the action,
speaking from the Slavutich police headquarters (tel. from Kiev:
8-279-22- 422), at 4:15 am police told the activists they would be
arrested.  The police asked Sergey Lapko of Ukraine, a journalist from
"Small World" to film the scene on video, but then took his camera,
filmed it themselves, and confiscated the materials.  At 4:45 police cut
the locks the activists had used to secure themselves to the tracks.  At 
5:00 am the first morning train carrying Chernobyl plant workers passed 
the site. The activists were then taken to the police station for 
questioning.  The video materials and camera have been returned, 
apparently unharmed.  The police at 11:30 said the group had just been 
released and are driving back to Kiev in their own vehicles.  Those 
arrested include citizens of Belgium, Finland, Germany, the Netherlands, 
the UK, and Ukraine.

        Covering the action were TV camera crews from Reuters, World
Television News, and Internews (based in Arcata, CA, tel: (707) 826-2030,
Kiev studio: +380 44 446 2076 attn: Sergey Shvets), and AP (contact Angela
Charlton in Kiev, tel/fax: +380-44-229-6425).

        The action took place at a point around 1.5 km down the tracks
from Slavutich, where high-voltage electrical lines, presumably from the
still- operating plant, cross over the railway.  The activists were dressed
in radiation suits, and are holding signs with the names of the most
dangerous nuclear reactors in various countries throughout the world.

        A simultaneous action was carried out at the Detyatki checkpoint
into the Zone.  There 40 activists from the same group blockaded the main
road entrance to Chernobyl, wearing white anti-radiation suits and
protective masks, and carrying banners and signs with the names of 83
evacuated villages and regions of Ukraine.  They conducted a "die-in"
right at the moment of Time Zero, 1:23 am, when ten years ago reactor No.
4 exploded. There were no arrests at this action.  At sunrise the Walkers
planted a tree, and reminded the world that, "The only nuclear reactor we
need is the Sun!".  This action was covered by Reuters TV
(+380-44-229-6167, fax: 229- 3045).

        Among the walkers was a ten-year-old boy, Maksim Kuzin of
Mogilev, a contaminated area in Belarus.  Maksim wore a gas mask
expressing his protest at having to grow up under the shadow of Chernobyl.
Other participants included Oleg, a man who at the time of the accident
lived in Pripyat, 2 km from the plant, and Natasha Zamorskaya from
Zhitomir, Ukraine who joined the Walk because her father, a Chernobyl-
aftermath construction worker in 1986, died of cancer three years ago.

        The total of 50+ members of FOR MOTHER EARTH taking part in
these actions are from Belarus, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, Germany, the
Netherlands, Romania, Slovakia, the UK, Ukraine, and the USA.  They are
finishing their 200 km Walk for a Nuclear-Free Future.

        Additional actions were carried out: by twenty FOR MOTHER EARTH
activists at the Doel NPP near Antwerp Belgium, also at time zero; and a
joint action by FME and Greenpeace activists in Slovakia at the Bohunice
NPP.  Look for news updates on this action on the net!

        FOR MOTHER EARTH demands the immediate closure of the
Chernobyl NPP and the global phase-out of nuclear energy.  FME also
demands the start of urgent programs for implementing energy efficiency
and the use of renewable energy sources (solar, wind, biomass).  For
Mother Earth believes we must stop nuclear pollution at its source - the
mining of uranium.

        UPCOMING EVENTS IN KIEV: On April 27 at 13.00 FME Walkers will
join a locally organized "human chain", that is to stretch from the
Chernobyl Museum to the Ministry of Energy building.  Look for reports!
        At 16.00 a press conference will be held at the House of Culture
"Korolyova", where Walkers will join with local organizers, Greenpeace,
the Heinrich Boell Foundation (Germany), and the Folkcenter (Denmark) in
presenting a specially organized exhibit on alternative energy that is
part of an evening of "networking", dancing, and music performed by various
CIS bands that are calling themselves "Musicians for Alternative Energy
Sources".

        In Amsterdam on April 27 an alternative energy bike tour jointly
organized by Omslag and FME will culminate with a national "No More
Chernobyls" demonstration.  The cyclists began pushing their peddles from
five different locations in the Netherlands where nuclear facilities are
threating the future of our fragile planet.  Look for the news!


        !!!!!!! FOR A NUCLEAR-FREE WORLD !!!!!!

        ***************************************
        *FOR MOTHER EARTH INTERNATIONAL OFFICE*
        *   Gewad 15, 9000 GENT - BELGIUM     *
        * Tel +32-9-2334924 Fax +32-9-2337302 *
        *                                     *
        ************** E-MAIL *****************
        *   int@fme.knooppunt.be (home) or    *
        *   office@motherearth.knooppunt.be   *
        ***************************************



