<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Australian Miners Disrupt Shareholder Meeting</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Australian Miners Disrupt Shareholder Meeting</H3>
<PRE>   By Garry West 

MELBOURNE, May 22 (Reuter) - Australian mining giant CRA Ltd  came under 
attack for its industrial relations record at a fiery  annual meeting 
on Wednesday but kept alive a A$1.1 billion  (US$872 million) zinc project 
opposed by native landowners. 

CRA, which is in a dual-listed company structure with  Britain's RTZ Corp 
Plc, delayed the start of the meeting  by one hour after scores of striking 
CRA coal miners blocked the  entrance to the meeting hall during a noisy protest. 

Hundreds of shareholders were abused by angry miners when they eventually 
entered the building through a barricade of  police officers. 

One shareholder collapsed during the commotion and was taken to hospital. 
CRA chairman John Uhrig said the man was in serious  condition. 

"I am distressed that such a thing could happen at a CRA shareholders meeting," 
Uhrig told reporters after the meeting,  referring to the disruption. 

Union officials holding proxies for shareholders clashed  with Uhrig during 
the meeting after criticising the company's largely successful move to shift 
employees to individual staff contracts from union wage awards. 

"Shareholders would have got an understanding about how passionate employees 
are in their hatred for this company," mining union official John Maitland 
told the meeting. 

He said CRA had breached workers' rights to collective bargaining by preventing 
them joining unions, a claim the company has denied. 

But Uhrig said the protest was by a small number of people and that most CRA 
workers had elected to take up staff contracts. 

"I believe that every time we get an experience like we had today, our position 
would be strengthened," he said. 

CRA believes workers on individual contracts are more productive. 

CRA also said it had delayed until June 30 a decision on whether to stop 
investment in the Century zinc project in north Queensland, which it has 
considered scaling back because of delays in gaining approval from local 
Aboriginal landowners. 

It has already spent A$200 million on the project, which would be one of the 
largest zinc mines in the world. Work at the site, however, has all but stopped. 

CRA said it would need to reach agreement with landowners by mid-June and gain 
secure legal title to the site by September 30, otherwise it could not commit 
itself to such a big project. 

"We are not suggesting we will walk away, never to return,"  Uhrig said. 

But he said there was an encouraging development last week when a meeting of 
native people gave general but qualified support to the project. 

CRA also needed confirmation from base metals group Pasminco Ltd that its 
Budel smelter in the Netherlands still intended to buy half of Century's 
annual output, now that CRA  could no longer meet a deadline to begin 
supplies by June 1998. 

Budel faces closure if it cannot meet this deadline to stop  producing the 
polluting waste material, jarosite, by moving to treatment of lower-iron 
zinc concentrate such as that mined at Century. 

Pasminco said on Wednesday it would ask the Dutch government to extend this 
deadline. 

RTZ-CRA, the world's largest mining group, announced in March a 26 percent 
jump in net profit to A$1.95 billion for calendar 1995. 

</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
