<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Greenpeace Previews China Protest</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Greenpeace Previews China Protest</H3>
<PRE>
      By Mark Bendeich 

SYDNEY, Australia (Reuter) - Environment group Greenpeace, resuming its 
anti-nuclear campaign after last year's dramatic confrontation with France, 
said Monday it would take a ``very soft'' approach in protesting against 
Chinese nuclear tests. 

Speaking aboard protest ship MV Greenpeace in Sydney, leading activists 
said they were sailing to Shanghai to meet local authorities and to hold 
an ``open day'' aboard the vessel to enable the crew to explain their 
cause to local Chinese. 

``This is just a very soft way of bringing this campaign message further 
forward and we do not expect or are planning confrontation,'' said activist 
Ken Ballard, a veteran of the group's attempt to disrupt French tests in the 
South Pacific. 

China conducted two nuclear tests last year -- in May and August -- provoking 
a storm of protest from Japan and other countries.     China is ready to 
resume testing after finishing a tunnel to accommodate a blast at the Lop Nor 
underground test site in far west Xinjiang region, a Japanese newspaper 
reported Saturday. Beijing has also begun building another tunnel, suggesting 
it could conduct at least two rounds of testing, the Tokyo Shimbun said, 
quoting unnamed Japanese government sources. 

Ballard, the MV Greenpeace's first mate, described as ``traumatic'' the 
experience of being arrested by French commandos while aboard the MV 
Greenpeace in international waters off the testing site of Mururoa atoll 
in French Polynesia last September. 

But asked if Greenpeace planned to stage another protest similar to last 
year's anti-nuclear demonstration in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, nuclear 
campaigner Jean McSorley said: ``It's not our intention to do anything 
like that at this time.'' 

``At the moment we are trying to keep things low key and as non-confrontational 
as possible,'' McSorley told a news conference on board the ship, a former 
ocean-going tug. 

China deported six Greenpeace protesters in 1995 after they unfurled a yellow 
banner demanding China halt its nuclear tests. 

The MV Greenpeace, seized by the French during the Pacific Ocean protests, 
is due to reach China around June 6, via Manila. Its voyage began last week 
from New Zealand and comes amid reports that another Chinese nuclear test 
is imminent. 

Greenpeace has requested to dock in Shanghai but has yet to receive a 
response, the activists said. ``We are not going to force our way in at 
all ... ,'' McSorley said. 

The daily said it was believed China decided to accelerate its nuclear 
testing program because Beijing had pledged to help conclude negotiations 
on the proposed comprehensive test ban treaty by June 30. 


</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
