<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Foods Not Bombs Protest</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/notiban.gif" ALT="Notices" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Thursday, May 16, Food Not Bombs Protest, S.F.</H3><PRE>
Posted: Keith McHenry <kmchenry@Catch22.COM>
ROBERT NORSE KAHN FACES 60 DAYS IN JAIL FOR SHARING FREE FOOD WITH THE HUNGRY
Protest Thursday, May 16, 1996 at 2:00 pm on the steps of the Court House
at 850 Bryant Street in San Francisco.
Robert was arrested in October of 1993 for sharing free food with a
hungry woman at Civic Center Plaza in San Francisco.  He went to trial in
February of 1994 and was convicted.  Judge Barclay refused to allow
evidence that would have shown that Robert did not violate a court order
because Food Not Bombs did have "all permits."   The permit process had
been abolished in 1990.  No permits have been available since.  Many
people feel that the law is clear.  No permits are required but because
Food Not Bombs has effectively defended the rights poor people in San
Francisco its protests are considered illegal by the government and
downtown business.

Robert appealed his conviction but the traditionally corrupt San
Francisco courts failed to uphold his appeal.  On May 16, 1996 Robert and
his supporters hope that the Judge will agree to the DA's proposal to
give him "credit for time served."  Robert Nores Kahn probably has spent
more than 60 days all total in jail for his support of the civil rights
of the homeless.

According to several published statements Amnesty International may adopt
Robert as a prisoner of conscience if the judge fails to agree to the
DA's proposal.

MULTIMEDIA FORUM AGAINST POLICE REPRESSION IN SAN FRANCISCO
On Friday, May 31, 1996 at 6pm a coalition of community groups including
A.Y.U.D.A., Food Not Bombs, Copwatch, Revolution Books, Action for Police
Accountability and the Coalition of the Homeless Streetwatch project will
be holding a public forum at New College, 777 Valencia Street in San
Francisco.  Police repression has increased under the new mayor and
community activists are organizing to end the attacks.  The arrests of
the homeless has almost doubled, pepper spray deaths, now called in
custody death syndrome continue and police sweeps of poor neighborhoods
are on the increase.  Video, music, photos, reports and free food will be
available.  Residence of San Francisco are seeing first hand the
repression of the police state and are starting to fight back.  This
summer the San Francisco Police will be using military helicopters and
other high-tech equipment to force the downtown business interests will
on local people.  On Wednesday, May 8, 1996 several dozen riot police
attended a small rally against the new anti-homeless policies of the
mayor.  The protest included about 75 people many of whom had been
harassed and arrested during the past few months.  Local organizers are
also planning nation wide protests against the police state scheduled for
October of 1996.  Please get involved.  As one German reporter commented
at one of our recent protests. "The next Hitler will come from the United
States."  Take action now before it is too late.
Food Not Bombs - 3145 Geary Blvd. #12, San Francisco, CA 94118
1-800-884-1136 or 415-386-9209


</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
