<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Food Not Bombs Member Has Day in Court</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Food Not Bombs Member Has Day in Court</H3>
<PRE>

New York Times
By CAREY GOLDBERG

SAN FRANCISCO -- In 1994 Robert Kahn was sentenced to 60 days in jail 
for giving soup and bagels to the homeless near City Hall. 

But that was in the old San Francisco, a city considered one of the 
country's toughest on street people, and where a person could be 
convicted of violating a court injunction against feeding the poor 
without a permit. 

Last week Kahn went to Municipal Court to appeal his sentence in the 
new San Francisco, a town so altered that he was even supported by 
the district attorney. 

"Those policies have changed now," District Attorney Terence Hallinan 
told the court. "This district attorney and this city intend to grapple 
in a different way with the homeless problem in San Francisco and the 
fact that there are people in the streets who are hungry and need food." 

The pronounced shift in policy toward the homeless came in with Mayor 
Willie L. Brown Jr., who promised voters a more compassionate city before 
taking office in January. It presents one of the greatest challenges to 
his administration, one that will be carefully watched in other cities 
to see what happens when a heavy-handed approach to the homeless is 
lightened. 

Brown has officially dismantled the controversial crackdown program that 
was begun by his predecessor, Frank Jordan. It required the police to 
clamp down on people sleeping, camping, drinking and relieving 
themselves in public places. 

Brown denounced the Jordan policies, saying they treated people as if 
homelessness were a crime, and voters appeared largely to agree with 
him. So did Hallinan, who had himself given out food to the homeless 
with Kahn's group, Food Not Bombs. 

Last month a municipal judge dismissed almost 40,000 citations and arrest 
warrants that were issued to homeless people since 1993, during the 
Jordan administration. 

But it is not so simple to relax the rules on the street. Although San 
Francisco is a traditionally liberal city, it also depends upon tourists 
for billions of dollars each year, and tourists tend to complain about 
panhandlers and street sleepers. Homeless people, encouraged by generous 
local welfare grants and the fine climate, have long gravitated toward 
San Francisco and are believed to number about 10,000 in a population of 
about 730,000. 

So while Brown declared the Jordan program over, he also declared that 
the laws would continue to be enforced, and tickets are still being handed 
out for so-called quality-of-life violations in public places. In the 
meantime, Brown and his officials have said, they will search for 
innovative ways to fight the poverty that leads to homelessness, from 
improved job training to added housing. 

"We're trying to begin with a clean slate as we try to develop a new 
approach to this problem," Hallinan said. 

Advocates for the homeless in San Francisco say Brown's approach is 
certainly an improvement, but they are frustrated that the police do not 
seem to have eased up on sweeping homeless people out of public places. 

"In the areas like creating housing, there's more hope under the Brown 
administration," said Judy Appel, a lawyer with the Coalition on 
Homelessness here. "But as far as the law enforcement, there's every 
indication everything's going to stay the same or get worse because now 
the police are at full staff." 

But the police say the citations for quality-of-life crimes like sleeping 
in parks and obstructing sidewalks have dropped noticeably. In March and 
April 1995, they totaled 2,610, said Sgt. William Herndon, while in the 
corresponding period in 1996 they were down 23 percent to 2,017. 

Despite merchants' complaints to the contrary, the easing of police 
enforcement does not appear to have increased the number of homeless people 
in San Francisco. Neither did the Jordan program succeed in reducing the 
numbers of homeless, advocates say. 

But the police statistics on citations are not enough for advocates for the 
homeless like Kahn, 48, a writer with a bushy beard and ponytail from Santa 
Cruz who appeared in court on Thursday in a bathrobe and carrying his teddy 
bear, Edwina, to protest citations' being issued to people sleeping in parks. 

"The issue for me is not just my case but general concern for the homeless 
people of San Francisco and that Brown keep his word about not arresting 
them," Kahn said. 

When Kahn was arrested in October 1993, he was volunteering for Food Not 
Bombs, an anti-military group whose message is that there would be plenty 
of food for everyone if military spending were cut. 

The San Francisco operation of Food Not Bombs, one of more than 100 around 
the country, was a particular gadfly of the Jordan administration, and 
members say they were arrested more than 1,000 times before Brown took 
office. They continue to distribute food every day here even though the 
city has not issued them a permit; they have applied for a permit more 
than 100 times, they say, but the permits have been denied. 

Kahn was accused of disobeying a court injunction against passing out food 
without permission. Other members of the group were also arrested on that 
basis, but he was the only one convicted. 

Kahn's lawyer, David Beauvais, told Judge Robert A. Barclay: "I feel like 
I'm in a twilight zone where thoughts are running backward to the Dark Ages. 
We're talking about serving food, soup and bagels, to the homeless across 
from City Hall in a manner offensive to politicians now no longer in office." 

The hearing was on Kahn's request that his 60-day sentence be reduced to 
time already served, or one day in jail. Barclay said he was impressed by 
the arguments presented on Kahn's behalf, but added that he would need to 
think about the case and would reconvene the hearing on June 7. 


</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
