<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: NOW Pickets Mitsubishi in D.C.</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>NOW Pickets Mitsubishi in D.C.</H3><PRE>WASHINGTON, May 11 (Reuter) - <A HREF="http://www.now.org">The National Organization for Women</A> (NOW)picketed a Mitsubishi dealership to protest the automaker's allegedretaliation against female employees who filed a federal sexualharassment lawsuit.Carrying signs reading "Mitsubishi: Hands Off Women" and "Real Men Don'tPinch Their Co-workers", about 50 women demonstrated outside OurismanMitsubishi in the Washington suburb of Marlow Heights, Maryland,according to NOW president Patricia Ireland.Participants urged onlookers to write to Mitsubishi Motor Manufacturingof America Inc and to the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission(EEOC), which filed suit against the company on April 9. The motorcompany is a U.S. subsidary of the Japanese firm Mitsubishi Motors Corp.The company has been accused of "egregious and pervasive sexualharassment and retaliation" against women at Mitsubishi's Normal,Illinois plant."We're organizing this action to get activists and consumers and thedealers themselves to pressure Mitsubishi Motor Manufacturing to make ajust settlement of this reported extreme retaliation against women andthe EEOC," Ireland said by telephone.She said NOW wanted to put pressure on Mitsubishi sales and would pushfor "some fairness of distribution of dealerships" to include more womenand minorities.Darnell Magruder, general manager of the Marlow Heights dealership, saidhis operation was separate from Mitsubishi and had a policy of"inclusiveness".Saturday's demonstration was miniscule compared to one on April 22 whichsaw about 3,000 Mitsubishi plant workers and their families travel bybus from Normal to the Chicago office of the EEOC to protest against thesexual harassment suit.Ireland said other NOW efforts were planned in Illinois, California andNevada over the next few days to focus attention on sexual harassment.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
