<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Chicago Police May Picket Democratic Convention</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Chicago Police to Protest Democratic Convention?</H3><PRE>From Chicago Sun Times, May 8, 1996Cop Supervisors Vow to Picket Democratic Convention by FRAN SPIELMANCity Hall Reporter Police supervisors threatened Tuesday to embarrassMayor Daley with informational picketing at the Democratic NationalConvention after the mayor vowed to appeal a ruling allowing them tobargain collectively.``Everywhere the delegates will be, we'll have pickets. Off-duty policeofficers and their families will let the Democrats know the mayor ofthis city is unfair to organized labor,'' said Lt. Tim Nolan, presidentof the Chicago Police Lieutenants Association.By declining to meet with groups representing sergeants, lieutenants andcaptains, Nolan said, Daley makes it obvious he ``wants aconfrontation.'' He'll get one at a time when all eyes will be onChicago, Nolan vowed.  ``The mayor has put his head in the sand and he'sbeing unreasonable. Has he given us five minutes? No. He flippantly sayshe's appealing. Well, excuse me. We have our rights, too,'' Nolan said. Daley, who has spent seven years resisting collective bargaining forpolice supervisors, said he has no intention of allowing anadministrative law judge for the Illinois Labor Board to be the finalarbiter on the issue.The Chicago Sun-Times reported Monday that the judge gave 1,500 policesupervisors the right to bargain collectively. The six-day trialfeatured testimony from former Mayor Jane M. Byrne, Daley's politicalnemesis. The city has 14 days to appeal the ruling to the Labor Board,and Daley told reporters Tuesday he would do so. If the Labor Board goesagainst the city, the next step would be the Illinois Appellate Court.``Lieutenants and sergeants should belong to the management team of theChicago Police Department. You cannot dilute 99 percent of a departmentand say less than 1 percent is management. It can't be thesuperintendent or five assistant superintendents and four captains inthe district,'' Daley said. The city needs the right to deploy managerswhere it sees fit without regard to seniority, Daley said. Sergeants,lieutenants and captains want, among other things, the right to bid onshifts and districts based on seniority.``That's the problem,'' Daley said. ``Everyone wants to bid on the bestdistricts. ...  You should not do it by seniority. Lieutenants andsergeants have to manage police officers.''    The mayor dismissedNolan's threat to embarrass him when Chicago holds the DemocraticNational Convention Aug. 26-29.  ``The convention will go on'' no matterwhat, Daley said.Posted in pol-abuse@igc.apc.orgTo subscribe, send this message: subscribe pol-abuseTo this address: <A HREF="mailto:majordomo@igc.apc.org">majordomo@igc.apc.org</A></PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
