<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Pastors for Peace -- Some Computers to be Released</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Pastors for Peace -- Some Computers to be Released</H3>
<PRE>

NEWS RELEASE
IFCO / Pastors for Peace

CONTACT:
In San Diego:      619/582-8288,   619/295-8769,   619/542-0826
In Washington:  202/544-3825 (phone),  202/886-7369, 202/886-5444 (pagers)
In New York: 212/926-5757, fax: 212/926-5842; email ifco@igc.apc.org

MEDIA ADVISORY -- 5/13/95 -- FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

AFTER 83 DAYS, IFCO/PASTORS FOR PEACE AND US TREASURY AGREE ON RELEASE TODAY OF
 SEIZED CANADIAN COMPUTERS.

US Treasury Department sources have indicated that US Customs in San Diego
will release the Canadian computers which were seized from Pastors for Peace
on 1/31.   The release is expected to take place on Monday, May 13.

Representatives of the national denominations and religious organizations
who will officially receive the medical computers from US Customs have
gathered in San Diego.  They include leaders of the General Board of Church
and Society of the United Methodist Church, the Episcopal Church, the
American Baptist Churches/USA--National Ministries, the Progressive
National Baptist Convention, the General Board of Global Ministries of
the United Methodist Church, and the National Council of Churches of
Christ in the USA.


Canadian faster Brian Rohatyn, for whom Monday marks Day 83 of his fast,
and Pastors for Peace director Tom Hansen, have arrived in San Diego to
be present for the release of the Canadian computers.

Rohatyn has announced that he will officially end his fast as soon as the
Canadian computers are released, checked for tampering, and taken across
the border into Mexico.  The Treasury Department agreement also stipulates
the return of the $100 bond, which was paid by Canadian volunteers to
guarantee transport of the computers across the US and on to Cuba.

Pressure continues to mount for the release of the remaining US computers,
still being held by US Customs, which are destined for Cuban churches and
health care facilities.  Rev. Lucius Walker, Jr., executive director of
IFCO/Pastors for Peace, speaking on behalf of the four fasters, expressed
gratitude to the government officials, the more than 60 members of Congress,
the religious and labor leaders, and the hundreds of thousands of grassroots
supporters who have advocated for the computers' release.

Walker said, "We applaud the release of the Canadian computers, and we
pray that our government officials also will release the computers which
were donated by US citizens.  The three remaining fasters will continue
the fast until the remaining computers are released."

In an official statement, Rohatyn said, "As a Canadian citizen, I call on
the US government to do the right thing, take the moral initiative, and
release ALL of the medical aid as quickly as possible."
                                -30-

Press Contacts/Beepers:
Andrea Saenz - 202/886-5444
Jim Mellor - 917/433-0386





</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
