<HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: WALL ST. RALLY: SPEAKING OUT IN BELLY OF BEAST</TITLE></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><P><IMG SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" BORDER=0 ><IMG SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" BORDER=0 ></P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>WALL ST. RALLY: SPEAKING OUT IN BELLY OF BEAST</H3><PRE>-------------------------Via Workers World News ServiceReprinted from the May 16, 1996issue of Workers World newspaper-------------------------By Carlos RoviraNew YorkInternational Workers Day was proudly commemorated here May 1 from thesteps of Federal Hall on Wall Street. For three hours an exciting MayDay celebration, organized by Workers World Party, took place in themidst of U.S. imperialism's financial center.The demands of the oppressed and exploited were defiantly displayed. Astatue glorifying the slaveowner George Washington had its view blockedby a banner reading, &quot;Ban layoffs, raise wages.&quot;The May Day action gained the approval of many people in the area,especially those who depend on a job to survive but suffer racism and/orsexism, low pay and the constant threat of layoff. Several applauded andclenched their fists in agreement.Organizers of the event were approached by many workers who wanted totalk about their experiences with various kinds of abuse. Messengers,clerks, secretaries, restaurant and maintenance employees were among themany who eagerly came to tables to exchange information and getliterature, including issues of Workers World newspaper.The program began at 12 noon--a lunch break for most people. Provingthat this May Day celebration was organized on behalf of the workingclass, a jazz-rock band of talented Workers World Party members gotthings going with a tune called &quot;Raise The Minimum Wage.&quot;The force of revolutionary culture when combined with revolutionaryworking-class politics became apparent to all.By the time speakers were ready to make presentations, curiousspectators had crowded the nearby intersections. The voices of theorators traveled far, bouncing off the walls of surrounding buildings,urging everyone to unite.Many speakers cited the rich's control of the government for the miseryendured by the poor.Workers World Party Presidential Candidate Monica Moorehead, thefeatured speaker, explained what socialism really is: a society wherethe political and economic power of the rich over the working-classmajority has been broken by taking ownership of production out ofprivate hands. Socialism, she said, allows working people to havecontrol over the important aspects of their lives.Moorehead posed the questions: &quot;Why are millions of our tax dollarsbeing used to bomb Lebanon and blockade Cuba while public services arebeing eliminated? Why is there construction of more prisons instead ofdaycare centers and schools? Why are there so many starving and homelesspeople in the richest country of the world?&quot;She concluded by pointing out that capitalism is responsible for today'ssocial evils--including racism, sexism, and anti-gay and anti-immigrantoppression and persecution.Although the May Day rally lasted for only a couple of hours, itssignificance was unquestionable. How often has this workers' holidaybeen commemorated in a location filled with symbols legitimizingplunder? May Day 1996 in New York was a harbinger of the coming storm ofworking class fightback.                         - END -(Copyright Workers World Service: Permission to reprint granted ifsource is cited. For more information contact Workers World, 55 W. 17St., NY, NY 10011; via e-mail: ww@wwpublish.com. For subscription infosend message to: <A HREF="mailto:ww-info@wwpublish.com">ww-info@wwpublish.com</A>. Web: <A HREF="http://www.workers.org">http://www.workers.org</A>===========================