<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Tribute for Legendary Canadian Activist Claire Culhane</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Tribute for Legendary Canadian Activist Claire Culhane</H3><PRE>The following is an obituary for Claire Culhane who helped to shapeanti-prison activism in Canada for 20 years. She was an exemplaryactivist, leading by example. The following obituary is from the TorontoGlobe and Mail, May 2, 1996, written by Kirk Makin who writes on prisonissues for the paper.Claire Culhane When a heart attack and stroke last year convinced ClaireCulhane she might be mortal, the legendary prison activists sent apoignant message to her enormous network in and outside of prison."This will have to be my last letter to you, and that really hurts," shewrote, "I must stop completely and totally what I've been doing for 20years. Damn!"Within weeks, the 77-year-old grandmother was at it again, cranking outletters and faxes and touring penitentiaries. When Ms. Culhane's heartfinally failed last Sunday night (April 30, 1996) in Vancouver, sheunquestionably held every record for visiting or corresponding withprisoners as well as being a general burr under the saddle of theCanadian correctional bureaucracy.She was born in 1918 to Orthodox Jewish parents of humble means ineast-end Montreal, and it was never entirely clear how Claire Elgin cameby her focused rage and relentless sense of mission.Perhaps the strongest clue lies in the favouritism her parents showed totheir only other child, a son. Ms Culhane's open resentment appeared tospill over into her obsession with justice and equality for women.in her teens, her ambition was to become a nurse. Tat dream died afteradministrators of her Royal Ottawa Hospital nursing program caught hersmuggling medication from the private ward to the public ward.A loyal member of the Communist Party of Canada, she married fellowactivist Gerry Culhane and worked in the trade-union movement. Theyproduced two children When her marriage failed, MS Culhane made anextraordinary sacrifice for one so ideologically driven: she dropped herpolitical activities to raise the children.In the late sixties, she landed a job run by the Canadian government inwar-torn South Vietnam. Upon her return, she chained herself to thepublic gallery in the house of Commons to protest Canadian complicity inthe war. At the war's end, she embraced a new cause - prisoner's rights.For the next twenty years, she devoted herself to lifting spirits andrighting perceived wrongs - whether this involved restoring familyvisits for an inmate or speeding his parole.In the eyes of inmates, her great strength was her unswerving, almostevangelical acceptance that their version of events was true. TheCulhane method involved a rain of letters, phone calls or faxes toprison officials and the press. If that didn't do the trick, shethreatened to picket the institution, or the warden's home.She never accepted one ounce of the system," recalled Andrew Graham,deputy commissioner of the Correctional Service of Canada. "A lot ofpeople were terrified of her. The fax machine was a lethal weapon in herhands."Ms. Culhane was as fearless as she was indefatigable. Temporarily bannedfrom Canadian prisons several years ago, she happily trespassed andinvited the authorities to risk arresting a white-haired grandmother.They caved in. She was astonishingly frugal, wearing only second handclothes and religiously recycling old paper and envelopes by typing onwhatever space she could find. Unwilling to waste low overnight phonerates, Ms. Culhane slept in snatches. her fax machine hummed incessantlyas she typed her nightly quota of letters.The Culhane filing system was legendary. A friend tells of once engagingin a frustrating search for a dishcloth. Each kitchen drawer or cupboardshe opened was crammed with files.Until her old-age pension kicked in, Ms Culhane's work was financed byhouse-cleaning or typing jobs. When she went on a prison tour, she wasinvariably given free room and board by her network of ex-prisoners,families of inmates or prison lawyers.Warm but demanding, Ms Culhane indulged in little recreational timebeyond the Sunday "crepe breakfasts" she put on for her extended family.Yet, despite her frenzied lifestyle, she managed to churn out two books.Her small victories were many, a fact given broad recognition last yearwhen Ms Culhane was named to the Order of Canada. (Canada's highestcivilian honour.) But she was ultimately able to do little more thandent a seemingly impregnable prison system. It was a failure thatincreasingly depressed her - a depression exacerbated by what she saw asa global descent into greed and destruction.A humanist, Ms Culhane requested that her death be marked by nothingmore than a memorial service, which is planned for May 11 at Vancouver'smaritime Labour Centre.Upon hearing of these plans, the CSC's Mr Graham sent a communique toevery penitentiary soliciting anecdotes and tributes from staff andinmates about his adversary's life.In the "office" she maintained in daughter Dara's home during her finalyear, Ms. Culhane's trusty fax machine is working overtime. For once itis only receiving.</PRE> </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
