<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Turkey counts cost of bloody May Day</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Turkey counts cost of bloody May Day</H3><PRE>ISTANBUL: Turkey began mopping up on Thursday after three people werekilled, 65 injured and 227 detained in violent May Day protests,security officials said.Istanbul governor Ridvan Yenisen said on Wednesday night that two ofthose killed in clashes between police and leftist protesters in thecity belonged to illegal organisations.``I leave it to the public to decide what masked groups were doing at ameeting that should have been a joyful demonstration,'' Mr Yenisen wasquoted by Anatolian news agency as saying. ``The aims are clear, tobring a sorry end to a legal gathering.''Many protesters in Wednesday's riots displayed the colours of a range ofillegal groups from outlawed leftist groups, including Dev Sol, amilitant armed group believed to be behind fatal attacks on police inIstanbul over the past year, to the rebel Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK),fighting a 12-year separatist guerrilla war in the southeast.The police, not usually hesitant in dealing violently withdemonstrations, took heavy casualties. Forty-eight police were among theinjured.Newspapers on Thursday were splashed with pictures of a plain clothespoliceman, his face dripping with blood, being beaten and kickedunderfoot by a group of demonstrators, who had recognised him by thepistol in his belt.Istanbul's new police chief, Kemal Yazicioglu, said police had beenrestrained during the demonstration to prevent further violence anddamage.``We had enough forces. If we had wanted we could have dispersed thecrowd. But we waited and were patient. If we had interfered the resultwould have been much more serious,'' Mr Yazicioglu was quoted byAnatolian as saying.The mass-selling 'Hurriyet daily put the damage done by demonstrators,who ransacked shops around the main square in Istanbul's Kadikoydistrict, at around $2.7 million.- Reuter** End of text from cdp:labr.global *****************************************************************************This material came from PeaceNet, a non-profit progressive networkingservice.  For more information, send a message topeacenet-info@igc.apc.org***************************************************************************</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
