<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Columbia Students End Successful Hunger Strike and Occupation</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Columbia Students End Successful Hunger Strike and Occupation</H3><PRE>By SARAH KERSHAW New York TimesNEW YORK -- Columbia University students demanding the creation of anethnic studies department ended a rancorous two-week battle, with theadministration pledging Monday night to hire more minority facultymembers and give students a role in the selections.As the settlement came, three students ended a 15-day hunger strike, andabout 100 students who had blockaded and occupied a campus buildingsince last Friday agreed to leave quietly.University officials insisted that they had made no concessions, sayingthey had already begun to pursue most of the proposals contained in thesettlement reached Monday night. The students' biggest demands -- thecreation of an ethnic studies department or a separate academic programdevoted to such subjects -- went unmet."We didn't get what we wanted," said Reena Shah, a junior. "But we got abeginning."Still, while administration officials asserted that they had made noconcessions during three days of intense negotiations with students, theagreement did appear to yield some compromises. The university agreedfor the first time to provide physical space for programs in Asian andHispanic studies that were already being developed, and they pledged toraise the money for an additional Hispanic professor.Officials said that they had already planned to hire the professor butthat they had approved the position in the last two weeks."The fact that things occurred at the same time as the student actionsdoes not mean they resulted from the student ] actions," Dean Austin E.Quigley of Columbia College said.Quigley reasserted what Columbia's President, George Rupp, said onSunday, saying that university officials do not negotiate with studentson questions of academic curriculum.In a stern statement on Sunday, Columbia's president, George Rupp vowedto retake the building whatever the outcome of negotiations and assertedthat the university does not negotiatiate with students on questions ofacademic curriculum.Monday night, the Quigley said the students had not pressured theuniversity into making academic policy changes that were not alreadyunder way."The fact that things occurred at the same time as the student actionsdoes not mean they resulted from the student actions," he said. "We weredoing serious things. The students were worried we weren't. They pressedus to provide reassurance, and this agreement registers both what wehave been doing and the reassurance they need to feel that this is aserious and long-term committment."Under the agreement, the university will hire four new minority facultymembers, two Asians and two Hispanics, and continue to recruit facultyfor the African-American studies department. New minority professorswill then have the chance to create an ethnic studies center, butneither a center nor a separate academic department devoted to minoritystudies was guaranteed.Over the last two weeks, students have held several demonstrations,including one last Wednesday in which 23 students were arrested afterblockading Low Library. Last Friday, about 100 students barricadedHamilton Hall, where they remained until 7:30 p.m. Monday night.Monday university officials ordered the students out of the building by5 p.m. and students refused, vowing to continue the occupation. Butseveral professors urged the students to leave the building and end thedispute."Quibbling about it now could cost us the whole game," said RobertO'Meally, an English professor who urged the students to accept theuniversity's offer.University officials also promised in the agreement that they would nottake disciplinary action against the students who had occupied thebuilding, a pledge that several students said had persuaded them to giveup the fight.As negotiations broke down before the settlement Monday, Marcel Agueros,one of the hunger-strikers, said: "I feel very frustrated. I'm extremelydisappointed in the complete lack of commitment and the stonewalling."Mr. Agueros, 23, a senior, said he had sustained himself on two gallonsof water a day, which he sometimes mixes with a powder containing arice-based iron supplement."We function essentially on adrenaline and on the positive feeling fromeveryone," he said. "It sounds New Agish, but that's how it works."On one wall of Hamilton Hall, the students have scrawled in pink andpurple chalk the names of writers and civil rights leaders they saidColumbia students should read in ethnic studies classes: Marcus Garvey,Bobby Seale, Steven Biko, Frederick Douglass and Cesar Chavez. Thebuilding faces the campus's main library, whose elegant facade isengraved with the names of philosophers taught in the university'srenowned classic academic courses: Homer, Herodotus, Sophocles andPlato.By Monday, several students who did not take part in the protests saidthey had become irritated with the demonstrations and the disruption theoccupation was causing.Groups of students rushed to the schedule of classes posted on the sideof the building, searching for new class locations. Others approachedthe protesters and begged them to end the occupation."Their tactics are infantile, and they serve to alienate more peoplethan they bring to their cause," said Will Crenshaw, a freshman whosemorning Latin class was held outside on the lawn near Hamilton Hall, butwas then cut short when the protesters' chanting became too loud. "Ididn't pay tuition for a 20-minute class," he said.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
