<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: 13,000 "Fight the Right" in San Francisco</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>13,000 "FIGHT THE RIGHT" IN SAN FRANCISCO</H3><PRE>By CAREY GOLDBERGThe New York TimesSAN FRANCISCO -- Nearly 13,000 young feminists, old leftists, concernedimmigrants and even "Angry White Guys for Affirmative Action" joinedforces Sunday for a national "Fight the Right" march along the bay.Held here because the National Organization for Women wanted to have amajor protest outside of Washington this year, the march was joined bysome 500 groups supporting liberal causes, like abortion and gay rightsand celebrities, including Gloria Steinem and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.What inspired the unusual unity of its disparate participants was whatthey call the "radical right," their common and increasingly powerfulenemy in American politics."They are racist," Ms. Steinem told a pre-march rally. "They are sexist.They are homophobic. They are useful in a way because they help make ourcoalition because they're everything we're against."The march was meant to start the election season of rallies andcanvassing, now about to begin in earnest, said NOW president PatriciaIreland said."Nineteen ninety-four gave us all a real heads up," she said ofelectoral gains by conservative Republicans. "If we don't unify andstand together, we're going to get pushed back. This gives us some realmomentum going into the next elections."The march was held in California in part because of NOW's concern abouta new initiative against affirmative action in public employment andeducation that will be on November's ballot."The affirmative action measure on the California ballot has made itclear what we all have to do," Ms. Steinem said. "Three things: get outthe vote, get out the vote, get out the vote."If nothing else, the day of hobnobbing and T-shirt selling allowedintense networking that could lay the groundwork for upcoming campaignwork. Backers of a proposal to legalize marijuana for medicinal usecould be seen signing the petitions proferred by backers of a measuresupporting affirmative action, and vice versa, in a great round robin.One of the hottest new groups among march participants was one selling a"Hands off Hillary" pin and collecting signatures on a petition callingfor an end to the investigation of the first lady's financial dealings.There were also groups agitating for immigrants' rights and NOW membersfrom as far away as Maine and New Hampshire.At the pre-march rally, one of the most popular speakers was PaulRockwell, a founder of the group "Angry White Guys For AffirmativeAction," which argues that preferences among Americans are so widespreadthat minorities should not be begrudged their own leg up."There are two kinds of preferences in America," Rockwell said toswelling cheers. "Favoritism for white men of power and sociallypatriotic preferences for the good of all Americans."Other recent NOW protests have included a 1992 abortion-rightsdemonstration and a protest last year over violence against women, bothin Washington, Ms. Ireland said, adding that the group does not plan tomake them annual affairs, except perhaps in election years.The National Park Service estimated the crowd at about 13,000 by the endof the march.The daylong event had a picnicky atmosphere under the hazy San Franciscosun. Slogans on T-shirts and signs ran the gamut, with one of the moreoriginal belonged to M.J. Wickham, a commercial photographer from nearbySanta Rosa, who had fashioned a placard reading "Oust the barbarians!""I think that the current congressional leaders are just building aplatform on hate and some pretty barbarian ideas, so I figured what theheck," she said.A group of Act-Up members caused a disruption when they tried to insistthat their AIDS-activist group be allowed to speak. But that was a minordisturbance in a long, warm day of intermingling among a strikingvariety of groups.Anne Kieckbusch, a data base technician, and Robin Yuknis, a paralegal,both 23 and from Milwaukee, said they were pleasantly surprised to seeso many men at a NOW rally -- and so many people there altogether.If it had taken place in Milwaukee instead of the liberal bastion of SanFrancisco, Ms. Yuknis said, "I just don't think it would be that big."</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
