<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Protest is the Sound of Spring at Columbia University</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>PROTEST IS THE SOUND OF SPRING AT COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY</H3><PRE>By NEIL MacFARQUHARThe New York TimesNEW YORK -- It's April. The trees in Central Park sprout buds. Baseballis back. And students at Columbia University occupy a building.While not precisely an annual rite, demonstrations at Columbia arecertainly a hardy perennial, passed immutably from one generation to thenext.The techniques -- the hunger strikes, the bullhorns, the stopping ofclasses -- were largely born of the violent confrontations of 1968.But even as protesting students embrace that legacy, they sometimes findthe inevitable comparisons with earlier upheavals more burden thaninspiration."Students there feel some need to live up to the heroism of theirpredecessors, they have this sense that once there was a generation thatwas activist," said Morris Dickstein, a former Columbia professor andnow an administrator with the City University of New York.Sunday was Day 14 of a hunger strike by three students who pitched ablue pup tent in the middle of the campus and demanded that theuniversity accelerate its development of minority studies by creating aseparate academic department.The subsequent protests edged closest to violence on Wednesday, when 23students were arrested after blockading Low Library, the mainadministration building. The university sealed its outer gates for daysafterward, limiting campus access to those with Columbia identificationcards.On Friday, about 100 protesters who had begun by whispering chantsinside Hamilton Hall suddenly barricaded themselves inside, forcingclasses and administrators to meet elsewhere.The university's president, George Rupp, vowed that the building wouldbe reopened Monday, whatever the outcome of overnight discussions withprotest leaders."We are not prepared to have Hamilton Hall unavailable to the studentsand faculty, to whom it is a very important facility," Rupp said bytelephone Sunday from Washington, where he was attending an academicconference.Aside from disrupting classes, the protesters prevented theadministrators determining next year's admissions and financial aid fromreaching their offices during a crucial period, he said."We don't develop academic curricula through negotiations, but throughthe regular process that has served Columbia very well," the presidentsaid. He noted that the faculty and most students supported the processwhich already produced a tremendous increase in courses on minorityissues and a continuing search for new faculty. "Students do not designour curriculum nor enforce our standards."Bleary-eyed, mussy-haired and draped in blankets, the students of allraces maintaining the vigil over this past weekend vowed to hang on tothe building occupied repeatedly over the years.They were not even born when Hamilton Hall was occupied for seven daysin 1968. Most were in elementary school when it was shut down for threeweeks in 1985 by students demanding that Columbia divest its endowmentof stocks from companies doing business in South Africa."We know what happened in 1968, we all know the history of the past 30years," said Andre Morales, 19, a spokesman for the group. "But we arehere more for ethnic studies and our cause than for just the history ofprotesting."And certainly there are changes. Morales carries a cellular telephonefor 24-hour press availability. Scores of E-mail messages from aroundthe country, both pro and con, have been flooding in to topadministrators.And the university can update the campus population on its actionsthrough the telephone system, leaving a message on the voicemail ofevery dormitory and office telephone.This time, Hamilton Hall was not renamed Malcolm X University (April1968), nor Mandela Hall (April 1985), but the students did drape abanner across the front proclaiming "Liberated Building. Ignorance FreeZone. Ethnic Studies Now."That was about as harsh as the revolutionary slogans went. When energyflagged, there was no war to denounce, nor did the group turn to rousingpolemics on social justice. Rather they ordered takeout caffe lattesfrom Cooper's Coffee Bar.Occasional speakers on the bullhorn referred to the protest as "the samething they did in the 1960s,"but this was not the kind of crowd to puttheir feet up on the desk and smoke the president's cigars. (One of themost famous images from 1968.)Most of the protesters were sitting around reading books like "TheFederalist Papers" or Jane Austen's "Pride and Prejudice," some of thevery works that provoked the showdown.In addition to a separate department for the study of African-American,Asian-American and Hispanic studies, the students are demanding thatmore works from these cultures be included in Columbia's famous corerequirements, whose central elements have been intact since the 1960s.All undergraduates must take four one-term courses in Westerncivilization that cover literature, philosophy, history, music and art.They must also take two more courses about non-Western civilizations."I am reading 'Pride and Prejudice' because I'm being forced to," saidValerie Vladavsky, 18, a freshman. "I think it could be replaced by asignificant work from another culture." Another protester, CarlosOlivares, 19, defended Austen (who was added to the core to include morefemale authors), although he said the course mix needed to change."It's like this big pie with little pieces that could be taken out wherewe could stick in our own works,"Olivares said.Their protest happened to coincide with the weekend's visit by hundredsof parents and alumni. For some alumni, a fervent demonstration at theiralma mater evokes the kind of devotion others might bestow on a goodsports team."Even though I disagree with them, God bless them," said Andrew Bronin,Class of '69, a doctor from Greenwich, Conn."I slept there -- well, I sort of slept there," yelled Steven Ross as hetalked to the protesters. (His class? "A member of the red class of '68,the class that never graduated.") He threw out questions like, "Have youguys locked the dean in his office?""No," came the response. "Thanks for the idea, though."Some graduates of earlier movements even took to the microphone to offeradvice: Stay vigilant when it rains and numbers dwindle; hang in there,the university always caves in."The university will try to divide and conquer you, they will charge youwith every possible violation of the discipline code but it is importantnot to be dissuaded," said Tony Glover, '86, and former co-chair of theCoalition for a Free South Africa, which organized the 1985 takeoverthat won divestment.Columbia students, faculty and alumni pointed to changes in the makeupof the student body as a key factor in lending the protest movement afervor gone from other campuses.Columbia has made a significant effort to attract more minoritystudents, now 36 percent of the approximately 3,000 undergraduates.(Harvard has 33 percent; Princeton, 18.)In 1968, the local issue that got the protesters rolling was theuniversity's plan to build a gym in Morningside Park, an open space muchused by Harlem residents. The demand for the university to be moresensitive to the surrounding community has never gone away."The protests in the 1980s and the 1990s have been about racial issues,"said Eric Foner, a history professor. "Black students often feel lessassimilated into the culture of the college than white students."But the issues still reverberate less than they did three decades ago.Long gone are the days when a small group of chanters mushroomed to2,000 people. At one point these protesters abandoned reading theirmanifesto and just pleaded with passers-by to listen."It's refreshing to see people motivated like this," said Phoebe Nobles,a sophomore eating a sandwich not far from the hunger strikerssubsisting on water with additives. "But you don't put your life indanger for a university issue like this. We are not Gandhi."</PRE> </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
