<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: LA Police Beating Reaction-Tale of Two Cities</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>LA POLICE BEATING REACTION-TALE OF TWO CITIES</H3><PRE>by Michael Novick with thanks to Charles DickensIt was the best of times; it was the worst of times.On Saturday, April 6, Los Angeles had two reactions to the beating ofseveral undocumented immigrants by Riverside County sheriffs. On thecity's west side, near UCLA and the V.A. Hospital and cemetery, 200middle-aged and older white folks gathered in front of the WestwoodFederal Building to cheer in support of the police and opposition toimmigration. Simultaneously, downtown, more than 6,000 marchers --mostly Latino, with Black and Asian contingents, chanted through thestreets, changing their destination from the downtown federal buildingas originally scheduled, to the larger plaza in front of City Hall, astheir numbers swelled beyond expectations or the capacity of the streetin front of the federal building to contain them.Ron Prince, initiator of the anti-immigrant Proposition 187, and GlennSpence, leader of the recent "Paul Revere Ride" from San Diego to thenortheast (warning of a 'Mexican' invasion), harangued the crowd ofBirchers, Perot-istas and Buchananites in Westwood. The anti-immigrant,pro-police crowd, organized by Prince's SOS (Save Our State) andSpence's Voice of Citizen's Together, with the support of the localUnited We Stand America and Buchanan's campaign people, managed to makeit onto all the local evening TV news shows despite their small numberswith their message of resentment and fear.Downtown, the pro-immigrants' rights, anti-police brutality march andrally were energetic, colorful, youthful.  A Black contingent from theUS organization as well as several larger Asian groupings, includingAPI-FIRE (Asian/Pacific Islanders For Immigrants' Rights and Equality)were greeted warmly by the mostly Mexicano and Central Americanprotesters.  As in the massive demonstration against Prop 187 in Oct.'94, though on a smaller scale, a strong Mexican presence was augmentedby Chicanos, Salvadorans, Guatemalans and other Central Americans insubstantial numbers.  There were some labor contingents, frommostly-Latino ranks such as Justice for Janitors.  Turnout fromprogressive white forces was disappointingly low, though State Sen. TomHayden, who represents the west side and west Valley area and isconsidering a run for Mayor, spoke from the platform in English andSpanish.  Speakers were interspersed with music and culturalperformances including "rap en espanol."  Principal organizers includedOne-Stop Immigration, a part of the Coordinadora that sponsored the Oct.'94 march of close to a quarter million, and has been planning a Latinocivil rights march on Washington for October '96 since before thatmassive L.A. rally against Prop. 187.  One-Stop has always incorporateda call for a new amnesty into its work against immigrant-bashing.Other demonstrations have also been held in recent days at the borderand in Riverside County against anti-immigrant violence and police andBorder Patrol brutality.Michael NovickPeople Against Racist Terror (PART)PO Box 1990Burbank CA 91507310-288-5003publication:Turning the Tide, journal of anti-racist activism, research & education** End of text from cdp:headlines *****************************************************************************This material came from PeaceNet, a non-profit progressive networkingservice.  For more information, send a message to peacenet-info@igc.apc.org***************************************************************************</PRE></TD><