<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Lastest Harrasment News from Food Not Bombs</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>LASTEST HARRASMENT NEWS FROM FOOD NOT BOMBS</H3><PRE>Keith McHenry3145 Geary Blvd. #12, San Francisco, CA 94118 - 415-386-9209Mayor Brown401 Van Ness Ave.San Francisco, CA 94102April 4. 1996Dear Mayor Brown,First let me express my appreciation for Parking and Traffic BureauChief Robert Lynch's support during what became 64 hours of bureaucraticterrorism in an attempt to register my truck.  Each year this happensand it is clear that this is just more harassment designed to waste mytime so I'm not able to spent my days working to improving ourcommunity.  It appears someone with access to Parking and Traffic andDMV computers deliberately changes information on me and my vehicle.  Irespectfully request that this stop.  Please ask Parking and Traffic tosubmit a budget request for $3,840. to the Board of Supervisors toreimburse me for my lost wages.Because of the change in administration, Attorney Karen Parker hasrequested that Food Not Bombs submit an update on the politicalrepression in San Francisco so she can add it to the United NationsHuman Rights Commission investigation G/SO 215/1 USA (297).  Thecommittee working to inform human rights groups on the status ofrepression had hoped to provide a report which indicated that thesituation in San Francisco had improved.  Unfortunately the change hasonly been for the worse.   I am also forwarding a copy of this update tothe investigation being conducted by Amnesty International in London andto the US Justice Department and US Senator Boxer.Today I experienced and observed a substantial amount of policerepression here in San Francisco.  I attended a protest against publichousing evictions organized by the Coalition of Concerned Residents ofLow Income and Public Housing with about 30 other people outside thetemporary City Hall at 401 Van Ness. (see flyer) At about 1:00pmeveryone at the protest except me went inside to deliver a letter ofprotest to the San Francisco Board of Supervisors.  I did not know it atthe time, but the group was blocked from entering the elevators by thepolice.  While I was standing out side watching the coalition's soundsystem, the literature table and the protest signs several officersincluding Stars, 1227, 1362, 1715, and 142 approached my pick-up truck. Lt. Bruce, Star 1227, started writing me a ticket. ( PD 2014762enclosed)  I asked him why he was ticketing me.  He told me I had tomove my truck which was legally parked but the back was very close tothe red bus zone.  I moved my truck up but when I got out Lt. Bruce toldme he would tow my truck if I didn't leave the area, so I told him thatI would pack up my table and leave.He then asked me for my ID.  I gave it to him.  This worried me becauseon April 27, 1994 Lt. Bruce had me arrested and towed for driving with asuspended license.  I discovered that the police had given me a covertdrivers license number XVZ0SUU2 which they claimed was suspended.  Thenumber on the drivers license that I had on me was A1441302.  (see printout with citation 074984265) That afternoon the California Department ofMotor Vehicles claimed my license was not suspended.  I was alsoarrested on October 31, 1994 and November 1, 1994 by Lt. Bruce forhaving a suspended drivers license and each time the DMV could not findany indication that it was suspended.  It turns out that at that timedriving with a suspended license is not an arrestable offense and thatmy license was not suspended.  It took me a total of six years tofinally straighten this out.  At least I hope the covert drivers licensenumber will not reappear.Lt. Bruce asked the inspector if he had a citation book while a deliveryperson was asking the police if they could move their cars, which wereblocking him in.  After a while they let the delivery man  out.   Heasked his assistant to find out what charges he could give me.  I wentover to the pay phone and called Police Chief Fred Lau.  Mr. Lau askedme if I had talked to Captain Carins.  I told him that I had not seenhim.  The Chief of Police told me he would call over to Northern Stationand talk to Captain Carins.There is little indication that talking to Captain Carins would be ofmuch help.  He has a bad record of violating people rights and wassuspended for breaking a protester's hand at an Act-up protest. Mr.Carins also broke a man's scull at the same event.  Carins threatened tokill me in front of witnesses while I was handcuffed to a wall atNorthern Station in 1994.  At least one witness made a sworn statementabout the innocent which has been introduced in a federal lawsuit.I went back over to Lt. Bruce, who issued me misdemeanor citation078809161 (see copy enclosed) and he again ordered me to leave. Theother protesters had not come back.  Another space opened up so I pulledup to the parking place, put money in the meter and went up to youroffice. When I tried to opened the  door to the reception area it waslocked. Nydia, who has been the mayor's office receptionist for yearscame up and tried to get in but she couldn't open the door either.  Atone point a man named Cliff Java came to the door and let Nydia in buthe would not let me nor any of the other people waiting in the hall wayin.  By this time about 8 San Francisco Police officers appeared andstood around me. Several delivery people, an attorney and the 8 cops allstood outside the receptionist's office for about 5 minutes.  Two men insuites were let in, they turned out to be San Francisco Policemen KevinDillon, Star 222 and Jeff Lindberg, Star 20.  Then Cliff Java came tothe door and said "all right you can come in now."  We all entered, Iasked to see the Mayor's Chief of Staff but was told he was out.  I thenasked to speak with who ever was the highest ranking person available tosee me.  Executive Assistant to the Mayor-Eleanor Johns said she wouldtalk to me.  I showed her the tickets and asked if she could make a copyand give one to you. I requested that the Mayor send me a letter statingthat the tickets had been dropped. Supervisor Mable Tang walked by and Iasked her if she could help.  Of course she couldn't help so I left andwent to my truck and drove to a 2:00pm meeting at Golden Gate Park.Several people who eat with Food Not Bombs told me that there was goingto be a meeting to protest the increased arrests of the homeless.  Whilewalking to the meeting a group of 7 or 8 older white people in greenshirts with the letters RAD walked past.  RAD stands for ResidenceAgainst Drugs which is the local Haight Ashbury anti homeless group. When I arrived at the park there were 5 or 6 patrol cars, 10 or 12officers hanging out with the RAD people.  They stood near the meetingmaking those attending uncomfortable.  The meeting went well any way andwhen we left the cops and their friends also left the area.I urge you to find a way to end this police repression.  So far the taxpayers of San Francisco have spent over $10,000,000 trying to stop FoodNot Bombs from protesting.  The City has become known around the worldfor its political repression.  I urge your office to publicly speak outagainst this repression and to take strong action to have it stop.  Ihope your administration will learn from the past two mayor's experianceand order an end to political repression.  Please direct the police todrop the charges and end their harassment.Sincerely,Keith McHenry</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
