<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: March for Tibet's Independence, Philly to NY</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>MARCH FOR TIBET'S INDEPENDENCE, PHILLY TO NY</H3><PRE>check out our website <ahref="http://www.nuvo.net/tibet">http://www.nuvo.net/tibet</a> forupdatesSubject: Progress Report #2: March for Tibet's IndependenceDate: April 5, 1996 To: Tibet Supporters From: Larry Gerstein,Coordinator March for Tibet's Independence Re: Progress Report #2We have now walked about 225 miles & are close to the New Jersey border.Our core group currently consists of 6 Tibetans & 4 Americans. GesheMonlam from Philadelphia joined the walk a week ago & will complete the"March for Tibet's Independence." We are very happy to have Geshe-lawith us. He has been a great inspiration & has helped to increase ourlaughter level. Most days there are 11-13 individuals walking, withlarger numbers (15-20) on the weekend. Our weekend walkers have beenmainly Tibetans from the NYC area who have also greatly inspired us. Wewelcome more of you to join us on the weekends.Thus far, we have been extremely successful with the printed media.Local stories have appeared almost every day & the Baltimore Sun &Philadelphia Inquirer have also published articles. Hopefully, thenational news services & TV stations will pick up our story in the nearfuture.Our visit through Philadelphia was incredible. The members of theTibetan Buddhist Center in Philadelphia along with the US TIbetCommittee-Philadelphia strongly supported our visit & helped to make ita huge success. The Mayor of Philadelphia signed a very strongproclamation recognizing March 30, 1996 as "March for Tibet'sIndependence" day. As far as we know, this was the first time that aU.S. city clearly & openly supported Tibet's independence. Thisproclamation was timed with our demonstration at the Liberty Bell inPhiladelphia. Approximately 100 people (50+ Tibetans) participated inthis demonstration. Our visit to the Liberty Bell was quite moving as weall realized the significance of this symbol of freedom, justice, &independence to the world community.Our presentation at the University of Pennsylvania was also impactful.About 75 individuals including members of the press attended the talkgiven by Thubten Jigme Norbu, Palden Gyatso, & Larry Gerstein. Thediscussion after the presentation revealed that the audience was notonly sympathetic about the Tibetan situation, but also well informed.Next week we will give similar presentations at Trenton State University(April 10) & Princeton University (April 11).Plans for our arrival in NYC are being finalized by the Office of Tibet,the U.S. Tibet Committee, & Students for a Free Tibet. Our goal is tofill up the Staten Island Ferry on April 25 with Tibet Supporters. Weintend to take the ferry from the Staten Island Ferry Plaza at 9AM,arriving in Battery Park-NYC at 9:30AM. Since the Statue of Liberty issuch a powerful symbol of freedom & independence, we highly encourageall of you to join us. By filling up the ferry, we will definitelyattract the worldwide media. We will be greeted in Battery Park with abreakfast & will then walk to the United Nations up Broadway. As areminder, April 25th is Gendhun Choekyi Nyima's birthday & we willdemand that China release the 6 year old Panchen Lama. Therefore, amajor goal of our ferry ride & walk to the U.N. is to educate peopleabout the Panchen Rinpoche & call upon world leaders to secure hisrelease & safety.Once again, please note our new e-mail address (kmurphy@nuvo.net) &check out our website (http://www.nuvo.net/tibet) for updates. UntilWednesday morning April 10, we can be reached between 6PM-10PM at215-536-7772. If absolutely necessary, we can also be contacted between9AM-5PM on our cellular phone (301-452-7095).Rangzen!** End of text from cdp:pn.announcemen *****************************************************************************This material came from PeaceNet, a non-profit progressive networkingservice.  For more information, send a message topeacenet-info@igc.apc.org***************************************************************************</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
