<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Latest Workers Actions Around the World</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>LATEST WORKERS ACTIONS AROUND THE WORLD</H3><PRE>-------------------------Via Workers World News ServiceReprinted from the Apr. 4, 1996issue of Workers World newspaper-------------------------WORKERS AROUND THE WORLDARGENTINA: 100,000 PROTEST COUP CRIMESSome 100,000 Argentineans demonstrated in Buenos Aires on the 20thanniversary of the March 24, 1976, military coup that brought a terrorregime into power. That military government, with the open support ofthe U.S. government, "disappeared" at least 9,000 people. Most wererevolutionary young people, executed without a trial.Demonstrators sang, chanted and carried signs with photographs of thedisappeared. Some shouted insults at President Carlos Menem, who grantedamnesty to many of the officers accused of human-rights violations.PARAGUAY: PEASANTS DEMAND LAND REFORMOn March 15 some 40,000 peasants gathered in Paraguay's capital ofAsuncion to demand land reform. The protesters want the government toallow them to farm vacant land, guarantee prices for what they grow andseize the property of big landowners. Eight thousand police were broughtout to hold back the farmers."The government and congress have no answer for us," said Alberto Areco,president of the national Farm Workers' Organization. "Occupation is theonly solution." According to census figures, over 70 percent ofParaguay's farmers and farm workers live in extreme poverty.MEXICO: BUS WORKERS FIGHT TO REGAIN JOBSTwelve thousand bus drivers and other workers of Route 100 in MexicoCity have been fighting for 11 months to win back their jobs. As thefirst week of March ended, their union-- SUTAUR--began a new series ofconfrontations with the government. On March 6, over 1,000 SUTAURmembers began a sit- in in front of the offices of Mexico City'sappointed mayor. One of SUTAUR's legal team--Jorge Garcia--began ahunger strike in the doorway of the Federal District offices.At 2 a.m. March 7, the government sent 600 riot police to remove thesit-in. But during the day, around 3,000 workers came back and reclaimedthe area in front of the mayor's office. The next day over 5,000 workersdemonstrated there; another 3,000 came March 9. During the 340 dayssince the original firings, SUTAUR has carried out about 325mobilizations of its membership. On March 14 they took the area beforethe mayor's office again.INDONESIA: THREE DIE IN PROTESTS AT U.S. COPPER MINEThe Indonesian military deployed 2,800 soldiers in two remote towns inthe province of Irian Jaya March 14 after protests at a copper mineowned by U.S.-based capital resulted in at least three deaths and 15injuries.According to an Associated Press report, 3,000 villagers from around thesite of the Freeport Indonesia copper mine attacked shops, buildings andvehicles starting March 17 and damaged the airport control tower. WAHLI,an environmental group in Jakarta, Indonesia's capital, blamed securityguards for the violence.Indonesian security officials in Timika said people there returned towork after their representatives met with James Moffett, chairperson ofthe New Orleans-based U.S. Freeport-McMoran Copper and Gold, Inc., whichhas an 82-percent stake in Freeport Indonesia. According to an official,"Moffett promised to give more attention to the demands of theindigenous people who live in villages around the company." Thosedemands include respect for local customs and traditions, more jobopportunities and improvement of social and economic conditions for theindigenous people.Freeport-McMoran Copper and Gold recently signed a new contract with theIndonesian government to expand activity in Irian Jaya, the Western halfof New Guinea, the world's second largest island. The mining company isthe biggest in the province. It plans to extract 1.1 billion pounds ofcopper and 1.7 million ounces of gold in 1996. U.S.-based companies haveinvested heavily in Indonesia to exploit the rich natural resources andthe low-paid labor force. The U.S. capitalists count on repression fromthe Indonesian military government-- installed in a bloody U.S.-backedcoup in 1965--to keep the workers from challenging them.JAPAN: WORKERS DEMAND HIGHER PAYWorkers in Tokyo held the biggest demonstration in a year on March 2. Atleast 50,000 union members and their families gathered in Yoyogi Parkand marched to defend workers' rights.Jinnosuke Ashida, chairperson of the Japanese Trade Union Confederation(Rengo), spoke at the march. "We must fulfill our demand, improve theworkers' livelihood restrained by the prolonged recession and revitalizethe economy," he told the rally. Other union leaders said there could bestrikes if management fails to meet their demands. Earlier that week,leaders of the steel workers' union said they were preparing to strikefor the first time in 25 years.Japan's unemployment rate is low compared to the United States andWestern Europe--that is, the other imperialist countries. But at 3.4percent, it's at the highest level since 1953. Japanese companies arebeginning to abandon their earlier policies of practically guaranteeingjobs and are beginning--though so far less drastically than in theUnited States--to downsize. They are demanding higher production fromboth labor and their managerial staff as a condition for keeping jobs.AUSTRIA: STUDENTS PROTEST EDUCATION CUTBACKSIn an extraordinary gathering, tens of thousands of university studentsfilled the streets of downtown Vienna March 14 to protest the newgovernment's plan to cut spending on education. The protest was thethird that week against the cuts. It forced Vienna University to suspendclasses. The cutback plan eliminates free public transportation forstudents and limits their scholarships. It also reduces payments made toparents of students. The students say that if the cuts go through itwill force many of them out of the university.The chairperson of the Austrian Students' Union, Agnes Berlakovich, said90,000 would lose public transport rights and 30,000 would lose familyallowances, $220 per month for one child. Faculty, staff and even therectors of the three universities in Vienna took part in the protests.CZECH REPUBLIC: 130,000 HEALTH WORKERS TO STRIKEAll the main doctors' and health-care workers' unions plan to strikeMarch 25 and 26 to express long-simmering discontent in the CzechRepublic's health service. Some 130,000 nurses, lab technicians, doctorsand other hospital staff will be involved. According to a report inPostmark Prague, doctor militancy over pay has turned into a generalbattle over the pay of all health workers and the general crisis in thehealth service.The union representing the health-care workers, OSZSP, is demandingchanges in the system of financing health care, including heavysubsidies to avert a collapse of the system. It also asks a 40-percentpay increase "to alleviate the exploitation of health workers."The Czech Communist Party says that while the strike plans reflectgrowing social discontent, the problems of the health service cannot beresolved by industrial action on pay issues alone. The KSCM calls for apolitical solution, one in which health care again becomesoverwhelmingly the responsibility of the government.Before the collapse of socialist Czechoslovakia, high- quality healthcare was free.--John CatalinottoBOSNIA: PENTAGON COST OVERRUNSSending U.S. troops to Bosnia is going to be another "cost-overrun" itemon the already super-bloated Pentagon budget. But don't expect to see alot of bad press about "bungling bureaucrats" and "incompetent"government employees.Unnamed Army officials warned the Associated Press that the cost ofdeploying 27,000 troops to the Balkans will be much higher thanexpected, perhaps by as much as $529 million--18 percent more than theoriginal Pentagon estimate of $2.5 billion.That's over $3 billion for the U.S. war machine.The Army had to hire civilian contractors to perform engineering tasks.And support services, like housing, cooking and laundry. It also neededhelp building a bridge over the Sava River. These businesses, operatingin a war zone, "charged more than expected," said the Army sources. Inaddition, they said, the German railroads that handle the transport inand out of Hungary might charge twice as much to return the U.S. troopsfrom Bosnia through Hungary back to their bases in Germany than they didto take them from Germany to Bosnia.Of course, the Pentagon will be more than happy to kick up U.S.taxpayers' dough.HAITI: WORLD BANK FORCES PRIVATIZATIONUnder pressure from the World Bank, which is sitting on $100 million ofaid for Haiti, President Rene Preval announced a plan to privatize mostof the modern, efficient state-owned enterprises. The four industriestargeted are the telephone company, the electricity company, the flourmill and a cement plant with the capacity to supply most of theCaribbean.The government admitted that half of the 12,000 people who work forthese companies would lose their jobs in the first six months of privateownership.At a union-sponsored international conference held in Port- au-Prince afew days before Preval's announcement, Haitian economist CamilleChalmers said, "A structural adjustment policy is catastrophic, aboveall for the popular classes. It ... destroys the productive sectors ofthe economy."Preval is trying to win support from Haitian peasants by promising themmoney from privatization sales. Gesner Jean- Phillipe of the UnionCollective against Privatization said this is demagogy. "The U.S. willdestroy the Haitian peasant economy by dumping cheap U.S. agriculturalproducts, like rice and sugar, on the market."Chalmers predicted, "Many peasants will have to leave their land to gobegging in the cities."--G. Dunkel- END -(Copyright Workers World Service: Permission to reprint granted ifsource is cited. For more information contact Workers World, 55 W. 17St., NY, NY 10011; via e-mail: ww@wwpublish.com. For subscription infosend message to: ww-info@wwpublish.com. Web: <a href="http://www.workers.org">http://www.workers.org</a></PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
