<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: UCSD Civil Disobedience March 12</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>UCSD CIVIL DISOBEDIENCE MARCH 12</H3><PRE>First of all a disclaimer:  I am not a UC San Diego student.UC San Diego held an incredible rally, march and civil disobedienceyesterday, March 12th.  The issues of the event focussed on regearingour strategies to defeat the anti-affirmative action California CivilRights Initiative.  This change of strategy is necessary for UC studentswho have been in the struggle to maintain affirmative action on theircampuses for over a year now.  Individually, my thoughts were on theissues of prison and police spending (and military or is that redundant)vs. cuts to the educational system.  Read on to further understand myown focus...Approximately 300 students participated during the march which overtookan intersection at La Jolla Village Drive.  In all 18 students werearrested under the charge of failure to disperse and underwent adeliberately slow booking process lasting approximately 10 hours.  Wewere all released at approximately 3 am this morning under our ownrecognizance.Both the undergraduate and the graduate student body presidents and thechair of the UC student association were among the students arrested.The UC San Diego students were: Jeff Corbett, Naomi Faulk, MelanieDeLaCruz, Felicia Duenas, Gabriela Juarez, Benoni Pantoja, Jose Arinega,Steve Dubb, Jay Chevalier, Ingrid Benedict, Gabriel Gutierrez, RosioO'Campo, Jaqulyn, Lorna and Rosa (my apologies as the last names for thelast three listed are unavailable at this second: no disrespectintended).2 UC Riverside students participated including myself and Lilia Garcia.Kris Kohler from UC Santa Barbara also took part.This event was well organized from all angles and received extensive andfavorable media coverage in the San Diego area.  A diverse base ofsupport was present at this event (there were even College Democrats atthis rally for a change).Good luck to all of you on March 14th.  My thoughts are split betweenwishing everyone the best and my imminent paper deadlines :).  I lookforward to campus reports from every participating college.  Like I saidUC San Diego has set the standard, as well as, the stage for tomorrow'ssuccess.Damian Tryon///UCR, 224 Costo Hall///Office: 909/787-3624 or4143////////// ///////////////Riverside, CA 92521///Fax:(909)787-MELT///////////////////</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
