<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Wal-Mart Rally Energizes Foes, March 7</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>WAL-MART RALLY ENERGIZES FOES, MARCH 7</H3><PRE>[Excerpts from an article by Christine Neuberger, TIMES-DISPATCHstaff writer, in the RICHMOND TIMES-DISPATCH, March 3, 1996: C1+]Plans to build a Wal-Mart store next to George Washington's boyhood homedrew more than 350 people to a protest rally yesterday.Speakers railed at the giant retailer and warned that the project wouldhave dire effects on the historic site and nearby small businesses.The rally culminated with high school baseball players competing in acoin-hurling contest to re-create Washington's legendary toss of asilver dollar across the Rappahannock River.The rally, at Ferry Farm in Stafford County, seemed to energizeopponents, whose protests have drawn national news coverage.But Wal-Mart insists it won't drop plans for the 93,000-square- footstore. The nation's largest retailer said the project is welcomed bycounty leaders.Chilly weather failed to cool the enthusiasm of protesters. A few woreperiod dress. Many carried sign bearing messages such as, "No Wal-MartBy George."The sharpest barbs were thrown by Al Norman, a national crusader againsturban sprawl."I like to compare Wal-Mart to a cheap pair of underwear," Norman said."They keep creeping up on you."Wal-Mart has stores in Spotsylvania County just west of Fredericksburgand in northern Stafford County. Norman said the area doesn't need athird."The message to Wal-Mart is, you've got 1,990 stores in America, butthere's only one Ferry Farm," he said.Supporters say the area needs the revenue, jobs and shoppingopportunities.Jack Warren, a University of Virginia faculty member, said he believesWal-Mart's plans must be resisted because Ferry Farm is one of thenation's most important landmarks.Washington weathered adversity as his boyhood home, Warren said."Without the lessons learned at this place, the country as we know itwould not exist."The original house burned, but the cellar has been found.According to legend, Washington chopped down his father's cherry tree atFerry Farm, and it was there that he tossed a coin across theRappahannock River.A fife and drum corps led 11 high school baseball players to theriverbank for the tossing contest yesterday.So far, 45 communities have successfully fought Wal-Mart's arrival,including Warrenton [Virginia] and Williamsburg."We've got to make this company realize they're trashing the history ofAmerica," said Bill Beck, president of the Historic FredericksburgFoundation, his voice cracking with emotion.The project needs approval from the county administration and the countyArchitectural Review Board.-----------------------------------------------------------------------U.S. McLibel Support Campaign                              Press OfficePO Box 62                                        Phone/Fax 802-586-9628Craftsbury VT 05826-0062                    Email dbriars@world.std.com-----------------------------------------------------------------------http://www.mcspotlight.org/http://www.interlog.com/eye/Misc/McLibelhttp://student.uq.edu.au:80/~s002434/mcl.html-----------------------------------------------------------------------To subscribe to the "mclibel" listserve, send email     To: majordomo@world.std.comSubject: <not needed>Message: subscribe mclibelTo unsubscribe, change the body to "unsubscribe mclibel"</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
