<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Latest Loggin Actions</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>LATEST LOGGIN ACTIONS</H3><PRE>LOGGING WITHOUT LAWS BULLETIN #41, from WAFC, the Western AncientForest Campaign.  Call (202)789-2844x288 or email WAFCDC@igc.apc.orgMonday, February 26, 1996, the 216th Day of Lawless LoggingCLINTON TACKLES RIDER: President Clinton pledged again to "fix" the"logging without laws" rider during his visit to Seattle Saturday, butdid not announce a decision about whether to support total repeal of therider or not.  Coverage in the Washington Post yesterday said thatClinton's announcement was an "election year turnabout" in a state"crucial to his hopes to winning a second term."  Clinton and his pressspokesman Mike McCurry spoke clearly to his interest in repealing the"green" portions of the rider affecting Section 318 and Option 9 sales,but were vague about total repeal.  The White House is believed to befollowing closely the lead of Sen. Patty Murray (D- WA) who told a groupof her constituents last week that she supported repeal of the rider butalso wanted a "salvage program" which might expedite salvage salespassed in its place.  A group of over 1000 forest supporters rallied inWestlake Park in downtown Seattle during the President's visit,displaying a 35 foot inflated chain saw and signs saying "Clinton Repealthe Clearcut Deal."RIDER REPEAL CALL IN TUESDAY:  The beginning of the eighth month ofclearcutting under the "forest health" rider will observed by activiststoday, as they conduct a National Repeal the Rider Call- In Day to floodthe Congress with phone calls urging support for rider repeallegislation.  The Congress is returning to Washington today after a"district work period" which has kept them out of town for most of themonth.  Cosponsorship of the Furse bill to repeal the rider, HR 2745,has climbed to 110 with the addition of Reps. Bill Coyne (D-PA), TomCampbell (R-CA), Peter Visclosky (D-IN), and Martin Frost (D-TX).  It isanticipated that Sens. Bill Bradley (D- NJ) and Barbara Boxer (D-CA)will file their companion bill in the Senate this week or next.TIM REAM ON THE ROAD:  A road show featuring Eugene OR hunger strikerTim Ream and his message about how citizens can get involved to save ournation's Ancient Forests from industrial logging and the Timber ClearcutRider has completed stops in Salt Lake, Boulder CO, and Denver and playsin Kansas City, MO, tonight. A crowd of 150 at Boulder is his biggest sofar.  Tim is using slides and video to tell listeners about his 75 dayhunger strike outside the Eugene OR federal building against "loggingwithout laws" and the threat that the Rescissions Act timber rider posesto native forests. Future stops include St. Louis, Indianapolis,Cincinnati, Lexington KY, Nashville TN, Atlanta, Columbia SC, RaleighNC, and Richmond VA.  For details call WAFC at (202)789-2844x291.FOREST CONGRESS CLOSES:  The 1200 participants in the 7th AmericanForest Congress finished their business Saturday and went home,approving principles that endorsed the rule of law and rights ofcitizens to appeal FS decisions, but rejecting the direct repeal of the"logging without laws" rider.  "The raging debate over the logging billdominated much of the forest meeting, even though the organizers hadsaid from the outset that the issue should be off- limits," wrote JackCushman of the New York Times.  Cushman said that the Forest Congresswas held "in the middle of a fierce fight over a law that the U.S.Congress passed . . to encourage accelerated logging on public lands." The leadership of the Forest Congress rejected the argument that the"participatory" ideals of their meeting were contradicted by the realityof the logging rider.** End of text from cdp:headlines *****************************************************************************This material came from PeaceNet, a non-profit progressive networkingservice.  For more information, send a message topeacenet-info@igc.apc.org***************************************************************************</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
