<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Radical Basque Separatists Flock To Rally</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>RADICAL BASQUE SEPARATISTS FLOCK TO RALLY</H3><PRE>    SAN SEBASTIAN, Spain, Feb 24 (Reuter) - Radical Basqueseparatists flocked to an election rally in northern Spain on Saturdayin angry solidarity with Herri Batasuna (HB), the political wing ofguerrilla group ETA.The rally was delayed for an hour as more than 36,000 HB supporterscrammed into San Sebastian's soccer stadium, which has a nominalcapacity of 30,000.Five masked people burned the stadium's Spanish and French flags as thecrowd chanted ``Long live militant ETA'' and held up a banner with ETAlogo covering an entire section of the stands.The crowd became even rowdier, hooting and shouting ``Jon Askastu''(Free Jon), after seeing a videotaped comment by HB spokesman JonIdigoras who was arrested last week on a charge of collaborating with anarmed band.A high court judge detained Idigoras for refusing to answer questionsabout an HB campaign video featuring ETA (Basque Homeland and Freedom)members and defending violence as means for achieving an independentBasque state.ETA has fought a guerrilla war for the past 27 years, killing about 800people. It claimed responsibility for one of two recent high-profilekillings that have sparked demonstrations across Spain calling for anend to terrorism.The Socialist government, which has tried unsuccessfully in the past tosanction HB, said the video could provide grounds to outlaw the party,widely seen as the political arm of ETA.HB won two parliamentary seats in the last elections and has the supportof about 15 percent of voters in the Basque region.``The big message of the day has been that ETA still has the power toattract the biggest crowds in the Basque region,'' a Basque radiojournalist told Reuters. ``The arrest of Idigoras prompted these crowds.It was a big electoral advantage for HB.''Security forces in San Sebastian were geared up for possible violenceafter the rally. Three people were injured late in the day when theytried to stop a group of masked people setting fire to a bus.A group of young HB sympathisers in San Sebastian staged acounter-demonstration earlier directly in front of a weekly gathering ofsupporters of Basque businessman Jose Maria Aldaya, kidnapped by ETA 292days ago.Public Works Minister Jose Borrell was among those calling for hisrelease. Baton-wielding police intervened to avert a confrontaton.----- End of forwarded message from Neighborhood Queen -----</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
