<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: 101 Arrested In Logging Demonstration Feb. 17</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>101 ARRESTED IN LOGGING DEMONSTRATION FEB. 17</H3><PRE>I wanted to give you a brief account of a rally we had up here onthe road to the Rocky timber sale on the east side of the OlympicPeninsula. About 300 people turned out in the pouring rain for the Feb.17 rally to protest the rider at the Forest Service road closure on theRocky Brook road. People circled up and spoke their minds about therider, its consequences, and our kinship and connection to ancientforests. Ben White of Friends of Animals, who had just concluded atree-sit in the sale, addressed the gathering and ended by invitingpeople to join him in crossing into the closed area to visit the trees.It was a powerful sight to see people calmly streaming across theclosure boundary. Officers made 101 arrests. The rally and mass civildisobedience was the latest in a series of actions at Rocky that hadbegun over a week before including blockades and the tree-sit.Rocky is a Section 318 sale that had been designated a late successionalreserve under Clinton's Option 9 Forest Plan. The trees are 200-250+years old on very steep slopes. They began falling last Monday, Feb. 12.David Atcheson, Pacific Crest Biodiversity Project bf633@scn.org</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
