<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Pastors Break Cuba Embargo Again</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>PASTORS BREAK CUBA EMBARGO AGAIN</H3><PRE>February 17, 1996                  ORGANIZERS ASK:  WHY IS THE U.S. SPENDING TAX DOLLARS TO STOP MEDICALAID TO CUBAN CHURCHES?San Ysidro CA/ Highgate VT-- 300 Pastors for Peace caravan volunteersgathered Saturday morning at San Ysidro to take medical aid to Cuba andto challenge the US blockade of the Cuban people.. In a joint effort,150 people congregated in Highgate, Vermont with medical aid includingcomputers.Despite a massive police presence, the caravanistas demonstrated a firmcommitment to deliver the medical cargo to their Cuban neighbors. Pastors for Peace volunteers walked across the border carrying boxes ofmedical aid, two weeks after  Federal officers had met them withexcessive force and confiscated 325 computers.Many enthusiastic bystanders spontaneously joined in the action, pickingup boxes of aid and carrying them across the border.  US Customs allowedhundreds of boxes of medical aid and supplies including computer partsto cross.  However, agents seized 35 c omputers in San Diego and 35 morein Vermont although Pastors for Peace assured authorities that thecomputers would be used for an medical information system."These computers are medical aid just as much as a box of aspirins orsutures," said Dr. Juan Reardon of Project INFOMED. "The US governmentis willing to spend money on computer technology to try to subvert Cuba;but today they spent thousands of taxpayers' dollars to stop us frombringing computers to be used in family clinics and hospitals."Monday, IFCO/Pastors for Peace will announce plans for continuingstrategy to free the computers still being held by the US TreasuryDepartment."The children of Israel had to walk around the city of Jericho seventimes before the walls came tumbling down," said Rev. Lucius Walker,Jr., Director of the Interrereligious Foundation for CommunityOrganization, which organizes the Pastors for Peace caravans. "We'llwalk back to this border wall as many times as we need to until theblockade against our Cuban brothers and sisters comes tumbling down.CONTACT: IFCO-PASTORS FOR PEACE(612) 870-7121, (212) 926-5757In San Diego:  (612) 291-9648</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
