<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Workers Actions Around The World</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>WORKERS ACTIONS AROUND THE WORLD</H3><PRE>VENEZUELAYouths fight fare hikeStudents at Caracas Luis Caballero Mejias technical college foughtpolice Feb. 3 with slingshots and Molotov cocktails. It was the latestflare-up in an ongoing battle between Venezuela's many poor people andthe government. According to the Associated Press, there were threeother clashes in Caracas that day. This one was sparked by an attempt toquadruple bus fares for students.The students won the skirmish when the wind changed and blew tear gasand acrid smoke away from the dormitories and down toward the massedpolice.During the past few years workers and poor people in Caracas have risenin rebellion against declining living conditions, only to be suppressedbrutally by the army and police. Now the state has again mobilized theseforces to stop protests during Pope John Paul II's visit the second weekof February.Unions call general strikeOn Feb. 6, Venezuelan government workers called for a general strike.Union leaders told thousands of demonstrators that they expect 700,000workers in 366 unions nationwide to take part. There are 1.2 millionpublic service workers in all.With 11 percent official unemployment, and with the minimum wage theequivalent of $52 per month after three years of recession, workerscan't afford even small increases in the cost of living. But the priceof food has doubled since late 1995. Prices for chicken and eggs rose 38percent and 46 percent respectively in January alone. Pay stayed thesame.The disastrous decline in living standards has led to massive workerresistance. As January ended, unions protested to demand a raise in theminimum wage and against social-security cutbacks. On Jan. 31, doctorsdemonstrated for back pay.The government is expected to announce a new minimum wage with anincrease of 167 percent.MEXICOThousands block Pemex oil pollutionSome 5,000 people in the southeastern state of Tabasco began blockingaccess to dozens of government-owned Pemex oil wells in late January.Under the leadership of activists with the liberal-opposition DemocraticRevolution Party, the protesters used tree trunks and their own bodiesto block at least 36 oil wells. They demanded that the Mexicangovernment use more of the oil profits to fund services and developmentin impoverished communities in Tabasco. They also aimed to spotlightPemex's pollution, which they say is hurting crops and people.On Feb. 2, the Mexican government moved troops in against theprotesters; officials said they had thus reopened 51 oil wells.PERUOil workers strikeWorkers in the state-owned Petroperu oil company went out on strike Feb.1 in the port city of Talara to protest plans to privatize. PresidentAlberto Fujimori's regime immediately moved in the army to surround therefinery and other company property. Union leaders say the refinery isshut down. They say privatization will cost 1,200 jobs--and so they willcall a national strike if the government goes ahead with its plans. OnFeb. 6, some 2,200 Petroperu workers in Lima and the northeastern junglejoined the strike, closing down more refineries and a pipeline thattakes oil to Occidental Petroleum, a U.S.-based oil company.NICARAGUAStudents occupy gov't buildingPolice stormed the Foreign Ministry building in Managua on Jan. 31 todislodge 500 students who had occupied it two days earlier. The studentsdemanded that the government use 6 percent of the 1996 government budgetfor university education. They held Foreign Minister Ernesto Leal andsome diplomats in the building with them.Police arrested 107 students, including the president of the NicaraguanNational Students' Union, Julio Orozco.From 1979 to 1990, Nicaragua was led by the revolutionary SandinistaNational Liberation Front, which had overthrown the U.S.-backed Somozadictatorship. Washington then waged war against the Nicaraguan people bybacking counter-revolutionary terrorists. Worn down by this 10-year-longwar, the Nicaraguans voted in a U.S.- backed regime in 1990. Since then,economic conditions for Nicaraguan workers and peasants havedeteriorated further. A presidential election is set for next Oct. 20.DENMARKSolidarity strike in CopenhagenSome 3,000 slaughterhouse, brewery and sanitation workers walked out fora one-day strike Jan. 31 in Copenhagen to demand the garbage collectors'union chief, Louie Andersen, be reinstated. The bosses fired Andersen inDecember after he called a walkout to protest their decision to makegarbage collectors work more than 37 hours per week. A strike by theseworkers in Aarhus has left garbage on the streets since Dec. 27.BELGIUMWorkers ground national airlineThe bosses of Sabena, Belgium's national airline, wanted to cancel 50labor-management agreements, extend working hours and freeze salaries.On Feb. 6, Sabena's workers met that threat with a 24-hour strike thatcanceled all flights. A coalition of unions representing all airlineworkers called the action, which opens up a new round of struggleagainst management's offensive.                         - END -(Copyright Workers World Service: Permission to reprint granted ifsource is cited. For more information contact Workers World, 55 W. 17St., NY, NY 10011; via e-mail: ww@wwpublish.com. For subscription infosend message to: ww-info@wwpublish.com. Web: <a href="http://www.workers.org.html">http://www.workers.org</a></PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
