<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Yale Strike II</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>YALE STRIKE II</H3><PRE>Thu, Feb. 8To Friends of the Yale unions:At 6:00 this morning, picket lines went up across the Yale campus as theUniversity's clerical workers walked off the job in the face of demandsfor drastic cutbacks in wages, health insurance and job security.  UnionLocal 34, representing 2,600 Yale secretaries, librarians, labtechnicians and health care workers, went out on strike after twiceextending its contract deadline in hopes of reaching an agreement withthe University.I know that many of you on this e-mail list initially became interestedin the particular issues surrounding the graduate teachers' strike here,and may feel less interested in a conflict which doesn't directlyinvolve teaching staff or questions of academic freedom.  For those ofus here, however, the TA strike and today's strike are part of the samestruggle.  The three unions here -- GESO, Local 34, and Local 35(service and maintenance workers) -- are formally allied together. Moreimportant, we all face the same kind of bullying and threats, and thesame attempts by administrators to prevent others from sharing in Yale'swealth or having a meaningful say over their work conditions here.Today's strike is over Yale's demands for cutbacks:  - Cutting the wagesof new dining hall workers by almost $4/hr, and making them intoseasonal workers who are laid off for 20 weeks a year.  This cut is theaverage dining hall worker's salary from $23,000 to $10,000 per year. -Cutting the health benefits of retirees by 40%.  The average New Havenretiree, after working at Yale for 25 years, will effectively have theirretirement package cut from roughly $500 to $350 per month. - Cuttingunion jobs by bringing in outside contractors to fill new job openings. Over ten years, this would cut the number of unionized workers by 40%.The ugliness of Yale's proposals is made even clearer when you look atthe relative wealth of Yale compared to New Haven.  Yale is the secondrichest school in the country, with a $4.5 billion endowment which earnsa profit (after inflation and after all expenses) of roughly $1 milliona day.  By contrast, the 1980 census ranked New Haven the 7th poorestcity in America, and the economy only gotten worse since then. Yale isthe city's biggest employer; 1 in 7 New Haven jobs is a Yale job.  Forus, this means that defending the ability to earn a minimally decentliving at Yale is critically important.  For Yale administrators, thenear-monopoly in the labor market is taken as an opportunity to forcemore and more people into low-wage, no-benefit, "permanent temp"positions, knowing that there are few options for people to goelsewhere.In the past few months, clerical and service workers have been subjectto threats similar to those which graduate teachers faced.  Workers havebeen reprimanded, suspended and, in one case, fired for talking to otherYale employees about the union.  When clerical staff attempted to telltemp workers about their right to join the union, Yale police evictedthem from the building.  The union has charged Yale with nearly 20separate cases of violating federal labor law, but this has not changedthe administration's tactics.While GESO is not now on strike, TAs have moved their classes intooff-campus coffee houses, churches and movie theaters in order to honorpicket lines, and have urged faculty to do likewise.  As of today,nearly half of all Yale classes have been moved off campus.But faculty face significant pressures from the administration.  Inaddition to the obvious, implicit worry of alienating administrators,faculty have been told explicitly that crossing picket lines is a matterof administrative policy rather than individual conscience.  On Jan. 24,Provost Alison Richard (alison.richard@yale.edu) issued a memo tofaculty stating that "I expect that, in the event of a strike, thefaculty will continue to meet classes on campus, and in the designatedclassroom."  Psychology Dept chair Tom Carew (thomas.carew@yale.edu)told one junior faculty member that she would be in "open defiance" ofuniversity authority -- the same charge levelled against TAs forwithholding grades -- if she did not cross picket lines.  In addition,many faculty have been told that Yale's liability insurance will notcover off-campus classes, i.e. if students get hit by a car on the wayto relocated classes the professor will be personally liable fordamages.  This threat may well be illegal, and has not yet been put inwriting, but it has been widely circulated and has undoubtedlyinfluenced some faculty.  Many faculty are honoring picket lines despitethis, but faculty remain subject to a climate of continuous pressure.From what we can tell, the administration's strategy seems to be tostarve us out, gambling that they can outlast a strike and force workersto accept lousy contracts.  In response, we have developed a strategy inwhich each group on campus has a particular part to play in pressuringthe university to settle fair contracts.  The clerical workers are outon strike for four weeks beginning today and running through thebeginning of spring break.  During that time, the 1,100 members of Local35 will remain at work, providing moral and financial support for thoseon strike, and reserving the right to strike later in the semester.  Wehope that the contracts will be settled soon, but we are prepared for along struggle.As during the grade strike, there is an important role for academicsupporters outside Yale.  Letters to the president(richard.levin@yale.edu, copied to this account) are still useful, butthere are things to do beyond that, too.  If you are a Yale alum, we askthat you withhold any contributions to the university until thecontracts are settled.  If you are planning to attend an event here,please contact us (203-624-5161) to have it rescheduled to an off-campussite.  If Yale big-shots are coming to your campus, let us know so thatthey can be greeted appropriately.  We know of plans for the Yalepresident and top administrators to visit Los Angeles, Washington DC,New York and Chicago in the next two months.  If you are in one of thosecities and can help get our message out, we need you. Finally, we have asignificant number of people who live paycheck-to-paycheck who are nowgoing without any paycheck at all.  We are raising contributions fromour own members to guarantee that no one loses their mortgage, has theirheat turned off, etc.  If you can contribute to this effort, checksshould go to the FUE Strike Fund, c/o Federation of UniversityEmployees, 425 College St., New Haven, CT 06511.  Anything you can offerwill be greatly appreciated.We will be setting up a web page in the coming week, and will advertisethat address for regular updates.  Otherwise, if you have any questionsabout what's going on here, feel free to contact us at any time. Again,thanks so much for your support.Gordon Lafer, Research DirectorFederation of University Employees</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
