<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: LA Auto Show Protest Against Mitsubishi</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>LA AUTO SHOW PROTEST AGAINST MITSUBISHI</H3><PRE>It's Auto Show Time AgainThe 1996 auto show season is off to a fashionable start. The idea thisyear was to stay with the agreement, made to Mitsubishi Motor Sale ofAmerica, not to commit civil disobedience as we did so successfully inthe past. The following is a description about the LA auto show andsuggestions about how to approach the show in your neighborhood. Goodluck!T-Shirts a Big Hit at LA Auto Show!For this year's auto show protest, activists form UCLA RAG, LARainforest Action Project and LA RAN showed up at the Mitsubishi autoshow display wearing black t-shirts that boldly stated on the front,"Boycott Mitsubishi, Mitsubishi Destroys Rainforests" and on the back,"Save the Rainforest, Boycott Mitsubishi."On the opening day, twenty-five activists-accompanied by two legalobservers-stood around the Mitsubishi exhibit for several hours, boldlycalling attention to Mitsubishi's rainforest destruction.Hundreds of potential Mitsubishi car buyers got the message and many ofthem approached the t-shirt clad activists for more information.Needless to say, Mitsubishi and the LA Auto Show Security were not happyabout any of this, and on the following day they decided to throw us outof the exhibit!On the closing weekend, things got really dramatic. Saturday they threwus out again. When asked why, security admitted, on camera, that thereason was because of what we were wearing. This was, of course, totallyunconstitutional, as well as a civil rights violation. The media filmedus being unconstitutionally, and roughly, denied entry to the show onthe closing day. Mitsubishi was not happy with this coverage, whichaired on two television and two radio stations.So wearing the shirts was a fun and effective way to get the word aroundabout Mitsubishi Corporation's forest destruction and it was an easy,straightforward way to do it-great media potential with no complicatedcivil disobedience. It really helps a lot to get legal observers, andalso to have someone with a video camera, if possible. If you areallowed to stray inside, it's probably less of a press story, but thenyou're still right in Mitsubishi's face, warning off all theirprospective buyers. Distributing leaflets inside is a murky area of thelaw (at least in California), so if you're interested in a clear legaltest of your constitutional and civil rights, we suggest you justleaflet in the lobbies or outside.If you would like to borrow some t-shirts or the 35' inflatable chainsawfor the auto show when it comes to your area, contact Becky at RAN.International Day of ActionSpring is fast approaching and it's time to start thinking about someaction. Last October, in San Francisco, we had an extremely successfulaction, which is still making the media today, and we want to see moreof this. We're thinking about March or April for the action date. Giveus a call with any of your ideas and we'll be calling you about thespecific dates and targets. Keep in mind that our targets are the Banks,the Corporation and dealers of Heavy Industry. We really need tomobilize keeping the pressure on Mitsubishi is crucial at this point inthe campaign.Save the Rainforest with Poems of Good WillMitsubishi pleaseYou are killing plants and treesLet them live in peace.       QJason Heilig, Age 10</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
