<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Peltier Demonstrations Across The Country</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>PELTIER DEMONSTRATIONS ACROSS THE COUNTRY</H3><PRE>Via Workers World News ServiceReprinted from the Feb.22, 1996issue of Workers World newspaperBy MahtowinTwenty years ago, American Indian Movement warrior Leonard Peltier wasarrested, framed by the FBI for the murder of two FBI agents. This year,hundreds of activists around the country picketed FBI offices on Feb. 6to show their support for Peltier and to condemn the U.S. government forkeeping him behind bars.From Seattle to Houston; from Red Bank, N.J., to San Francisco; frommajor cities like New York to small towns like State College,Pa.--activists raised one main demand: "Free Leonard Peltier now!"Bill May of the Leonard Peltier Defense Committee told Workers World:"Leonard was very pleased with the actions. He thought it was a greatidea that we were out there."Peltier is a Lakota/Chippewa and a leading activist with the AmericanIndian Movement. In 1975, the FBI laid siege to the Pine RidgeReservation in South Dakota. During the FBI attack, two cops werekilled.Peltier was convicted of the killings after cops and FBI agents withheldevidence and threatened witnesses into lying on the witness stand. Theoriginal prosecutors now admit that they have no idea who actuallykilled the two cops.Despite documentation of the government frame-up-- including FBI recordsobtained through the Freedom of Information Act--courts have ruledagainst granting Peltier a new trial.Some of the bigger demonstrations on Feb. 6 took place in New England.In Springfield, Mass., over 100 people braved zero-degree temperaturesto demand Peltier's freedom. Participants in the multinational event,initiated by the Western Massachusetts National People's Campaign,distributed petitions calling for a presidential clemency order.In Boston, speakers from the United American Indians of New Englandaddressed the crowd of 150 people, calling for "all justice-lovingpeople from the four directions to rise up and demand that the FBI admitto their misconduct and let Leonard Peltier walk free once again."In Tampa, Fla., Peltier's supporters held a guerrilla street theateraction. A man dressed as an FBI agent symbolically shot "Lady Justice."In Milwaukee, a picket line initiated by the American Indian Movementand the Job is a Right Campaign linked the call for Peltier's freedomwith the demand for freedom for Mumia Abu-Jamal, an African Americanjournalist and activist facing the death penalty in Pennsylvania.At many activities around the country, a solidarity statement fromWorkers World Party presidential and vice- presidential candidatesMonica Moorehead and Gloria La Riva was warmly received. The statementcalls for "the immediate release of all political prisoners being heldhostage by the U.S. government."Monica Moorehead took part in the New York action Feb. 6.</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
