<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Perched Protester Prevents Logging Of Ancient Forest</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/repsban.gif" ALT="Reports" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>PERCHED PROTESTER PREVENTS LOGGING OF ANCIENT FOREST</H3><PRE>News Release Friday, February 2, 1996Contact: Karen Wood, (541)846-6366, kwood@igc.apc.orgForest protection activist ascends 21-foot-high tripod to block loggingroad at Hoxie Griffin.Before sunrise today, about 20 forest protection activists erected a 21-foot-high tripod in the middle of the logging access road to the Hoxie-Griffin timber sale, approximately 20 miles from Ashland, Oregon. (TakeDead Indian Point Road, on the east side of the southernmost I-5 exit toAshland, about 16 miles to the action site.) One of the activists nowsits perched at the top of the three-pole structure, risking personalinjury in order to prevent further logging of ancient forest here. The"tripod-sitter" is a young woman who prefers not to give her name to themedia at this time."I can't just stand by and watch ancient forests falling any longer,"stated the tripod-sitter before her ascent. "What will we tell thechildren?" One of her supporters at the site, Colin Jerwood fromAshland, blames the President and Congress for the continued logging ofancient forest. "The recent passage of the 'Logging Without Laws' riderhas declared open season on what remains of ancient forests and roadlessareas on public lands," he declared.The Hoxie-Griffin timber sale is located on federal land managed by theBureau of Land Management, directly next to the Pacific Crest Trail.After improvements were made to the sale to try to mitigate the damageof logging by protecting some of the largest trees, the "Logging WithoutLaws" rider (also referred to as the "timber salvage rider", Public Law104-19, section 2001) demanded that the sale be offered according to the"original terms and conditions" of the sale.** End of text from cdp:headlines *****************************************************************************This material came from PeaceNet, a non-profit progressive networkingservice.  For more information, send a message topeacenet-info@igc.apc.org***************************************************************************</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
