<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Demonstrate for Guatemala at Democratic Convention</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/notiban.gif" ALT="Notices" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Demonstrate for Guatemala at Democratic Convention</H3><PRE>Dear Guatemala press recipients:
To date, I have resisted the temptation of sending you information
on topics not directly related to Guatemala, so please forgive me
in advance for taking advantage of a captive audience.
Please pass this message on to anyone you think may be interested.
Regards,
Anthony

                             A Call for Action
                                DEMONSTRATE
                                  at the
                      DEMOCRATIC NATIONAL CONVENTION
                               August 26-29
                  at the United Center, Chicago, Illinois

Join us to speak out against the Democrats' platform on criminal
"justice."  Our demands are:
1.  EXPOSE AND OPPOSE THE RACISM AND CLASSISM OF THE CRIMINAL
"JUSTICE" SYSTEM.
    The U.S. has a legacy of racism towards Native Americans,
African Americans and Latinos.  Currently, one of the most blatant
forms of racism is the millions of Blacks and Latino people,
particularly youth, who are arrested, prosecuted, and persecuted.
One out of three Black men is in jail, on probation or parole.
Under federal law 50 grams of crack gets a mandatory 10-year, no-
parole sentence and the defendants are 92 percent Black.  For power
cocaine, the same drug -- used primarily by whites -- 5,000 grams
is needed for the same sentence.
     In addition, we denounce the classist nature of prisons, which
are disproportionately filled with poor people.  We also denounce
the frightening increase in Capital Punishment and the growing
restrictions on appeals by persons on death row.
     We live in a country where prison officials have reintroduced
chain gangs.  Although they attempt to justify this cruel and
humiliating punishment as an example of "tough love," we condemn it
as inhumane and reminiscent of slavery.
     The Democrats offer more jails, stiffer sentences --three
strikes and you're out! -- and worse prison conditions as the
solution to crime.  Punishment, not rehabilitation, is their
solution.
     Women represent the fastest growing population in prison.
Between 1980 and 1993, the population of women in prison increased
313 percent, 60 percent of them women of color.
2.   FREE ALL POLITICAL PRISONERS IN U.S. JAILS.
     There are over 100 political prisoners in U.S. jails.  They
are people like Native American leader and activist Leonard
Peltier, framed for murder and unjustly imprisoned for over 20
years.  Despite worldwide demands for his release, which include
the support of Amnesty International, the U.S. Justice Department
recently denied him parole once again.
     Alejandrina Torres has spent years fighting for the
independence of her homeland, Puerto Rico.  She was convicted of
being part of a clandestine armed organization and sentenced to 35
years in jail.
     Geronimo ji jaga Pratt, targeted in 1971 by the FBI because of
his active participation in the Black Panther Party in California,
has spent over 25 years in jail for a murder charge that FBI
records show he could not possibly have committed.
     Mumia Abu Jamal, former Black Panther Party activist and MOVE
supporter, was sentenced to death in 1982 for the murder of a
Philadelphia police officer -- a murder he did not commit.
     Susan Rosenberg, white anti-imperialist activist, was
sentenced to 58 years for her support of Black, Puerto Rican, and
other struggles.
     All of these political prisoners have spent years and years in
jail.  We demand their release and return to their families and
communities.
3.   STOP POLICE BRUTALITY
     Police brutality, including the murder of innocent people, is
spreading throughout Black and Latino communities.  The video taped
examples of police brutality against Rodney King and the
undocumented Mexicans are but the more visible examples of how the
police treat Blacks and Latinos.  In Chicago, the recent murders of
Jorge Guillen and Joseph Gould, a homeless man, by Chicago police
officers are tragic examples of the level of police brutality
directed against Latino and African American people.  This must
stop!

We call upon you, your family, friends, and community to take
action to expose and repudiate this so-called criminal "justice"
system.  We choose to target the Democratic National Convention
because the American public needs to hear what we have to say.  We
won't accept more prisons, longer sentences, and chain gangs!  We
won't accept continued incarceration of political prisoners!  We
won't accept police brutality!

The "Not on the Guest List" coalition has been formed to work on
this project.  The list, in formation, includes:
Aaron Paterson Defense Committee
A Job is a Right Campaign/Milwaukee
American Friends Service Committee
American Indian Movement Grand Council
Anti-Racist Action/Minneapolis
Autonomous Zone
Gaiter Bradley (United in Peace)
Coalition for Prisoners' Rights/Santa FE
Coalition to Free Mumia Abu Jamal
Jack Cohen-Joppa (The Nuclear Resister)
Committee to End the Marion Lockdown
Dave Dellinger
Eighth Day Center for Justice
Equal Justice/Quixote Center
Free Mumia Abu Jamal/Pittsburgh
Interfaith Prisoners of Conscience
Leonard Peltier Defense Committee
National Committee for Nonviolent Civil Disobedience to Free
Leonard Peltier
National Lawyers Guild
Prairie Fire Organizing Committee
Neighbors Against Police Brutality
Phil Berrigan/Jonah House
Refuse and Resist!
St. Martin de Porres Catholic Worker/Hartford, CT
Tony Rios Support Committee/Quebec
N.W. Suburban Direct Action
P2 Program/Quebec
Prison Action Committee
Puerto Rico Cultural Center
Women's Action Coalition (WAC)
Workers World

For more information on what will happen and how to get involved
contact Not on the Guest List!
Phone: (312) 278-6706
Fax:   (312) 278-0635


Print out this message, then clip and send the following to:
Not on the Guest List!
2048 W. Division
Chicago, IL 60622

