<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: March for Latino Rights</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/notiban.gif" ALT="Notices" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Saturday, October 12, March for Latino Rights</H3><PRE>--Note: The following article was recently published in Los Angeles.
  The author, journalist, and current subscriber of the Coordinadora 96
  listserv, Marilyn Martinez, interviewed several persons in preparation
  for the essay and this is what she ended up with. See, "Foot Soldiers:
  March on Washington Will Bring the Fight for Latino Civil Rights to
  Clinton and Dole's Doorstep," LOS ANGELES READER 18:39 (July 5,
  1996): 4. The READER is one of LA's longest running alternative
  weeklies.

  Posted: Roberto R. Calderon/email: beto@ucrac1.ucr.edu
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

    Marilyn Martinez, "Foot Soldiers: March on Washington
    Will Bring the Fight for Latino Civil Rights to
    Clinton and Dole's Doorstep," LOS ANGELES READER 18:39
    (July 5, 1996): 4. (Photograph by Steve Appleford)

     Before Proposition 187 made bashing Latino immigrants a popular
pastime, before Bob Dole agreed that locking undocumented immigrant
children out of classrooms is a great idea, and before Riverside
deputies played beat-up-the-Mexicans on live television, Juan Jose
Gutierrez saw it all coming.

     From his East Los Angeles office, Gutierrez and others have
spent three years planning a massive rally in Washington, D.C.,
on October 12 to end "this season of anti-Latino politicking" and
attacks on the "fundamental interests of working people."

     "Our people are hard-working, law-abiding, family-oriented
human beings, and nobody is here to undermine anybody," said
Gutierrez, national co-coordinator of Coordinadora '96, or
Campaign '96. "All that we want to have is an opportunity to
participate."

     The march is drawing widespread support from Latino activists
across the nation. Southern California organizers expect to send a
contingent of at least 25,000, and one Salvadoran leader has
promised 100,000 from Washington, Virginia, and Maryland.
Organizers' appeals are being answered by varied Latino groups,
including those in the Central American, Mexican, Mexican-American,
Puerto Rican, and Dominican communities.

     Organizers project a crowd of several hundred thousand at the
rally, which will be followed by a week of lobbying, forums, media
interviews, and cultural performances. Such large numbers are
realistic, organizers insisted, considering that recent pro-
immigrant marches in Los Angeles alone have drawn thousands,
while a crowd of 150,000 marched to City Hall for an anti-187
rally in [October] 1994.

     There is a generalized frustration in Latino communities
around the country, and everyone is looking for something to do
that would give some meaning to what they are feeling," said
Gutierrez, who described the march as drawing from new immigrants,
seasoned Latino activists, and college and high school students
energized by the failed campaign to defeat Prop. 187 in
California.

     Frustrated with public misperceptions of the Latino
community as racial separatists or illegal immigrants living
on the public dole, and Republican readiness to exploit these
fears, organizers want to set the record straight. Almost 98
percent of Latinos are U.S. citizens and permanent residents,
they say, and most undocumented immigrants want nothing more
than to become Americans.

     "We are going to Washington to say, 'Look, our issue is
not just immigration.' We are part of the American nation, and
we are  American citizens," said Gutierrez, a lawyer and executive
director of One Stop Immigration and Educational Center in East
L.A. "We are treated as though we have no opinion and no ideas
about education, about opportunities in the arts and, in economic
matters, in foreign policy. Everything is almost reduced entirely
to immigration, to drug trafficking, to decadent kind of things
and seldom to anything else."

     Organizers have adopted a politically progressive platform
of seven "demands," which include a streamlined citizenship
application process, a seven-dollars-per-hour minimum wage,
citizen police review boards, the preservation of affirmative
action, and "human and constitutional rights for all." The
creation and public advocacy of their own political agendas is
an effort to do more than just react to conservative legislation,
organizers said.

     Such a huge and public undertaking is a necessity because
immigrant Latinos and Latinas would be deeply affected if proposed
conservative federal and state legislation is passed, organizers
said. Among the most severe is Simi Valley Congressman Elton
Gallegly's proposed legislation that would allow states to cut
off education to the children of undocumented immigrant children.

     "Some of the extremists on the other side would like us...
to accept the unacceptable roles of becoming for the foreseeable
future as a community of modern-day slaves of our society,"
Gutierrez said. "And that, we are not going to accept."  R

     * "Get on the Bus," a benefit concert for the march on
     Washington, D.C., will be held July 28 at 5 p.m., at
     CSO, 2130 E. First St., East L.A. Performers will include
     Culture Clash, Money Mark, Maria Fatal, YESCA, and
     Aztlan Nation. Tickets are $15. Call (800)410-1296.

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   LATINO CIVIL RIGHTS MARCH ON WASHINGTON, D.C.: OCTOBER 12, 1996
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
ESTA ES MI TIERRA/ESTA ES MI LUCHA++ESTA ES MI TIERRA/ESTA ES MI LUCHA

