<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Conference for Student Activists</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/notiban.gif" ALT="Notices" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Conference for Student Activists</H3><PRE>Building Progressive Student Power
Summer '96 Conference (August 9-11)


Dear Progressive Student Leader,

Greetings from Ithaca; we hope your summer is going well.  Besides being a
welcome respite from course work and cold weather, the summer is an
excellent time to get together to share ideas and experiences about
progressive student activism. The Center for Campus Organizing is helping to
coordinate student conferences in many different regions of the United
States this summer.  The United Progressives (UP), a student activist
organization at Cornell University, is hosting the "Building Progressive
Student Power" conference for the Northeast Region.  We hope that by coming
together to discuss common issues and strategies, we will strengthen the
progressive student movement as a whole.  Tentative agenda items for the
conference include but are not limited to (please see reverse for a more
complete list) the following:

        * share organizing issues and strategies
        * dialogue about group dynamics and coalition building within
                marginalized groups and between campuses
        * assist in the development of  a national progressive student agenda
        * discuss ways to utilize student governments for progressive causes
        * consider third party politics.

The Northeast Regional Conference will meet in Ithaca at Cornell University.
It's open to all progressive students, whether they currently hold a
leadership position or not.  We're contacting people from a number of
schools in the area including Amherst, Brown, Columbia, Harvard, Moravian,
Skidmore, and Uconn (see reverse).  If you know another person who may be
interested, please pass our phone numbers along.  We're aiming for about
thirty people; a group this size should be dynamic but allow us to remain
focused and engaged.

If you're interested in coming please contact us as soon as possible.  The
dates are Friday evening August 9th to Sunday afternoon August 11th.  The
conference fee is $10 on a sliding scale (pay what you can) to help cover
copying costs.  We have accommodations all set in Ithaca but you will need
to get here.  The Greyhound bus leaving NYC Friday and returning Sunday
costs $63. We can also get bus information from other cities and try to
arrange carpools.  You will need to pay for some meals (probably lunch)
yourself, but we are trying to arrange breakfast and dinner.

As the title suggests, the conference is about building a movement.  This
means that although issues are important (see reverse), we can't forget to
nurture our spirit.  We're trying to put together an inspiring speaker, some
music, a little party and other assorted activities to make the weekend fun!
Please bring any musical instruments, games, poetry and other fun items
along! We really hope you can make it.  Please call with questions and/or
register as soon as possible (but definitely by July 15).
                                                -Cornell United Progressives

contacts:       Cori    (607) 273-8832  cmc21@cornell.edu
                        Gwen    (607) 256-7382  gem3@cornell.edu


Very Tentative agenda items...
        Developing a national progressive student agenda.  Special focus:
increased spending on weapons and prisons while defunding education.
        Starting a national student organization or network to further
this agenda
        Dealing with administrators
        Dealing with right- wingers
        Taking over and using student governments
        Coalition building, especially across ethnic and racial lines, and
between
                different campuses
        Tactics: some tactics may have diminishing returns. Do we need to
develop
                new ones?
        Third party politics
        Group interactions and dynamics

and activities...
        Civil disobedience training/other workshops
        Teamwork building games
        Speaker/Music
        Party/BBQ/Dancing


Some people we're trying to contact about the conference (if you know one
other person who may be interested, please pass our number along)

Eric Albert             Harvard                 Danny Forster   Wesleyan
Dawn Scirmer    school unknown          Kristin Rockerman       Brown
Dave Wade         Brown                         Andrea
Lee                      Brown
Jennette Barnes  Skidmore                       Steven Gensemer         UConn

John Potash             Columbia                        Jed
Brandt                      Hunter
Sugene Yang     Amherst                 Al Ferkel                       Moravian
Josh Marcus     Penn                            Cathy
Rion                      Stanford

Carrie Kleimen  Brandeis                        Dan
Lang                        Yale
Rebecca Barson  Williams                        Dan
Clowes                      Swarthmore
Joah Marcus     Upenn                           Jennifer
Hope                   Rutgers
Gideon Oliver           Vassar
Various                 Cornell

We'll send out a more complete list with phone numbers as people start to
register.

Hope to hear from you soon!
</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
