<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Dineh Alliance Seeks Assistance</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/notiban.gif" ALT="Notices" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Dineh Alliance Seeks Assistance</H3><PRE>Dineh Alliance
dineh@primenet.com
http://www.primenet.com/~dineh/


BIG MOUNTAIN UPDATE -- 6/19/96


Good Greetings relatives and friends,

We are once more again, trying to let ourselves be heard at the national
and international levels.  We are on our way to Washingtion D.C. to take
training and workshops that relate to our cause and the issues here on
Black Mesa, AZ.  We will also lobby on behalf of ourselves, June 24th
through the 28th, 1996, and we will join the milions of others worldwide
who support Leonard Peltier in his Fight For Freedom; we feel and
believe that we are prisoners also, he behind bars and we behid a fence
line.  SDN-Dineh Alliance will participate in a joint press conference
with the Leonard Peltier Defense Committee (LPDC) on the 26 & 27th.  The
leaders of the United States must listen to their constituents and
respond to their call; we believe if the general American public knew
what was being done with their hard earned tax dollars they would
themselves sit up and take notice of the on-going horrific waste.

As you might know, our Big Mountain Annual Spring Gathering was placed
under seige by a multi-jurisdictional task force led by official Hopi
tribal law enforcement personal.  We are currently in direct
negotiations with the Hopi tribe for the Sundance scheduled for July
7-14, 1996, at Camp Ana Mae; at present we are following every step of
protocol and procedure directly with Hopi Chairman Ferrell Secakuku's
office to obtain a permit to host the upcoming Ceremony.  Our last
meeting for this will be on June 19, 1996, near Camp Ana Mae on Hopi
Partitioned Land (HPL).  We are seeking peaceful and non-violent means
to avoid a repeat of the recent display of attrition.  Likewise, with
the "Enforcer" of the Accommodation Agreement, we hope to begin to amend
Public Law 93-531--The Relocation Act of 1974, and incorporate our input
to the Congressional legislation being created at this time.  This is
our last opportunity, so they tell us, to get something into the
development of the "Accommodation Agreement" (Agreement).  January 01,
1997, is the dead line for all Dineh on Hopi Partitioned Land (HPL) to
sign the new lease that the official parties want to ratify, enact, and
enforce (thru P.L. 93-531).  We need your support for this trip.  It is
short notice but somehow things are looking positive.  This is an
important trip and The People need your assistance.

For the trip we are requesting some cash assitance to help with the cost
for the trip, its an emergency trip.  The Navajo and Hopi tribal
Governments are trying so hard to sell us out to the Acommodation
Agreement, a document which only serves their interest.  We have been
circumvented and impeded at every level from direct and meaningful
participation in the "mediation"and told there is "no alternative" for
those of us who will not sign the Agreement.  The only way for us to be
heard is by doing this ourselves.  Thank you very much for your support
during this critical time.

Send help to;
                Sovereign Dineh Nation-Dineh Alliance
                c/o Will Collette, Citizens Coal Council
                110 Maryland Avenue NE, Room 408
                Washington, D.C. 20002
                (202) 544-6210, fax (202)543 0978

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

                     FAX ATTACK TIME

The other area we need your help with is getting a meeting set up
sometime before the Congressional recess with Senator John McCain during
the week of June 24 to 28, 1996.  McCain is the Chairman of the Senate
Committee on Indian Affairs and is very hard to reach at this point.  He
must listen to those who are affected by the "land dispute" and only a
face-to-face meeting will do; the delegation from Black Mesa is prepared
to meet with him even after office hours...Bottom line:  After Congress
returns it will be too late.  Direct your FAX, Letter, E-mail, or Call
to:

Senator John McCain, Chairman          Phone: 202/224-2235
Senate Committee on Indian Affairs     FAX: 228-2862
838 Senate Hart Bldg.                  Senator_McCain@mccain.senate.gov
Washington, D.C.  20510

YOUR OWN REPRESENTATIVES CAN BE CONTACTED AS WELL AS THE MEDIA.

                         THANK YOU!




** End of text from cdp:headlines **

