<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Seeking Sites for Nonviolent Resistance Training</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/notiban.gif" ALT="Notices" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD>
<H3>Seeking Sites for Nonviolent Resistance Training</H3><PRE>This is a proposal for the tour of speakers from Tabasco which
will happen between November 5-26, 1996.  We are talking to
groups in the different cities listed, and can add other
sites/cities if people are interested.  Please notify me as soon
as possible if you would like to schedule an event so we can
start coordinating the schedule.

Thank you for your interest.


Sincerely,


Ken Preston
Global Exchange, Speaking Tour Organizer



Tabasco Speaking Tour: Nonviolent
Resistance and the Global Defense of the Eco-system

Sponsored by Global Exchange

REQUEST FOR LOCAL ORGANIZERS AND
TOUR PRESENTERS

WHEN:  The tour will take place in mid- November, 1996.  Once commitments are
made by local groups, we will coordinate and confirm the schedule.

WHERE:  Speaking engagements for the tour are being sought in the following
areas:
California: Los Angeles, San Francisco, Sacramento, etc.
Northwest: Seattle, Portland, Eugene, etc.  Rocky Mountain: Denver, Boulder,
etc. Midwest: Madison, Minneapolis, Chicago,
etc.
Northeast States: Massachusetts,
Connecticut, Vermont, Maine, etc.
East Coast: Washington, D.C., etc.
Gulf Coast: Louisiana, Texas, etc.

PROGRAM: We envision a typical program to be a talk followed by a
question and answer session.  Some groups may also wish to host a
reception.  The format can be flexible according to the needs of
each group.

SPEAKERS: Rafael Landerreche is one of the leaders in Tabasco's
social resistance movement.  A student of the nonviolent tactics
of Gandhi and Martin Luther King, Rafael travels throughout
Tabasco training communities in the techniques of peaceful
resistance.  Rafael has worked closely with Andres Manuel Lopez
Obrador, the leader of the opposition PRD political party in
Tabasco, who will likely be elected president of the PRD.  Rafael
has been a leader in Servicio, Paz y Justicia (Service, Peace and
Justice), a pacifist human rights organization started by
Argentinian Nobel Prize recipient Adolfo Peres Esquivel.  The
second speaker, still to be determined, will be a campesino
leader.

TOPICS: Since 1994 the opposition in the state of Tabasco have
engaged in a large and powerful resistance movement to counter a
political and ecological crisis.  Tabasco became a symbol of
political corruption in 1994 when it was revealed that the
newly-elected candidate of the ruling party (PRI), Governor
Madrazo, had spent $70 million on his election campaign, sixty
times the legal limit of just over $1 million.  Currently,
Madrazo is under investigation by the Attorney General's Office
for campaign fraud.  Madrazo is also facing demands from a
popular movement made up of peasants and indigenous people who
have seen their fields, coastal waters and livelihoods damaged by
a largely unaccountable national petroleum industry, Petroleos
Mexicanos (PEMEX).  For the past two decades, PEMEX has been
intensely and recklessly exploiting Tabasco's oil reserves,
resulting in badly skewed income distribution, huge increases in
the cost of living, forced relocations, environmental
destruction, soaring health problems as the result of toxics and
conditions of extreme hazard for people living in the petroleum
producing zones.

The two speakers will detail the historical context of these
ecological and political crises.  Rafael will discuss the various
ways the social movement is utilizing nonviolent resistance
principles, including fasts, marches, sit-ins, oil well
occupations and other techniques.  The campesino leader will
provide a grassroots viewpoint -- that of the people living in
the oppressive conditions.

LOCAL ORGANIZERS WILL COORDINATE
ALL EVENTS IN THEIR
RESPECTIVE CITY, INCLUDING:

* Coordinating logistical support, to include food, housing and ground
transportation.
* Putting co-sponsoring organizations in touch with each other.
* Publicizing events to English press/media.  Global Exchange can provide
assistance in this effort.

WE ARE ASKING TOUR PRESENTERS TO:

* Provide venue arrangements.

* Publicize events within your university/groups.  Global
Exchange can help with this.

* Provide hospitality to three out of town guests, our two
speakers and Global Exchange representative, Ken Preston, for one
night.  Food/lodging (home stay ok/hotel is not necessary),
transport to/from airport.

* Funding: We need to receive between $500 and $1000 per event
(depending on associated costs) in order to cover the expense of
the trip.  We understand that some groups can provide more
support than others.  Our experience has shown that seeking co-
sponsors (eg. among departments or student groups) helps to share
the costs andresponsibilities of an event.

FOR MORE INFORMATION, CONTACT:

Ken Preston at Global Exchange
tel: (415)255-7296; fax: (415)255-7498
e-mail: <globalexch@igc.apc.org>

Global Exchange is a non-profit education and action center working to promote
citizen diplomacy.  We seek to build more people-to- people ties between North
and South, and closer collaboration among U.S. groups doing such work.

------- End of forwarded message -------</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
