<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site:</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/commban.gif" ALT="Commentary" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><H3></H3><PRE>Petty Crimes Are Swelling the Dockets
New York Times
NEW YORK -- In the early morning hours of April 18, four members of Act 
Up, the AIDS protest group, knowingly broke the law. Furious that a 
pharmacy in Chelsea was making what they considered an unacceptably large 
profit for a new AIDS drug, they papered the store's windows with huge 
signs that read "Profiteers" and "Price Gougers." 

It was a conscious act of civil disobedience and within minutes police 
officers, summoned by a neighbor of the pharmacy, arrested them. The four 
were then held in custody for more than 24 hours, for the misdemeanor of 
defacing a window with graffiti. 

They said they had nothing to drink, and spent hours in handcuffs outside, 
because the holding pen was too crowded. What's more, two of the men who 
are infected with HIV said they could not get to their medication while 
behind bars. Nor, they contended, could any of them reach families or 
friends until one got to a phone to call a lawyer 14 hours after the arrest. 

This account of such grueling treatment may sound implausible, but in fact 
it is not unusual. Lawyers and judges agree that overcrowding is routine now 
that the city's crackdown on quality-of-life crimes is in full flourish. The 
Police Department stepped up arrests for violations and misdemeanors early 
this spring and the system is clogged. 

Andrew Stettner, one of the four arrested in the April incident, said that 
there were people in the pen with him who had been in custody for two days 
and more, waiting to see a judge. 

Many couldn't reach anyone because central booking in lower Manhattan, where 
prisoners are held until they are arraigned, does not have enough telephones. 

Jonathan Lippman, the state's chief administrative judge, said Thursday that 
the dockets are indeed crowded, and he urged the handling of many cases 
administratively instead of in the courts, so judges can focus on more 
serious crimes.

But Colleen Roche, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's press secretary, said: "It's 
a fruitless exercise to give you the facts because you continue to 
misrepresent the facts. The simple truth is, the courts are not overworked." 

Michele Maxian, director of litigation for the Legal Aid Society, does not 
agree. Conditions in the courts are such these days that prisoners "become 
part of the disappeared," she said. 

Under the law, prisoners in New York are supposed to see a judge within 24 
hours of their arrest. There is no practical way to enforce that in each case, 
so the Legal Aid Society brings writs of habeas corpus whenever the backlog 
gets too severe. That prods the Police Department to release some prisoners. 

In the past month, Legal Aid has brought writs on behalf of almost 4,000 
arrestees, including one filed Thursday. At 9 a.m. Thursday morning, Legal 
Aid said, 130 of the 457 awaiting arraignment in Manhattan had been in jail 
over 24 hours, most accused of misdemeanors or violations. 

That included two unlicensed peddlers who had spent two days in jail. Others 
have spent that long in jail for riding a bicycle in Washington Square Park 
and for drinking beer in public. 

Not long ago, most of those arrested for misdemeanors were given summonses 
at local station houses and released. But as many as half never showed up 
in court, the police said. Hence, the crackdown, on the theory that small 
crimes beget more serious crimes. 

Besides, the strategy is a political winner. "People figure, if more people 
are locked up, they're going to be a certain degree safer," said Susan 
Tipograph, a lawyer for the Act Up members. Isn't that likely, she was asked? 
"I know it's useful to send some people to prison. But certainly everybody 
should have the right to go before a magistrate quickly, to determine whether 
they should be held or not. People like easy answers, but democracy is by 
its nature very raggedy." 

Mark Milano, an AIDS educator who was part of the four that defaced the 
pharmacy, said he knew he was taking a risk. 

"They were within their rights to arrest us," he said. "But why prevent 
people's access to phones, never give them any idea of what was going to 
happen, keep them in the dark?" 

Stettner, an associate with People for the American way, agreed: "It's 
ridiculous to waste taxpayer dollars on this. It isn't a crime, it's democracy." 

He, Milano and their colleagues are to return to court on June 19. They could 
be sentenced to up to a year in jail but it is much more likely that a judge 
will direct them to perform community service. 

They have, after all, already done time. </PRE></TD>
</TR>
