<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site:"Bad Food" Sign Near Restaurant is Protected Speech</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/commban.gif" ALT="Commentary" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>"Bad Food" Sign Near Restaurant is Protected Speech</H3>
<PRE>

By Alan Alden
New York Law Journal
April 25, 1996

A lawyer in an office above a recently opened Kenny Rogers Roasters 
restaurant on Broadway may keep a sign in his window reading "Bad Food," 
according to a Manhattan judge who ruled that the sign was a 
constitutionally protected expression of opinion.

In tossing out the restaurant's suit, Supreme Court Justice Charles 
E. Ramos rejected a contention that its property rights should outweigh 
the right to free speech of attorney Aaron C. Lichtman, its upstairs 
neighbor at 2067 Broadway near 71st Street.  

Mr. Lichtman's "activities" have not "approached the level which would 
warrant a serious consideration of balancing Roasters' property rights 
with Lichtman's First Amendment Rights," wrote Justice Ramos in K.R. 
Roasters Broadway Inc. v. Aaron Lichtman.

"Were Lichtman to stand outside Roasters, physically approach and scream 
at customers that they would suffer from abdominal distention after eating 
Roasters' food, the balance may be tipped more favorably to Roasters," he added.

"However, in this case, First Amendment rights must not be compromised merely 
because plaintiff may suffer a loss of profit.  First Amendment rights are 
not conditioned upon being non-offensive, whether the harm is to reputation 
or profits."

Noting that the "positive and negative aspects of food are discussed in 
subjective, not factual terms," Justice Ramos declared that it is "unreasonable 
to view Lichtman's sign as anything other than Lichtman's own biased opinion."  
People looking at the sign, therefore, would conclude that Mr. Lichtman is 
"conveying nothing more than his distaste with...the consistency, odor and 
taste of said cuisine."

In mid-February, prior to opening for business, the restaurant, which is part 
of chain endorsed by the country music superstar, Kenny Rogers, sought an 
injunction forcing Mr. Lichtman to remove his handwritten sign and accused 
Mr. Lichtman of defamation and interference of business relations.

The eatery argued that the "Bad Food" sign was a "weapon" in a tenant-to-tenant 
dispute which was intended to hurt its profits.  It alleged that Mr, Lichtman 
posted it only after complaining that the illuminated signs and awnings were 
obscuring the view of his law office sign.

Justice Ramos refused to grant the preliminary injunction and Mr. Lichtman 
moved to dismiss the suit, contending that the sign was merely his response to 
Roasters' ad touting the quality of their food.  Mr. Lichtman said that he had 
eaten in Roasters' 1st Avenue location and had found the food to be "overly 
salty, greasy, and otherwise to have poor taste, consistency and odor."

Invoking classic free speech passages from Judges Learned Hand and Oliver Wendall 
Holmes among others, Justice Ramos sided with Mr. Lichtman.
Noting that Judge Hand had stated that the First Amendment guaranteed free 
speech even during wartime, Justice Ramos wrote that "although freedom of speech 
has never been held to be absolute, most speech is protected speech."

Mr. Lichtman's expression, "Bad Food," he concluded, "does not amount to the 
level of imminent danger" which has been recognized as the threshold for 
restraining the exercise of an individual's First Amendment rights."  
Mr. Lichtman's response to Roasters' claim is "merely advocacy," he added.

Citing Justice Holmes's pronouncement that the "best test of truth" is "the 
free trade of ideas," Justice Ramos, noting that Roasters is "open and 
operating," said that their claims of selling good food "may be more or less 
credible if they are able to withstand the public debate arising from the 
counter-viewpoint of Lichtman.

The "affirmative duty of this court," he asserted is to "ensure that this 
debate is not suppressed as it represents the fundamental freedom to develop 
and express opinions."

Mr. Lichtman represented himself.  Adrian Zuckerman and Robert Boneberg of 
Davidoff & Malito, represented K.R. Roasters.  Mr. Zuckerman said his client 
would appeal.

</BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
