<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Anti-Abortion Protester Banned From "Stalking"</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/commban.gif" ALT="Commentary" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>Anti-Abortion Protester Banned From "Stalking"</H3><PRE>c.1996 N.Y. Times News Service 

PORTLAND, Ore. - A judge, using a year-old law to protect people from 
stalkers, has ordered one of the nation's most outspoken foes of 
abortion to stay away from the head of a Portland clinic after he had 
repeatedly harassed her and picketed her house. 

Judge Thomas L. Moultrie of Multnomah County District Court ruled on 
Thursday that the abortion opponent, Paul deParrie, was permanently 
forbidden to have any contact with Jude Hanzo, the executive director 
of All Women's Health Services. DeParrie will face charges if he violates 
the order. 

Moultrie invoked Oregon's anti-stalking law, which was passed in June 
1995, and protects citizens from alarming or unwanted contacts. 

Judges have imposed stalking orders on anti-abortion protesters before. 
But the current ruling is significant because deParrie, 45, is probably 
the most prominent protester ever to be so restricted. He is one of the 
three leaders of Advocates for Life Ministries, a national group based 
in Portland, and is also the editor of the Ministries' monthly magazine, 
Life Advocate. 

Ms. Hanzo has said that deParrie's campaign against her began in April 
1995 when he visited her neighborhood to deliver fliers that bore her 
picture and read, ``Your neighbor is an abortionist ... Let her know 
that you think she should not kill children for a living.'' 

Later, Ms. Hanzo said, deParrie called her unlisted phone number, sent 
her a threatening postcard, and led two demonstrations outside her home. 
At the second demonstration, on Jan. 6, she said there were 22 people, 
all of them bearing signs that read, ``Jail Abortionists.'' 

``I can't tell you how many nightmares I had,'' said Ms. Hanzo, who began 
wearing a bulletproof vest and installed a home security system. ``I never 
knew what would happen next. I was afraid when I drove to work. I was 
uncomfortable gardening with my back to the street.'' 

In court, Ms. Hanzo's lawyer, Katherine McDowell, argued that deParrie 
had no right to disrupt the tranquillity of her client's home. Robert 
Barnhart, a weapons specialist for the Multnomah County sheriff's office, 
testified that deParrie is capable of violence - and he therefore revoked 
deParrie's permit to carry concealed weapons. 

DeParrie, who defended himself, argued that the case was about free speech 
rather than violence. He said that he had not contacted Ms. Hanzo 
directly - that he had merely picketed her home, with no intention of 
threatening her. 

``She was scared,'' deParrie said in a telephone interview, ``because we 
made her look deep inside herself, and deep inside she knows what she's 
doing is evil.'' 

Dallas A. Blanchard, the author of ``Religious Violence and Abortion,'' 
calls Advocates for Life ``the biggest voice in the justifiable homicide 
movement,'' which champions the killing of abortion providers, and notes 
that deParrie has written several articles supporting murder. 

Priscilla Smith, a staff lawyer at the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy, 
said that DeParrie's punishment ``sends a very clear message to those who 
are thinking about following in his footsteps.'' 

DeParrie says he would obey the terms of the stalking order. But his colleague, 
Andrew Burnett, director of Advocates for Life, noted that his group regularly 
picketed those who gave abortions, and might return to Ms. Hanzo's house. 

Burnett said he had no pickets planned, and, at least for the moment, Ms. 
Hanzo said she was not worried. ``I feel safer today than I have in over 
a year,'' she said, ``I feel like my home is a safe place, and I'm 
tremendously relieved.''</PRE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
