</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Supporters say flag amendment will return</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/commban.gif" ALT="Commentary" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>SUPPORTERS SAY FLAG AMENDMENT WILL RETURN</H3>by Tony Mauro<P>The most serious congressional effort in decades to alter theprotections of the First Amendment failed last month as the Senatenarrowly defeated a proposed flag-desecration amendment.<P>The amendment, which would have authorized passage of laws tooutlaw desecration of the American flag, had passed the Housein June and probably would have been ratified by the states. Butthe Senate proved to be the fatal stumbling block for the amendment,voting 63 to 36 in favor-three votes shy of the necessary 99 votes.<P>Supporters of the amendment said the defeat was only temporary.&quot;This amendment is not going to go away,&quot; threatenedSen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. &quot;We will debate it in the nextCongress.&quot;<P>Hatch blamed President Clinton for the defeat. Clinton, who aspresident plays no constitutional role in the passage of amendments,had said he opposed the amendment but could accept legislationto protect the flag.<P>The Citizens Flag Alliance, which coordinated the grassroots campaignfor the amendment, said its members would remember which senatorsvoted for and against it. &quot;See you in November,&quot; saidDan Wheeler, president of the alliance.<P>Some analysts suggested that, although the actual vote marginwas narrow, opposition to the amendment ran even deeper in theSenate. Several senators may have voted in favor of the amendmentto appease constitutents after it became clear that their &quot;no&quot;votes were not needed.<P>Several alternative proposals were also defeated by the Senate,including one by Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., that would havebanned flag desecration by legislation, not by a constitutionalamendment. The Supreme Court has twice struck down anti-flag-burninglaws in the past, but McConnell's proposal might have passed constitutionalmuster because it banned flag-burning as an incitement to violence-whichthe court has said falls outside the protections of the FirstAmendment.<P>Before defeating the amendment, the Senate did accept one changefrom the version passed in the House. The House amendment wouldhave left it to the states and to Congress to pass laws banningflag desecration, but the Senate opted to give that job to Congressalone-to prevent a patchwork of different laws in the 50 states.<P>But ultimately, even the amended amendment failed, following floordebate that turned into an eloquent appraisal of the importanceof the First Amendment.<P>&quot;The first sign that freedom or democracy is in trouble aroundthe world is when the government starts locking up dissenters,&quot;said Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va. &quot;The acid test of democracyis whether or not we can speak out in peaceful dissent againstour government without fear of being arrested or prosecuted orpunished. And in this case, the amendment goes directly to theheart of that freedom.&quot;<P>Said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.: &quot;To me, the flag symbolizesour strength, our democracy, and our unprecedented freedoms-freedomsthat set us apart from every other country in the world. Our Constitutionguarantees all of us this freedom, including the right to freespeech. I believe we should be very cautious about altering thedocument, because to do so alters the fundamental ideals on whichour country was built.&quot;<P>Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, one of only four Republicans whoopposed the amendment, said, &quot;If we start amending the Constitutionevery time there is a Supreme Court decision with which we disagree,we run the risk of seeing the Constitution turned into somethingother than basic law.&quot;<P>Supporters argued with equal passion that the First Amendmentwould not be significantly altered by the amendment.<P>&quot;Until the Supreme Court ruled flag desecration to be protectedfree speech in 1989, 48 states and the federal government hadstatutes which penalized an individual for desecrating the flag,&quot;said Sen. Dirk Kempthorne, R-Idaho. &quot;I do not believe thetime prior to 1989 may realistically be viewed as a dark periodin which Americans were denied their constitutional rights.&quot;<P>Said Hatch: &quot;Individual rights are constantly expanded, butresponsibilities are shirked and scorned ... The Flag is one overridingsymbol that unites a diverse people in a way nothing else canor ever will. We have no king. We have no state religion. We havean American flag.&quot; <P>Tony Mauro covers the Supreme Court for <I>USA TODAY</I></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
