<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Link To Violence Could Put Curbs On Speech</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/newsbut.gif" ALT="NEWS" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/commban.gif" ALT="Commentary" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>LINK TO VIOLENCE COULD PUT CURBS ON SPEECH</H3>by Tony Mauro<P>The recent spate of violence-first at abortion clinics, then atthe federal building in Oklahoma City-has triggered new debateover one of the oldest questions under First Amendment law: Whatis the relationship between speech and violence? Or, to put itmore simply, can words hurt?<P>The issue has arisen in recent years in other contexts, when some have argued that pornography, hate speech, and even violence on television have been the cause of harmful acts and should be restricted. In the aftermath of the Oklahoma City bombing, President Clinton drew the connection between hateful speech and violence, saying, &quot;Bitter words can have consequences.&quot;<P>But the relationship between speech and actionhas been drawn most closely in the abortion-clinic setting. There,violence that has left five people dead since 1991 has occurredin a climate of intense and virulent rhetoric aimed at clinicdoctors, workers and patients.<P>&quot;We have to re-evaluate how much speech is free,&quot; says Kathryn Kolbert of the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy, which advocates abortion rights. &quot;Given the context, it can be incredibly incendiary.&quot;<P>Some of the more extreme anti-abortion activists have equated abortionwith murder in their demonstrations and literature, issued listsof clinic workers and spoken freely of the need to exact retributionfor abortion sins. &quot;The Bible is very clear. You will reapwhat you sow,&quot; says the Rev. Donald Spitz of Chesapeake,Va.<P>John Salvi III, accused of killing two clinic workers and injuringfive others in Brookline, Mass., last December, had many anti-abortionpublications and posters in his apartment, police said. One anti-abortionnewsletter had recently listed the address of the Norfolk, Va.,abortion clinic where Salvi was arrested after spraying it withbullets.<P>Another publication widely distributed in the anti-abortioncommunity listed the name of John Britton, the physician who replacedDr. David Gunn at a Pensacola clinic after Gunn was killed inMarch, 1993. Last July, Britton was shot to death by Paul Hill,who was convicted of the murder last November.<P>The climate of violence - both rhetorical and real - has prompted some on both sides inthe abortion debate to draw the connection between speech andviolence. After the Brookline shootings, Boston's Roman CatholicCardinal Bernard Law called for a moratorium on clinic proteststo calm the atmosphere of violence.<P>An advertisement by Planned Parenthood of New York City proclaimed &quot;Words Kill,&quot;and attacked religious broadcaster Pat Robertson and others forbroadcasting &quot;the words which have caused a rampage of anti-choiceterrorism.&quot; Robertson angrily denied the charge, noting thathe has called for an end to clinic violence in numerous broadcasts.<P>Abortion-rights advocates say the escalation of violence has prompted them tocall for restrictions on speech that they never would have consideredfive years ago.&quot;<P>The context shifts,&quot; says Kolbert. &quot;Thirtyyears ago, no one would have given a second thought to someonejoking that a bomb was on an aircraft, either. But then you hadhijackings, and the same joke becomes a crime.&quot;<P>Kolbert says people making threats against clinic doctors and workers shouldbe more aggressively prosecuted under criminal laws, even if theirthreats would have seemed like protected speech in calmer times.&quot;More and more, we shouldn't allow criminals to masqueradebehind concepts of free speech,&quot; she says.<P>Congress and the courts have already enacted and upheld laws that create specialbuffer zones around clinics where protests are limited - restrictionsthat might not be viewed as constitutional in other settings.The Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances (FACE) Act of 1994 makesit a crime to interfere with clinic operations &quot;by forceor threat of force.&quot;<P>A federal judge in Milwaukee struck down the FACE law in March, but not on First Amendment grounds. Judge Rudolph Randa said the law goes beyond the power of Congress to regulate interstate commerce, and upsets the balance of power with states.<P>Robert O'Neil of The Thomas Jefferson Center for theProtection of Free Expression says, &quot;I have confidence thatthe political process won't extend these doctrines beyond abortionclinics.&quot;<P>He notes that the Supreme Court has declared overthe years that certain kinds of &quot;fighting words&quot; andother expressions that incite &quot;imminent lawless action&quot;are not protected by the First Amendment. The cases include <I>Chaplinsky</I>v. <I>New Hampshire</I> (1942) and <I>Brandenburg</I> v. <I>Ohio</I>(1969). A classic example of unprotected speech is shouting &quot;Fire!&quot;in a crowded theater and causing a stampede.<P>But the court has not extended those rulings to other contexts in which the connection between speech and action is more tenuous. At a philosophical level, drawing such a connection is impossible, says Franklyn Haiman of Northwestern University, because &quot;it falsely presumes that human beings are inanimate objects that have no consciousness, make no decisions and react mechanically to stimuli.&quot;Others on both sides of the abortion debate also say that laws alreadyon the books are sufficient to handle clinic violence and thattargeting abortion protesters would endanger the First Amendment.<P>&quot;There is an extraordinarily serious problem of violence at clinics,&quot; says Steve Shapiro of the American Civil Liberties Union, whichsupports abortion rights. &quot;But I don't think the solutionis to tinker with the First Amendment. The First Amendment doesnot protect terrorism.&quot;<P>Jay Sekulow of the American Center for Law and Justice, which defends clinic protesters, also says the free-speech rights of peaceful demonstrators should not be interfered with because of the recent violence.&quot;<P>You can't hold Martin Luther King's peaceful civil disobedience responsiblefor the Black Panthers,&quot; say Sekulow. &quot;There's a distinctionbetween robust debate and violence.&quot; <P>Copyright 1995 The Freedom Forum First Amendment Center<A HREF="http://www.fac.org">http://www.fac.org</A> </BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
