<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Court Decision: Going Limp Is NOT Resisting Arrest</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/refsbut.gif" ALT="REFERENCES" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/legaban.gif" ALT="Legal Materials" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Court Decision: Resisting Arrest</H3><BLOCKQUOTE><I>A New York judge decides that going limp is NOT resisting arrest.</I><P></BLOCKQUOTE><H3>Court Decision: Dismissal In The Interests Of Justice</H3><BLOCKQUOTE><I>St. Patrick's Day Parade demonstrators' arrests NOT dismissed in the interests of justice.</I><P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><BLOCKQUOTE>CRIMINAL COURT OF THE CITY OF NEW YORK<BR>COUNTY OF NEW YORK:  PART  AP-1<BR><P>DECISION AND ORDER<BR>Docket No. 950006437 et al.<P>THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEW YORK                 <P>             -against-                                                    <P>AMY BETH, et. al.,                                  <P>                 Defendants.<P>WILLIAM MOGULESCU, J.:<P>          The defendants are variously charged with resistingarrest (PL 205.30), and disorderly conduct (PL 240.20(5) and(6)).  Defendants now move for an order granting dismissal of theaccusatory instruments in the interest of justice.  Defendantsalso move for dismissal of the resisting arrest charges as beingfacially insufficient, as well as for other forms of reliefshould this court deny defendants' motion to dismiss.  The caseshave been consolidated for the purpose of this motion anddecision.                    Statement of Facts<P>          For the past several years the St. Patrick's Day Paradehas spawned what has now become a familiar battle between thesponsor of the parade, the Ancient Order of Hibernians(hereinafter &quot;AOH&quot;), and the Irish and Lesbian Gay Organization(hereinafter &quot;ILGO&quot;), the members and supporters of which aredefendants in this case.  Briefly, ILGO has pressed formeaningful inclusion in the parade, which occurs on March 17thand runs between 44th and 86th Streets on 5th Avenue.  In 1991,having earlier been denied participation, ILGO was invited by oneof the divisions of AOH to march in the parade.  When they didso, they were subjected to verbal and physical abuse along theparade route.  In the following years, ILGO did not participatein the parade, but rather held counter-protests of various forms,including an alternative march in the opposite direction of theofficial parade as well as a march along the official route priorto the sanctioned parade.  These counter-protests came about onlyafter much litigation by all the parties and often resulted inthe numerous arrests of ILGO members and supporters.<P>          The defendants' rendition of facts surrounding the 1995parade is not disputed by the People.  In December of 1994, ILGOapplied to the New York City Police Department for a permit for aprotest march for March 17, 1995, on 5th Avenue between 42nd and86th Street, beginning at 8:30 A.M.  A written reply was notreceived.  On February 21, 1995, ILGO's counsel was informed byofficials at the police department that their permit applicationwas denied.  The next day, ILGO sought and order of mandamus instate court compelling a formal response to their permit andcompelling the police department to issue ILGO a permit for theirprotest march.  The action was removed to the United StatesDistrict Court, Southern District of New York.<P>          During the proceeding in district court, the Cityindicated that it intended to deny ILGO's permit application andthat this denial was based upon its concerns regarding trafficcongestion.  In response, ILGO had offered to hold its march at10:00 A.M., rather than 8:30 A.M. as originally requested. However, the City argued that despite the fact that the AOHpermit for the parade was for 11:00 A.M., to permit ILGO to marchwould interfere with the approximately 1000 people who would beleaving St. Patrick's Cathedral after attending the pre-parademass.<P>          On March 15, 1995, the United States district court, inan opinion by the Honorable John F. Keenan, denied ILGO'sapplication [ILGO v. Bratton, 882 F. Supp 315 (SDNY 1995)].  Inso ruling the court noted that the City's decision to deny thepermit was content neutral and was narrowly tailored to meet agovernment interest.  The court further noted that ILGO had noright to carry its message to the same audience as is present atthe sanctioned parade.  Finally, as to the &quot;informal&quot; march thatoccurs prior to 11:00 A.M. at the conclusion of the mass, thecourt stated that the permit &quot;tacitly&quot; included that aspect aswell.  ILGO's appeal of Judge Kennan's decision to the SecondCircuit was unsuccessful; the district court's decision wasupheld by the Second Circuit on March 16, 1995, in the per curiumdecision [ILGO V, Bratton, 52 F.2d 311 (2d Cir. 1995)].  This wasILGO's final effort at litigating the issue prior to the parade.<P>          In March 17, 1995, at 9:30 A.M., the defendants,proceeding en masse up Fifth Avenue, were arrested between 41stand 42nd Street.  For those charged by way as of a misdemeanorcomplaint, the facts are alleged as follows:<P>          1.   Deponent observed a large group of demonstrators          on Fifth Avenue in the street, between 41st and 42nd          Streets;<BR>           2.   Deponent observed that at the time the       demonstrators began walking on Fifth Avenue, Fifth          Avenue (south of 42nd Street) was open to vehicular         traffic;<BR>           3.   Deponent observed the demonstrators enter onto          Fifth Avenue between 41st and 42nd Street, thereby          blocking all vehicular traffic travelling south on          Fifth Avenue, causing a traffic jam;<BR>           4.   Deponent heard the defendant and demonstrators          being warned by police officials that they were        obstructing vehicular traffic and if they did not           disperse they would be arrested;<BR>           5.   Deponent heard the defendant and demonstrators          being warned by police officials that they were        obstructing vehicular traffic and if they did not           disperse they would be arrested;<BR>           6.   Deponent observed defendant seated among the          demonstrators on Fifth Avenue, thereby  continuing to          block vehicular traffic;<BR>           7.   When deponent attempted to arrest defendant,          deponent asked defendant to voluntarily walk to the          police van;<BR>           8.   Deponent then observed defendant passively resist          arrest by refusing to get up and accompany the deponent          to the police van, thus requiring some police officers          to carry the defendant [sic] away.                             <P>			Resisting Arrest<P>          Defendants move to dismiss the charges of resistingarrest for facial insufficiency.  In order to be faciallysufficient, an information must contain an accusatory part and afactual part alleging facts of an evidentiary charactersupporting or tending to support the charges.  CPL 100.15(1)(3). Further, the allegations of the factual part of the information,along with any supporting depositions, must provide reasonablecause to believe that defendant committed the offense charged. CPL 100.40(1)(b).  Nonhearsay factual allegations mustestablish, if true, every element of the offense charged anddefendant's commission thereof.  CPL 100.40(1)(c).<P>          Penal Law 205.30 states that:          A person is guilty or resisting arrest when he         intentionally prevents or attempts to prevent a police          officer from effectuating and authorized arrest of          himself or another person (emphasis added).<P>          Defendants contend that in the absence of anyaffirmative act, passive resistance, or merely going limp, doesnot constitute resisting arrest.  The People counter that thestatute does not require an affirmative act, noting that nowherein the history or language of the statute is there such arequirement.  Rather, the People argue that the charge simplynecessitates a refusal to submit to the authority of thearresting officer.  This court disagrees with the People, andfinds that a consideration of the applicable section of the PenalLaw, the predecessor statute, as well as cases interpreting thatstatute, compels the opposite conclusion.<P>          The predecessor statute to the current resisting arreststatute required a finding of guilt where a person &quot;wilfullyresists, delays or obstructs a police officer in discharging, orattempting to discharge, a duty of his office.&quot;  Penal Code of1909, 1851.  Under this section there exists a line of caseswhich hold that passive resistance constitutes the crime ofresisting arrest.  In People v. Crayton, 55 Misc. 2d 213 (App.Term 1st Dept. 1967) the court, in upholding defendants'convictions for resisting arrest where defendants went limp,noted &quot;Section 1851 of the Penal Law explicitly includes delayand obstruction in any form in addition to physical resistance. Id. at 216 (emphasis supplied).  Similarly, in People v.Williams, 25 NY2d 86 (1969), the Court of Appeals, in findingthat appellant's passive resistance constituted resisting arrest,stated that &quot;each of the appellants delayed his own arrest andnecessarily the arrest of the others.&quot;  Id. at 90.  Clearly, inthese cases the language of &quot;delay&quot; and &quot;obstructs&quot; was the basisof the courts' findings.  See People v. Knight, 35 Misc. 2d 216(1962) (&quot;to interfere and obstruct and delay within section 1851of the Penal Law does not and need not require active resistanceand force ....&quot;  Id. at 222).<P>          In contrast, the revised section compels a differentfinding.  In People v. McDaniel, 154 Misc. 2d 89 (App. Term 2dDept. 1992), lv. to app.denied, 81 NY2d 889 (1993), defendants,who were participating in an antiabortion protest, blocked theentrance of a building.  When the police arrived to arrestdefendants they were either seated or in the &quot;fetal position&quot; andhad to be carried from the property in order for the officers toeffectuate their arrests.  Distinguishing 1851 of the Penal Codefrom the current statute, the court noted the absence of thewords &quot;delays and obstructs&quot; from the revised provision and heldthat defendants' inaction did not constitute resisting arrest. The court stated:<P>               The conduct of the defendants ...               did not prevent the officers from               effecting and authorized arrest....               [T]here has been no citation to               this court of any statute, rule or               ordinance that requires a defendant               arrested and so long as the               defendant does not affirmatively               act to resist the arrest than here               is no independently unlawful act               that the defendant is committing.               Id. at 2. (citation omitted).  <P>In reaching this decision, the court points to the rationale employed by the appellate court in a related appeal, [People v. Heiner, NYLJ, July 5, 1991, p. 30, col. 2 (App. Term 2d Dept.)], wherein that court found that passive resistance does not amount to obstructing governmentaladministration.<P>          The McDaniel court relied on the Court of Appealsholding in People v. Stevenson, 31 NY2d 108 (1972), in support ofits position.  Oddly, the People now also rely on Stevenson toadvance their claim.  However, rather than buttress the People'scase, the facts of that case lend further support for defendants'position herein.  In Stevenson, the defendant, upon being told hewas under arrest, began &quot; 'backing up ... and started throwingboth hands, closed fists, swinging both hands.'  A scuffle ensuedduring which [the officer] was shoved into the car and bumped....&quot;  Id. at 110.<P>          Although it is clear that the defendant in Stevensonacted forcefully to resist the arrest, the Court of Appeals wenton to quote the practice commentary where it states that it isnot necessary that a defendant use force or violence inobstructing the officer.  It is enough that he engaged in sameconduct with the intent of preventing the officer from effectingan authorized arrest of himself or another person.&quot;  PracticeCommentary, McKinney's Cons. Law of NY, Book 39, Penal Law,201.30, p. 677 (emphasis supplied).  It is clear that someconduct is meant to encompass something more than inaction.<P>         The defendants in this case had seated themselves onthe roadway of Fifth Avenue prior to their arrests.  Theirrefusal to assist in the arrest, &quot;by refusing to get up andaccompany [the police] to the police van' (see complaints) ishardly conduct engaged in with the intent to prevent an arrest. Further, the &quot;conduct&quot; of the defendants in sitting down occurredprior to their arrests.  The defendants neither prevented norattempted to prevent their arrests.  They simply refused to aidthe police on effectuating the arrest.<P>          The legislature affirmatively modified the resistingarrest statute to remove any reference to resisting by delayingan arrest.  The legislature must be credited with understandingthe import of the change in the law.  In light of themodification of the statute and the weight of the judicialauthority, this court finds that the defendants' refusal toassist the police in making their arrest easier does notconstitute the crime of resisting arrest.  Accordingly, thischarge is dismissed.<P>          		Motion to Dismiss in the Interest of Justice<P>          All defendants have moved to dismiss the charges in theinterest of justice pursuant to CPL 170.40.<P>          The defendants' motions to dismiss in the interest ofjustice must be determined upon consideration of the ten factorsenumerated in CPL 170.40(1):<P>          (a)  the seriousness and circumstances of the offense;<BR>          (b)  the extent of harm caused by the offense;<BR>          (c)  the evidence of guilt, whether admissible or               inadmissible at trial;<BR>           (d)  the history, character and condition of the            defendant;<BR>           (e)  any exceptionally serious misconduct of law            enforcement personnel in the investigation, arrest               and prosecution of the defendant.<BR>           (f)  the purpose and effect of imposing upon the            defendant a sentence authorized for the offense;<BR>           (g)  the impact of a dismissal upon the safety or               welfare of the community;<BR>           (h)  the impact of a dismissal upon the confidence of               the public in the criminal justice system;<BR>           (i)  where the court deems it appropriate, the attitude               of the complainant or victim with the respect to               the motion;<BR>           (j)  any other relevant fact indicating that a              judgment of conviction would serve no useful                purpose.<P>          While a Clayton motion [People v.Clayton, 41 AD2d 204(2d Dept. 1973)] may be granted at the discretion of the court,such discretion should be exercised cautiously and the reliefgranted sparingly.  See People v. Andrew, 78 AD2d 683 (2d Dept.1980).  After considerations of the interests of the defendant,the complainant and the community, a motion to dismiss in theinterest of justice should be granted only in those instanceswhere a miscarriage of justice would result from the adherence tothe strict letter of the law.  See People v. Belkota, 50 AD2d 118(4th Dept. 1975); People v. Andrew, supra.  Applying theseconsiderations to the case herein, this court find that thedefendants have failed to establish the existence of a compellingfactor which would render the prosecution fundamentally unjust. See People v. Schlessel 104 AD2d 501 (2d Dept. 1984).<P>          The defendants advance several arguments in support oftheir motion.  In essence, defendants point out the nonseriousnature of the offense, a claim which is buttressed not just bylack of injury to persons or property, but by the offers ofadjournments in contemplation of dismissal made by the trialassistant.  Defendants also contend that their protest was anexercise of their constitutional rights and that the continuedprosecution would be an abrogation of those rights.  Further,defendants emphasize that their protest, which only resulted whenall avenues but for an appeal to the United States Supreme Courtwere exhausted, was a peaceful attempt not just to demonstrateagainst their exclusion from the parade but to bring forth thebroader issue of discrimination against the lesbian and gaycommunity.<P>          This court has carefully considered all the defendants'arguments and affidavits submitted in support thereof.  While thecourt applauds ILGO's peaceful attempts to eradicate a history ofsocial wrongs and does not question the sincerity of defendantsarguments, the strong moral conviction which the defendantsprofess cannot be used as a shield from prosecution,  &quot;It iscommonly conceded that the exercise of a moral judgment based upon individual standards does not carry with it ... immunityfrom punishment for a breach of the law&quot;.  United States v.Kroncke, 459 F.2d 697, 703 (8th Cir. 1972), quoting, UnitedStates v. Moylan, 417 F.2d 1002, 1008-1009 (4th Cir. 1969), cert.denied, 397 US 910 (1970).  While defendants advanced their causein a peaceful manner, they nonetheless did so breaking the lawand infringing upon the rights of those pedestrians who wereunable to proceed and those motorists who were caught in thetraffic blockage caused by their protest.<P>          Further, this court rejects defendants argument thatthis prosecution is a violation of their first amendment rights. Indeed, the first amendment does not ensure the absolute right toany person to express his or her view at any time and in a anyplace.  Heffron v. International Social for KrishnaConsciousness, 452 US 640 (1981); Adderley v. Florida, 385 US 39(1966); Olviviera v. Ward, 801 F.2d 602 (2d.Cir 1986).  Rather, aperson's first amendment right will be subjected to reasonableregulation and control in the interest of public safety andorder.  See Cox v. New Hampshire, 312 US 569 (1941)(municipality's authority to impose regulations regarding the useof public highways is not inconsistent with civil liberties).<P>          Thus, reasonable &quot;time, place and manner&quot; restrictionshave been upheld despite the fact that such might infringe upondefendant's first amendment right.  Grayned v. City of Rockland,408 US 10 (1972).  In this regard, both provisions of thedisorderly conduct statute under which defendants stand charged[PL 240.02(5) and (6)] have been held to be a reasonable time,place and manner restriction.  See People v. Pearl, 66 Misc. 2d502 (App. Term 1st Dept. 1971); People v. Maher, 137 Misc. 2d 162(Crim. Ct. NY Co. 1987), aff'd, 142 Misc. 2d 977 (App. Term 1stDept.) app. denied, 74 NY2d 794 (1989); People v. Bakolas, 108Misc. 2d 74 (City Ct. Rochester 1981), rev'd on other grounds,113 Misc. 2d 832 (County Ct., Monroe County 1982), aff'd, 59 NY2d51 (1983),<P>          In contrast to the civil rights cases now relied uponby defendants [see e.g., Shuttleworth v. Birmingham, 373 US 262(1963)], here defendants had available other legal avenues as ameans to publish their message.  Furthermore, the defendants werefully aware that their actions would result in their arrests. The arrests were part of their advocacy, a statement of theintensity of their belief in the correctness of their positionand an indication that they were willing to put their bodiessymbolically on the line in support of their cause.  Thedefendants' actions were obviously motivated by righteousindignation at discrimination based on sexual orientation. Nevertheless, the moral validity of the ends sought is notcontrolling.  Notwithstanding what one may feel about the justiceof their cause, the extraordinary remedy of dismissal in theinterest of justice is simply not warranted in these cases.<P>          The motion to dismiss pursuant to CPL 170.40 isdenied......<P>Dated:  October 19, 1995<BR>         New York, New York<P><P>                                   ___________________________<BR>                                    WILLIAM MOGULESCU<BR>                                    Judge of the Criminal Court<P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
