<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Insufficiency Of Prosecutor's Information</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/refsbut.gif" ALT="REFERENCES" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/legaban.gif" ALT="Legal Materials" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Motion To Dismiss: Insufficiency Of Prosecutor's Information</H3><BLOCKQUOTE><I>Here is an excerpt of a motion to dismiss Riot and Disorderly Conduct charges on the grounds of "facial insufficiency", that the factual allegations were insufficient to support the offenses charged.</I><P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><BLOCKQUOTE>CRIMINAL COURT OF THE CITY OF NEW YORK<BR>COUNTY OF NEW YORK: PART AP 3<P>THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEW YORK,<P>		   -against-                      <P>PAUL DEAN,                              	Docket No. 94N039310<P>                   Defendant.<P>....	I.	MOTION TO DISMISS THE INFORMATION<P>	To be sufficient, an information must contain factual allegations which &quot;establish, if true, every element of the offense charged and the defendant's commission thereof.&quot;  C.P.L. Sec. 100.40(1)(c).  See People v. Alejandro, 70 N.Y.2d 133, 517 N.Y.S.2d 927, 511 N.E.2d 71 (1987).  The information here essentially alleges that defendant was standing with a crowd in which someone threw a bottle, and that individuals other than the defendant chanted political slogans.  These allegations do not constitute the offenses charged, and the information therefore must be dismissed.<P>	A.	Riot in the Second Degree<P>	&quot;A person is guilty of riot in the second degree when, simultaneously with four or more other persons, he engages in tumultuous and violent conduct and thereby intentionally or recklessly causes or creates a grave risk of causing public alarm.&quot;  Penal Law Sec. 240.05.  The phrase &quot;'&quot;tumultuous and violent conduct&quot;...means much more than mere loud noise or ordinary disturbance.  &quot;It is designed to connote frightening mob behavior involving ominous threats of injury , stone throwing or other such terrorizing acts.&quot;'&quot;  People v. Morales, 601 N.Y.S.2d 261, 262 (N.Y.C. Crim. Ct., N.Y. Cnty.  1993)(quoting McKinney's Practice Commentary to Sec. 240.05; internal quotation omitted); see also People v. Biltsted, N.Y.L.J., June 10, 1991, p. 34, col. 3 (N.Y.C. Crim. Ct., N.Y.Cnty.).<P>	In this case, the information states that the deponent &quot;observed the defendant, along with a group of about thirty to forty others, throw a bottle at the police...&quot;  Assuming that thirty people did not, together, all directly participate in throwing one bottle, this sentence can only describe one or two scenarios:  someone other than the defendant threw a bottle, or the defendant threw a bottle.  If the former, then the defendant has not engaged in any &quot;violent&quot; or &quot;tumultuous&quot; conduct and is not guilty of riot.  If the latter, then four or more other persons have not simultaneously engaged in any such conduct, and again, defendant is not guilty of riot.<P>	In sum, the throwing of a bottle by one person in a crowd is not a &quot;riot&quot; under the Penal Law, and this count of the information consequently must be dismissed.<P>	B.	Inciting to Riot<P>	1.	Defendant is not Alleged to Have Made Any Statements<P>	&quot;A person is guilty of inciting to riot when he urges ten or more persons to engage in tumultuous and violent conduct of a kind likely to create public alarm.&quot;  Penal law Sec. 240.08.  The information here states that &quot;defendant was standing with a crowd who were [sic] yelling and screaming fighting words, such as 'Riot,' 'No more,' 'No more,' 'No police state'...&quot; Defendant is not alleged to have said a word; it is the crowd next to which he was standing that supposedly made remarks.  The factual accusations, therefore, are insufficient to support a charge of inciting to riot against the defendant, and this count must be dismissed.<P>	2.	The Alleged Comments are Protected Political Speech and	Are Not Incitement                                    <P>	In any event, the words alleged to have been used by others in the crowd are not sufficient to establish inciting to riot.  To support such a charge consistent with the first Amendment, &quot;defendant's conduct must be alleged to constitute an incitement that is both directed towards and likely to produce imminent violent and tumultuous conduct.&quot;  Biltsted, N.Y.L.J., June 10, 1991, p. 34, at col. 2 (citing Brandenburg v. Ohio, 395 U.S. 444 (1969); other citations omitted).  &quot;[T]he First Amendment protects a significant amount of verbal criticism and challenge directed at police officers.&quot; id., at col. 4 (citing Houston v. Hill, 107 U.S. 444, 451 (1987); other citations omitted), and statements merely causing &quot;'a hateful and negative reaction to police officers...'...do not implicate criminal liability under P.L. Sec. 240.08&quot;  People v. White, N.Y.L.J., August 3, 1990, p. 18, col. 6 (N.Y.C. Crim. Ct, N.Y. Cnty.)(quoting People v. Mighty, 142 Missc.2d 37, 40, 535 N.Y.S.2d 944, 946 (Rochester City Ct.  1988)).  For instance, a &quot;defendant is entitled to express dissatisfaction with official police action and urge other citizens to, by means of inaction, defy a police order,&quot; as such statements are &quot;within the ambit of protected speech.&quot;  People v. Cawley, N.Y.L.J., June 14, 1991, p. 24, col. 6 (N.Y.C. Crim. Ct., Bx. Cnty.).<P>	Under these standards, the following statements have been held not to constitute inciting to riot: &quot;fuck the police, they can't tell us what to do; there are more of us than there are of him; ...we don't have to listen; there are more of us that [sic] him,&quot; id., at col. 5,; &quot;Pigs go home this is our park; pigs get out,&quot; Bilsted, N.Y.L.J., June 10, 1991, p. 34, at col. 2; urging others &quot;to ignore the officers' instructions to leave,&quot; followed by &quot;a barrage of abusive language, name calling and accusations of racism,&quot; Mighty, 535 N.Y.S.2d at 945; and &quot;fight the power, no more honkies, no more Teaneck,&quot; White, N.Y.L.J., August 3, 1990, p. 18, at col. 6.<P>	The words allegedly spoken by the crowd here are even less likely to incite violence than the above examples.  &quot;No police state&quot; is pure First Amendment-protected speech and does not urge action of any kind.  &quot;No more, no more,&quot; is somewhat meaningless, and the lone word &quot;riot&quot; apparently is a simple description of police behavior, in the speaker's opinion.  None of these comments is intended to or is likely to produce imminent violence, and this count must be dismissed pursuant to both the statute and the First Amendment.<P>	C.	Disorderly Conduct<P>	&quot; A person is guilty of disorderly conduct when, with intent to cause public inconvenience, annoyance or alarm, or recklessly creating a risk thereof, he engages in fighting or in violent, tumultuous or threatening behavior...&quot;  Penal law Sec. 240.20(1).  The information here does not allege that defendant engaged in fighting, and, as explained above, supra at Sec. I(A), defendant also is not alleged to have personally engaged in any &quot;violent, tumultuous or threatening behavior.&quot;  Defendant, rather, is accused of standing with a crowd after the police had ordered the crowd to leave.  This is not &quot;'frightening mob behavior involving ominous threats of injury,'&quot;  Morales, 601 N.Y.S.2d, at 262 (quotation omitted), and this count as well must be dismissed.<P>Dated:  New York, New York<BR>	   July 12, 1994<P>							_____________________________<BR>								ATTORNEY FOR DEFENDANT<P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
