<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Demonstrator's Site: Motion To Dismiss: In The Interests Of Justice</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#D90000" ALINK="#FFFF00"><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=500><TR><TD><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/refsbut.gif" ALT="REFERENCES" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=90><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../gifs/legaban.gif" ALT="Legal Materials" HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=410 HSPACE=0><P></TD></TR><TR><TD><H3>Motion To Dismiss: In The Interests Of Justice</H3><BLOCKQUOTE><I>This is an excerpt of a motion to dismiss Disorderly Conduct and Resisting Arrest charges made against AIDS activists who demonstrated in the St. Patricks Day parade without an invitation.</I><P></BLOCKQUOTE><HR><BLOCKQUOTE>CRIMINAL COURT OF THE CITY OF NEW YORK<BR>COUNTY OF NEW YORK: PART AP 3<P>THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEW YORK,<P>		   -against-                      <P>JILL ENZMANN, THOMAS LINDENFELD ...(and 29 others)                	Docket No. 94N039310<P>                   Defendants.<p>(The defendant AIDS-activists were arrested participating in the New York City St. Patrick's Day parade without an invitation.)<p>...II.       Dismissal In The Interests of Justice is Appropriate<p>CPL. Sec. 170.40 allows the trier of fact to dismiss charges against individuals inthe furthermore of justice even if there may be no basis for dismissal, upon considering,individually and collectively, <b>the seriousness and circumstances of the offense, the extent if harmcaused by the offense, the evidence of guilt, the history, character and condition of the defendant ,any exceptional misconduct of law enforcement personnel, the purpose and effect of imposing asentence authorized for the offense, the impact of a dismissal on the safety or welfare of thecommunity, the impact of a dismissal upon public confidence in the criminal justice system, theattitude of the victim, and any other relevant fact indicating that a judgment of conviction wouldserve no useful purpose.</b>  <p>A.   The Harm That The Defendants Are Alleged To Have Caused Is Minor And Should BeWeighed Accordingly.<p>The defendants are also charged with disorderly conduct in violation of PL Sec.240.20(5).  Any harm that defendants may have caused is minor, however, when compared withthe harm that silence and nonaction cause.  Furthermore, defendants did not intend to cause harm;rather, they acted out of a moral sense of duty to the people of the City and State of New York.<p>B.   The Extent Of The Alleged Harm Was Minor.<p>If any harm was caused by the defendants, the extent of that harm was negligible. The demonstration was confined to the parade route, and caused no more inconvenience to theCity of New York than the St. Patrick's Day parade itself.  Furthermore, there was no violenceand, hence, there were no injuries.<p>C.   Defendants Are All Conscientious, Concerned Citizens<p>These defendants acted out of a sturdy moral commitment.  They are all engagedin some sort of community service.  Some volunteer their services; others are dedicatedprofessionals.  None of them have prior criminal records, and they all have extremely strongcommunity ties.<p>D.   Defendants Did  Not Intentionally Resist Arrest.<p>It cannot be proven beyond a reasonable doubt that the defendants intended toresist arrest.  A person is guilty of resisting arrest when, pursuant to PL Sec. 205.30, he or she"intentionally prevents or attempts to prevent a police officer or peace officer from effecting anauthorized arrest of himself or another person." (emphasis added.)<p>In People v. Ben-Levi, 565 N.Y.S.2d 404 (1990), the court dismissed chargesagainst ten demonstrators, pursuant to CPL Sec. 170.40 for "lack of any affirmative resistance tothe police, even though the charges include resisting arrest" (supra, at 407).<p>Defendants in the instant case were sitting in the street holding hands and singingand chanting as part of their demonstration of unity.  It was not their intent to resist arrest, nor didthey question their arrest.  No violence ensued, and there was no affirmative resistance to theirarrest.  All of the demonstrators, including these defendants, were arrested and taken intocustody.<p>E.   Conviction Would Serve No Useful Purpose.<p>In determining whether the charges against the defendants should be dismissed, theCourt is asked to weigh mitigating factors, including the purpose and affect of the sentence, theimpact of a dismissal upon the public, the attitude of the complainant, and any other relevant factthat a judgment of conviction would serve no useful purpose.<p>In People v. Ben-Levi, supra, the Court analyzed those facts and, pursuant to CPLSec. 170.40, dismissed charges that were strikingly similar to the instant case.<p>The ten defendants in Ben-Levi, demonstrating against New York City'sinadequate response to the AIDS epidemic, were charged with obstructing vehicular traffic andresisting arrest.  The Court reasoned that, although the defendants had committed the allegedacts, the demonstration involved "no offensive conduct and an objective as laudable as that of thedefendants here, with an impact of unlawful activity as minimal as occurred here, should beentitled  to be treated within approach grounded in the principles of expression, as well as withcompassion, at least as to those defendants with no prior record of unlawful activity." (supra, at407.)<p>The Court considered the defendants' motives, the lack of offensive conduct, thepeacefulness of their actions, the lack of affirmative resistance to the police, and the lack ofphysical harm to any person or property.<p>Considering the total circumstances and measuring them against the criteria of PLSec. 170.40, the court noted "If an act as anathema to so many Americans as the burning of the American flag is to be conducted on constitutional principles of value of freedom of expression(see Texas v. Johnson, 491 U.S. 397, 109 S.Ct. 2533, 105 L.Ed.2d 342 [1989]), then it certainlywould seem that demonstrations involving no offensive conduct and objective laudable as that ofthe defendants here, with an impact of unlawful activity as minimal as occurred here, should beentitled to be treated with as approach grounded in the principles of freedom of expression, aswell as with compassion, at least as to those defendants with no record of prior unlawful activity."<p>The Ben-Levi court was careful to note several times that the charges againstdefendants were dismissed "not because the defendants' actions involved a constitutionallyprotected form of free expression or because such acts did not impinge upon the rights of others. On the contrary, the defendants' actions did cause inconvenience to motorists and pedestrians. But, as I have noted, CPL Sec. 170.40 clearly does not contemplate application only to thosecases where no violation of law at all has occurred." (supra, at 407.)<p>Defendants in the instant case acted out of the same motives as did defendants inBen-Levi.  Their  actions were virtually the same.  They are entitled to the same approach,grounded in the principles of freedom of expression, compassion, and justice. <p>(The defendant AIDS-activists were arrested participating in the New York City St. Patrick's Day parade without an invitation.)<p>...II.       Dismissal In The Interests of Justice is Appropriate<p>CPL. Sec. 170.40 allows the trier of fact to dismiss charges against individuals inthe furthermore of justice even if there may be no basis for dismissal, upon considering,individually and collectively, the seriousness and circumstances of the offense, the extent if harmcaused by the offense, the evidence of guilt, the history, character and condition of the defendant ,any exceptional misconduct of law enforcement personnel, the purpose and effect of imposing asentence authorized for the offense, the impact of a dismissal on the safety or welfare of thecommunity, the impact of a dismissal upon public confidence in the criminal justice system, theattitude of the victim, and any other relevant fact indicating that a judgment of conviction wouldserve no useful purpose.  <p>A.   The Harm That The Defendants Are Alleged To Have Caused Is Minor And Should BeWeighed Accordingly.<p>The defendants are also charged with disorderly conduct in violation of PL Sec.240.20(5).  Any harm that defendants may have caused is minor, however, when compared withthe harm that silence and nonaction cause.  Furthermore, defendants did not intend to cause harm;rather, they acted out of a moral sense of duty to the people of the City and State of New York.<p>B.   The Extent Of The Alleged Harm Was Minor.<p>If any harm was caused by the defendants, the extent of that harm was negligible. The demonstration was confined to the parade route, and caused no more inconvenience to theCity of New York than the St. Patrick's Day parade itself.  Furthermore, there was no violenceand, hence, there were no injuries.<p>C.   Defendants Are All Conscientious, Concerned Citizens<p>These defendants acted out of a sturdy moral commitment.  They are all engagedin some sort of community service.  Some volunteer their services; others are dedicatedprofessionals.  None of them have prior criminal records, and they all have extremely strongcommunity ties.<p>D.   Defendants Did  Not Intentionally Resist Arrest.<p>It cannot be proven beyond a reasonable doubt that the defendants intended toresist arrest.  A person is guilty of resisting arrest when, pursuant to PL Sec. 205.30, he or she"intentionally prevents or attempts to prevent a police officer or peace officer from effecting anauthorized arrest of himself or another person." (emphasis added.)<p>In People v. Ben-Levi, 565 N.Y.S.2d 404 (1990), the court dismissed chargesagainst ten demonstrators, pursuant to CPL Sec. 170.40 for "lack of any affirmative resistance tothe police, even though the charges include resisting arrest" (supra, at 407).<p>Defendants in the instant case were sitting in the street holding hands and singingand chanting as part of their demonstration of unity.  It was not their intent to resist arrest, nor didthey question their arrest.  No violence ensued, and there was no affirmative resistance to theirarrest.  All of the demonstrators, including these defendants, were arrested and taken intocustody.<p>E.   Conviction Would Serve No Useful Purpose.<p>In determining whether the charges against the defendants should be dismissed, theCourt is asked to weigh mitigating factors, including the purpose and affect of the sentence, theimpact of a dismissal upon the public, the attitude of the complainant, and any other relevant factthat a judgment of conviction would serve no useful purpose.<p>In People v. Ben-Levi, supra, the Court analyzed those facts and, pursuant to CPLSec. 170.40, dismissed charges that were strikingly similar to the instant case.<p>The ten defendants in Ben-Levi, demonstrating against New York City'sinadequate response to the AIDS epidemic, were charged with obstructing vehicular traffic andresisting arrest.  The Court reasoned that, although the defendants had committed the allegedacts, the demonstration involved "no offensive conduct and an objective as laudable as that of thedefendants here, with an impact of unlawful activity as minimal as occurred here, should beentitled  to be treated within approach grounded in the principles of expression, as well as withcompassion, at least as to those defendants with no prior record of unlawful activity." (supra, at407.)<p>The Court considered the defendants' motives, the lack of offensive conduct, thepeacefulness of their actions, the lack of affirmative resistance to the police, and the lack ofphysical harm to any person or property.<p>Considering the total circumstances and measuring them against the criteria of PLSec. 170.40, the court noted "If an act as anathema to so many Americans as the burning of the American flag is to be conducted on constitutional principles of value of freedom of expression(see Texas v. Johnson, 491 U.S. 397, 109 S.Ct. 2533, 105 L.Ed.2d 342 [1989]), then it certainlywould seem that demonstrations involving no offensive conduct and objective laudable as that ofthe defendants here, with an impact of unlawful activity as minimal as occurred here, should beentitled to be treated with as approach grounded in the principles of freedom of expression, aswell as with compassion, at least as to those defendants with no record of prior unlawful activity."<p>The Ben-Levi court was careful to note several times that the charges againstdefendants were dismissed "not because the defendants' actions involved a constitutionallyprotected form of free expression or because such acts did not impinge upon the rights of others. On the contrary, the defendants' actions did cause inconvenience to motorists and pedestrians. But, as I have noted, CPL Sec. 170.40 clearly does not contemplate application only to thosecases where no violation of law at all has occurred." (supra, at 407.)<p>Defendants in the instant case acted out of the same motives as did defendants inBen-Levi.  Their  actions were virtually the same.  They are entitled to the same approach,grounded in the principles of freedom of expression, compassion, and justice. <P>Dated:  New York, New York<BR>	   March 3, 1995<P>							_____________________________<BR>								ATTORNEY FOR DEFENDANT<P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><HR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../../gifs/backbar.gif" ALT="BACK" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
