<H2>COMING EVENTS</H2><p>

<TABLE BORDER>
<TR><TH>DATE</TH><TH>EVENT</TH></TR>





<P>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
<TD><STRONG>Feb., 1997</STRONG>
<BR>INTERNET</TD>
<TD><STRONG>INTERNET COURSE ON RISK BEHAVIOR</STRONG><br>

A "virtual classroom" seminar on Risk Homeostasis Theory and its implications for risk-taking behavior will be conducted early in the new year by Minnesota's St. Cloud State University. The program will be co-taught by Dr. John Palmer, Assistant Dean of the College of Education at St. Cloud State University and Professor Gerald J. S. Wilde in the Department of Psychology at Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario. Gerald Wilde is the originator of the theory of risk homeostasis and author of the book Target Risk: Dealing with the dangers of death, disease and damage in everyday decisions (available at the Village Web site - www.pde.drivers.com). <br>
The program will be self-paced, with students operating within the time frame of the academic calendar. To complete the program, students will be asked to carry out a project that implements a strategy based on their analysis of risk taking behavior and the theory of risk homeostasis. If you would like more information about the program please send your request to: <br>
<B>John W. Palmer, Ph.D.,<br>
Interim Assistant Dean<br>
College of Education,<br>
St. Cloud State University<br>
720-4th Ave. South<br>
St. Cloud, MN 56301</B><br>
E-Mail: <A HREF=mailto:jpalmer@tigger.stcloud.msus.edu>jpalmer@tigger.stcloud.msus.edu</A> <br>
Further information will be posted at the Traffic Safety Information Village Web site as details are finalized. 
</TD></TR><P>
<P>


<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
