<html><head>
<title>WASHINGTON SUMMIT ON DRIVER ED</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>WASHINGTON SUMMIT ON DRIVER ED</h2>
<p><html>

<head>

<title>Washington Summit</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="ffffff" text="000044" link="0000ff" vlink="660099">





<p>

<blockquote>

A very remarkable "summit" meeting took place in Washington D.C. on September 16 and 17. The meeting was remarkable for at least two reasons­it was the first major initiative aimed at improving driver performance in almost two decades; and, most remarkable of all,  it had the unique goal of bringing together a Gulf-War-style alliance of powerful private, public and non-profit partners in an all-out struggle against a common enemy, the casualty toll on our roads. <P>



The meeting had, in the best tradition of Washington summits, a goodly share of noble spirit, special interest maneuverings, and what the locals called "beltway politics." When it was over, the bold new initiative had been set in motion but, again in the best tradition of Washington summits, there remained a lot work to be done to weld together the diverse interests represented by the delegates to the summit. <P>



When the meeting ended, a planning group had been set up with a 90-day agenda that includes the establishment of a Coalition for the Improvement of Youthful Driver Performance as a 501C3 non-profit foundation, the goal of refining the objectives of the Coalition, and the establishment of a framework through which other major corporations can contribute to the effort. <P>

</blockquote>

<H3>Why a summit?</H3>

<blockquote>



Traffic crashes have become a sort of "white noise" of modern life. We read about them, hear about them, see the aftermath in the media and sit in traffic tie-ups caused by them, and yet they have become a background hum in the everyday, familiar world of roadway traffic. We may fear them but we don't dread them. And we need to drive, so we allow the crash problem to be pushed into the background of our consciousness by things we do dread, such as AIDS, drugs, crime and plane crashes. And yet, road crashes remain, particularly for teenagers, the most likely cause of injury or death.  <P>



Unfortunately, in recent years, efforts to combat the crash problem have suffered from near-paralysing uncertainty about what to do. There are so many factors affecting the casualty rate from road crashes that it's extremely difficult to isolate the effectiveness of any one remedy. <P>



We've made cars and roads much safer but those efforts, while effective, show no signs of resolving the problem. Safety experts are in general agreement that we must now focus on drivers, but here there's a huge challenge and a contradiction­most people believe in the efficacy of training and education, but in driving, the research community are telling us that it doesn't produce safer drivers and even increases risk by increasing the exposure of young novice drivers. <P>



Intuitively, most people agree that training and education are good. After all, a hefty chunk of the national budget of every industrialized country in the world is channeled into training and education of various kinds. But in driving, this intuitive agreement about the value of training and education is matched by a frustrating failure to back up the intuition with scientific proof that they reduce crashes. <P>



The most famous, most expensive and most extensive effort to do that, the massive DeKalb County Study of the early '80s, is a good example of the difficulty of finding such proof. In comparing the crash and violation records of teenage students who took high school driver education courses with those who didn't, the study has been criticized (in hindsight, of course) on a variety of counts­for example, not providing enough behind-the-wheel time and using what we now regard as outdated concepts of how training and education should be conducted. As well, the control group of students, those who were supposed to have taken no formal education program at all, were free to take formal training on their own initiative. It's not known how many actually did. <P>



</blockquote>

<H3>The roots of the summit</H3>

<blockquote>

Interestingly, it was a project to utilize modern computer technology in driver training that set the summit idea in motion. A small group that included Ron Blue of State Farm Insurance, Dave Houston of Ford Motor Company, Ron Sonner of Kodak, and Leo Cyr and other representatives from the autoglass industry, had gathered in Bloomington, Michigan to discuss possible funding of a simulation project. <P>



Discussions at the meeting were lent a degree of urgency by the fact that, after a long period of decline, traffic crashes are on the increase again, particularly amongst teenagers. Add to this a rising chorus of complaints against the problem of bad driving, aggression and "road rage," and the simulation project began to take on a new perspective.  It became apparent to the group that no matter how well-executed and effective the project might be, it would not, in itself, offer a solution to the traffic crash problem. Any project to improve drivers and driving, the group decided, would have to be a part of a much larger offensive. <P>



The group decided to bring together a larger group of potential partners and float the idea of a powerful alliance capable of mounting such an offensive. The result was a planning session in Deerborn, Michigan on July 26.<P>



The 30 or so people who attended that meeting went through a brain-storming process facilitated by Dudley Davis, a Baltimore-based strategic planning and change management consultant. An agenda was set for the Washington summit of September 16 and 17. The focus was narrowed down to the problem of improving youthful driver performance. <P>

</blockquote>

<H3>What happened in Washington</H3>

<blockquote>

About 100 participants attended the Washington summit. A mission statement and goals had been prepared and the meeting began with the establishment of rules aimed at allowing this large and diverse group to put aside special interests and competitive instincts in pursuit of a common goal. The process kicked off with an address by Philip R. Recht, Deputy Administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA). <P>



Presentations by Dr. Allen Williams, Research Director for the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS); Dr. Allen Robinson, CEO of the American Driver and Traffic Safety Education Association; and Dr. Gary Bloomfield of the Washington State Department of Public Instruction, put brackets around the research and education perspectives on the problem.<P>



As breakout discussion groups tackled different aspects of the task of forming a coalition and giving it direction, some of the critical facets of the challenge began to take shape. Bringing awareness of the extent of the problem back to the forefront of public consciousness was high on the list, but that part would be easy for a such a high-powered coalition. More difficult would be the challenge of creating a public demand for better driving and for more knowledge and skills. Even more challenging is the problem of creating and supporting effective interventions.<P>



The latter problem was highlighted during one of the open discussion sessions. Since many of the conference participants belonged to competitive organizations, everyone was asked to refrain from selling their wares during the proceedings. But a request for input on what's happening in the world of driver awareness and improvement brought on a flood of "introductions" of individual products and services. The process turned some people off, but it was interesting and it did provide a clue to one of the big advantages of having a coalition as envisaged by the planning group­there are all kinds of things going on out there, but there isn't any coordination and strategic planning that would focus these initiatives for maximum effect. <P>



For State Farm's Ron Blue, that's exactly what the coalition is all about. "Everybody is trying to address the problem," he said,  "but I don't think anyone has a plan...we're just putting bandaids on, not trying for a cure."<P>



There are a number of roles the coalition might play, Blue points out. In addition to acting as a funnel for funding from a wide variety of sources, the coalition could act as a clearinghouse of ideas, as a forum for discussion, and possibly as an instrument of quality control if it played the role of an endorsing or certifying agent for initiatives of various kinds.<P>

</blockquote>

<H3>What's next</H3>

<blockquote>

Consultant Dudley Davis has been retained to facilitate the planning process over the next few months. Another meeting is expected sometime in October or November and efforts are under way to draw in corporate funding to finance the first year of operation. <P>



The immediate planning emphasis is on  setting up a framework that is acceptable to all particpants in the alliance, and  on laying out a clear agenda for alliance activities. The suggested framework  is a small, professionally-run organization with a board of directors and a board of trustees to which the organization is accountable. <P>



<STRONG>PDE</STRONG>  will have further articles on the progress of the coalition as developments occur. In the meantime, interviews and <strong><A HREF="/ARTICLES/restricted/partic.html">more details about the participants</A></strong>, the discussions, and the issues will be available shortly in the subscriber area of the Village. <P>

</blockquote>

<P>

<p>
