<html><head>
<title>IMPROVING TEEN DRIVING (MIRACLE IN CRYSTAL CITY)</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>IMPROVING TEEN DRIVING (MIRACLE IN CRYSTAL CITY)</h2>
<p><H3>By David Thompson</H3>
<blockquote>
Washington, D.C.-- Just south of what Beltwayers call "the district" near 
Washington's National airport, some far-sighted real estate developers in the 
'70s planned and built a commercial complex of hotels and shopping centers. 
For the name they chose <STRONG>Crystal City</STRONG> -- a memorable, optimistic handle implying specialness.<P>

For the past two days, this writer has been a part of another planning session -- 
a remarkable gathering of men and women from all over North America. 
From California to Florida, from Canada to Texas, these 100 people gathered 
in Crystal City to craft an organization and a plan called <STRONG>The National 
Coalition to Improve Youthful Driver Performance</STRONG>. We should only hope 
that their work achieves the same kind of special quality that the Crystal City 
developers probably had in mind.<P>

<H3>So what's the problem?</H3>

The automobile is the number-one cause of death among young people 
between 14 and 24 years of age. While traffic speed and density increase, while 
accident rates and costs drive up insurance rates; while the death and 
disfigurement tolls mount; government bodies everywhere have been busily 
chopping away at the very root of the tree -- driver training and improvement. 
Overall, the problem is growing faster than solutions are being invented.<P>

<H3>We need a leader</H3>

The National Coalition to Improve Youthful Driver Performance was 
originally conceived by a small group led by Ron Blue of State Farm 
Insurance and Dave Houston of Ford. These men quickly called their 
counterparts at the other insurance carriers and at Chrysler and General 
Motors. Their objective was simple: to find the root causes of this national 
crisis among teenaged drivers and to figure out what can be done about it. 
Then they made an incredibly optimistic assumption -- that it might be 
possible to enlist the unreserved involvement and support of what they call 
the "stakeholders" -- auto manufacturers; insurance companies; safety 
organizations such as the National Safety Council, the AAA, the Transportation 
Research Board; government agencies such as the National Highway Traffic 
Safety Administration and the Federal Highway Administration; educational 
groups such as ADTSEA, the driving teachers' professional association; MADD, 
SADD and others.<P>

Their hope was that if the resources and experience of this collective could 
somehow be focused on the problem of teenaged drivers, we could create 
change faster and more effectively than if we waited for government alone to 
address the problem. Of course, for that to happen, the stakeholders would 
have to put aside their normal competitive attitudes, their senses of turf, self-protection and promotion, their pride and prejudices, and freely cooperate 
towards solutions. <P>

So Ron Blue and his group sought out a man named Dudley Davis, a 
professional who is skilled in the techniques of organizing and guiding such a 
disparate group toward common ground. For two days in Crystal City, the 100 
participants broke away into working groups to address such matters as how 
to organize the effort administratively, how to fund it, how to create public 
awareness of the problems and solutions, what fundamental changes should 
occur and how to move forward. <P>

<H3>And the envelope, please</H3>

Here is the miracle of Crystal City. Contrary to the expectations of a majority of the participants, the process worked. At the final session of the 
conference, where each of the working groups came to report the progress 
they had made, the accomplishments were obvious. The <STRONG>Research</STRONG> group 
presented a realistic plan for evaluating potential solutions. The <STRONG>Education</STRONG> 
group proposed that we develop a set of national standards for granting a 
driver's license and if people don't meet these standards, they shouldn't be 
allowed to drive (they also concluded that the only way to improve the driver 
training curriculum and the instructor corps is through clear and higher 
standards). The <STRONG>Awareness</STRONG> group proposed a plan for generating public 
awareness of the problem and multi-level support for the solutions. The 
<STRONG>Organization</STRONG> group produced the biggest miracle of all. They rejected the idea 
that all of these goals might be accomplished through one of the existing 
organizations. The leader of one of these organizations, who is a major player 
in the overall process, said it best when asked why he did not recommend 
that all this activity be channeled through his organization. "I have considered it," he said, "and I believe that for this effort to succeed, it 
must not carry the baggage of the past." At the moment that was said, I began 
to believe that a miracle was occurring and that there was hope amidst 
hopelessness. Great things happen when people put cause above self and 
that's what happened in Crystal City.<P>

The automobile, which used to be an instrument of freedom and joy, is being 
transformed into a threatening, annoying, necessary evil. Part of that 
transformation is the deterioration of the quality of drivers. So I'm excited. 
The willingness of the people I saw in Crystal City to face reality, to set aside 
petty differences, to roll up their sleeves and to start building a different 
future, is thrilling beyond measure. Even though we were inside the beltway, 
the thinking was, as Dudley Davis urged, "Way outside the box."<P>

I hope the miracle in Crystal City will be sustained, because the most satisfying 
experiences in human nature are the accomplishment of goals. An "A", a 
raise, a promotion, a child going through college -- these are the things that make 
human experiences understandable and worthwhile. If the mission statement 
of the National Coalition to Improve Youthful Driver Performance can be 
realized -- "To significantly reduce the number of youthful driver crashes, 
injuries and fatalities" -- everyone who participated in Crystal City and in the 
future of this effort will know that their lives have been useful. And that 
miracle can happen.<P>
</blockquote>
<HR><P>
<STRONG>David Thompson</STRONG> is the founder of the <A HREF="/car_control/index.html">New Driver Car Control Clinic</A>. 
This article first appeared in <STRONG>The News & Observer</STRONG>, Raleigh, North Carolina, on Thursday, September 19, 1996. Thompson can be reached at Tel: (919) 554-4022 or at <A HREF="mailto:autotest@nando.net">autotest@nando.net</A>
</body>
</html>
<p>
