<html><head>
<title>CHANGING THE DRIVER ATTITUDES THAT CAUSE AGGRESSIVE DRIVING BEHAVIORS</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>CHANGING THE DRIVER ATTITUDES THAT CAUSE AGGRESSIVE DRIVING BEHAVIORS</h2>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
by JOHN A. LARSON MD<P>

<I>John Larson is a lecturer in psychiatry at Yale University Medical School and a Director of the Institute of Stress Medicine in Norwalk, CT. </I><P>
(A Traffic Safety Information Village news article)<P>
Research by the Friedman institute, beginning in 1978 and by now including over 5,000 participants, has demonstrated conclusively that driver rage, impaired judgement, and risky driving behaviors can be dramatically reduced by group sessions aimed at changing drivers' values and attitudes. This is done by identifying the attitudes held and then systematically pairing each with an alternative attitude, which the participant learns. Once the new attitude is learned, driving behavior becomes safer.<P>

These findings came as a by-product of research aimed at preventing heart attacks. Individuals inclined to have heart attacks have a short fuse, both on and off the road. The Friedman Institute devised a 28 session group treatment to change attitudes triggering temper outbursts. The initial 12 sessions focused on over-reactivity on the road. Changing the attitudes leading to rage on the road proved relatively easy; rage reactions off the road took longer to change, but there too, changing the attitudes led to reduced anger, irritation, aggravation and impatience, and reduced incidence of heart attacks. <P>

Because the researchers were primarily interested in heart attack prevention the implication of the results for safer driving weren't considered. In 1987, I became interested in the possibilities when a rash of shootings occurred on highways in California. I knew how dramatically my own highway rage reactions had changed when I altered the attitudes I took to the highway, and I began writing a book on the subject and teaching this method to groups. <P>

The reason this approach works stems from how the brain works. Attitudes and beliefs have top priority in the brain; behavior follows attitudes. For example, if the teenage driver's attitude is to "show off" his or her driving skills, behavior will reflect this attitude. Parking, starting, passing, turning and merging will be done in an exaggerated fashion in order to "make it show". Secondly, the brain doesn't stop anything; it begins something new and the old brain activity falls into disuse, and eventually becomes discarded as the new behavior becomes reinforced and preferred. Hence, an alternative attitude to "showing off must be taught. For example, "highways are no place for games."<P>

The time is ripe now for research to demonstrate that this approach, incorporates into novice and adult driver training programs, will reduce traffic violations, accidents and deaths. In my opinion, enough data has already been assembled by the Friedman institute to justify a decisive research, establishing the method's practicability.<P>

My recent book, <i>Steering Clear of Highway Madness, </i> presents those principles derived from the research in a highly readable and understandable form. I propose its use as a text for that portion of driver training focusing on attitude change. The following rough outline of research would be relatively easy, inexpensive, and permit collection of data within three to 12 months. <P>

<B>First,</B> have the instructors read the book, carefully following the steps outlined; especially taking the test, before and after, and writing out 3 X 5 cards. The key is to learn "by heart" an alternative attitude to take at the precise moment when, ordinarily, the stress producing attitude is triggered. 
In this process, the instructors will become aware of changes in their own driving, which should convince them of the book's value. <P>

<B>Secondly,</B> add the book as an additional text, to several novice and/or adult classes (at least thirty students should be involved, although the more you have the greater the statistical validity). Students should be required to read the book, do the exercises described, discuss the materials in class, and pass a test on the knowledge.<P>

<B>Thirdly, </B>following the instructional phase, collect data on their driving records for one year, and compare them with a comparable control group (traffic violations, accidents, injuries and deaths). <P>


I will be happy to assist you by conducting seminars for your instructors. <i>Steering Clear of Highway Madness </i>  may be ordered from my office (fax: 203-838-3268) or from the publisher, BookPartners (Fax: 503-682-8684). <P>

<B>Steering Clear of Highway Madness</B><br>
by John A. Larson M.D.<br>
BookPartners, 1992. 190 pages. $14.95 ($19.95 Can)
<P></BLOCKQUOTE>




<p>
