<html><head>
<title>LEARNING TO DRIVE IN RUSSIA</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>LEARNING TO DRIVE IN RUSSIA</h2>
<p><i>This article was written by Les Dobson and is based on files <br>
from Finnish Traffic Safety researcher Reima Lehtimaki.</i><P> 

<blockquote>Armed police control checkpoints on major roads, pedestrians scurry out of the path of speeding cars, vehicle insurance is in its infancy and regarded with suspicion by many individuals. At the same time, traffic safety rates high on the school curriculum, many students join the popular "Traffic Scouts" movement and youngsters must be 14 before they ride a bicycle on public roadways, and then only after passing a test.<P>
That's the contradictory situation in Russia painted by Finnish traffic safety consultant Reima Lehtimaki after a recent visit to the republic of Mari El, about 600 kilometres east of Moscow.<P>
Before the collapse of the USSR, foreigners were denied entry to Mari El because of the missile bases there. These bases are  now closed. In common with much of Russia, Mari El is in economic chaos, but Lehtimaki feels the traffic situation there is similar to that prevailing across Russia.<P>
"Although there are few privately-owned vehicles, their number is rapidly increasing," he says. "Urban and rural public transport is abundant and profitable. There are many trucks, jeeps and motorcycles with sidecars. Bicycles are unusual in the towns and the bad condition of the roads makes their use difficult in rural areas.<P>
"In fact, vehicles suffer frequent damage because of the bad roads. Service stations and repair shops are rare," he adds. "Drivers have to make minor repairs themselves and spare parts are difficult to obtain. New vehicles are expensive. As a result, they're kept on the road as long as possible and every car owner needs a garage to protect against thieves. Guarded parking lots are provided for visitors."<P>
Lehtimaki says the automobile is, indeed, the "king of the road" and pedestrians need to keep their eyes peeled. Drivers negotiate the streets at high speed whenever the road surface permits. Road repairs take months and potholes are not always marked. About 200 road-related deaths annually occur in Mari El.<P>
That's the downside. On the other hand, Lehtimaki praises the GAI (pronounced "guy") or traffic police in making the best use of their resources under difficult economic circumstances. GAI has overall responsibility for road safety, including compliance with traffic regulations, technical inspection of vehicles, driver examination and licensing and vehicle registration. GAI, which operates at the federal, state and municipal levels, also co-operates with the education and health authorities in organizing school road safety programs.<P>

<H3>Training and licensing</H3><P>

Regulations introduced in 1994 provide for a uniform approach to traffic regulations across Russia, Lehtimaki says. Car driver training, for example, can be carried out by either a qualified driving school instructor or any licensed driver, providing they are a family member. Drivers cannot get their licence until they're 18, although training can begin as early as 16.<P>
Lehtimaki toured a commercial driving school in the capital city of Yoshkar-Ola that caters to car, bus, truck and trolley drivers and also gives instruction to drivers carrying hazardous materials. The car driver course, conducted mainly after working hours, includes 180 hours of theory and at least 16 hours of driver training.<P>
"Apart from traffic regulations and matters of safety, the course places considerable emphasis on technical matters," Lehtimaki says. "The driver must learn to make minor repairs on the highway. Trainees practice driving only on certain rural and urban routes stipulated by GAI."<P>
It takes two to three months to get a car licence if the student puts in a four-hour session at the school three times a week after work. The course to obtain a car licence costs 600,000 rubles, nearly twice an average month's salary. A theory examination must be passed before proceeding to the actual driving test, which is in two parts - a test in a field to check basic maneuvering skills followed by a test in urban traffic.<P>
GAI enforces speed limits and correct driving procedures by the use of police cars. Such items as documentation, mechanical safety and correct loading are controlled at fixed checkpoints. On seeing a policeman wearing a bullet-proof vest and carrying an automatic rifle at one of the checkpoints, Lehtimaki asked his hosts how often guns are used. "The GAI deputy chief told me the only incident he could recall in 43 years was when an injured moose had to be shot."<P>

<H3>Safety education begins early</H3><P>

Traffic safety education begins in the first grade and Lehtimaki was taken to a school in the city of Volsk, on the Volga River, that had a special classroom designed as a road crossing with traffic lights on the wall and lines painted on the floor. Youngsters were being taught how to safely cross the road. Traffic Scouts is a popular movement across Russia and scouts participate in a nationwide safety contest each year. Older scouts frequently tutor children of kindergarten age and it's not uncommon for the more active scouts to be recruited by GAI. All teachers take road safety training and parents are often the focus of campaigns regarding the use of seat belts and the placing of children in cars.<P>
Lehtimaki says a recently-enacted law permits private insurance companies to set up business and there are now 17 operating in Mari El. Insurance is not mandatory and one company he spoke to paid out only eight claims in 1995 - an indication that the insurance culture in Russia has a long way to go.<P>
The centralization of road safety under GAI has many positive aspects, Lehtimaki says, resulting in little overlapping of responsibilities or in-fighting over jurisdiction. Offsetting these advantages is the danger that road users are too much under the supervision of a single authority. However, the role GAI plays in traffic safety education does much to bolster its public image.<P>

Subscribers will find a more detailed report by Reima Lehtimaki in the <A HREF="infodbase.html">Village library</A></blockquote>






<p>
