<html><head>
<title>TEACHING THE PHYSICALLY CHALLENGED DRIVER </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>TEACHING THE PHYSICALLY CHALLENGED DRIVER </h2>
<p>We have just added to our free articles list a series of short articles by William Earl Jones, a former Assistant Professor at the University of Central Oklahoma, who now operates his own training service for physically challenged drivers in Oklahoma  City. <p>Most people take driving, the ability to drive, the process of learning to drive, for  granted. But every driving instructor knows that each novice driver who comes for  instruction brings to the car a unique set of capabilities, perceptions, knowledge and attitudes. <p>In fact we might, and  perhaps should, consider each and every individual  who wishes to learn to drive as having unique physical and mental challenges to conquer before becoming a fully fledged driver with full rights to operate a motor vehicle in our traffic system.<p>In the not-too-distant future, we very likely will look more carefully at each novice  driver candidate. We will identify strengths and weaknesses in the physical and and mental capabilities that are essential to driving and we will design programs that  are customized so that each individual gets the best possible training and education  before embarking on a lifetime of automobile driving in our highway traffic system.   <p>In the meantime, William Earl Jones offers some insights and advice into the challenges of diagnosing  and teaching physically challenged drivers, and some  details about teaching the driver who is challenged with aphasia.   <p>To see the articles by William Earl Jones please <a href= "http://www.pde.drivers.com/pde/pde-free/jonesmain.html">click here.</a> Visitors to the Village are invited to submit articles for inclusion in this free database.<p>


<p>
