<html><head>
<title>TEXAS LAW LETS PARENTS TEACH DRIVER ED</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>TEXAS LAW LETS PARENTS TEACH DRIVER ED</h2>
<p>A law just passed in Texas could result in Texas teens getting a full 
driving license at age 16 without even taking a road test. Ironically, 
the law, which was originally aimed at Òhome schoolersÓ (parents who teacher 
their kids at home instead of sending them to state-run schools), 
was tacked on to another bill which raises standards for the State's 
commercially run driving schools. Somewhere in the course of becoming law the 
Bill was changed to apply to all parents rather than just home schoolers. 

The law is currently being subjected to a review by State Attorney General 
Dan Morales before being put into effect. It is being protested by the driver 
education community, including the Driving School Association of Texas (DSAT).
As currently drafted, parents who opt to teach their own teens could purchase 
a course curriculum (for $20) from the Department of Public Safety (which 
oversees licensing in the State) and then sign two avidavits to have their 
teens licensed. One avidavit would testify that the teen had passed the 
requirements for a learnerÕs permit. The other would testify that the teen 
had passsed the driver education course. With these requirements met, the 
teen would not have to take a State behind-the-wheel driving test. 

ÒWe're not against parent input into driver training, says DSAT President 
Carlos Reyna, but we feel that it should be monitored and be a compliment to 
professional training, not a substitute for it.Ó

However, Republican Representative Jim Horn, who sponsored the bill,  is not 
backing off. ÒI'm incredibly strong to give home school parents the right and 
I see nothing wrong to allow all parents to do it. If it turns out itÕs a good
deal, and these kids probably drive better because their parents care about 
their safety more than somebody else, then we probably ought to leave it the 
way it is.Ó

Since the issue of family training Vs professional training is to critical to 
the driver training/education community we will be following up with more 
news and articles on this shortly.

<p>
<i>PDE
</i><p>
