<html><head>
<title>RESEARCH SUPPORTS TOUGHER TRAINING, TESTS </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>RESEARCH SUPPORTS TOUGHER TRAINING, TESTS </h2>
<p>A research study that reviewed and analysed existing scientific literature from around the world on how skill-related differences between novice drivers and experienced drivers
affect novice driver crash rates has just been published by the Insurance
Bureau of Canada IBC). <p>The review was supported by a survey of expert
opinion on the important skills that novices need to acquire to become
safer drivers. Amongst the recommendatons of the study are: that training
be extended to and more emphasis placed on critical skills and tasks; that
teaching strategeis be improved; that tests be made longer and place more
emphasis on critical skills; that examiners be trained to create more
demanding multiple-task driving situations and pay more attention to
searching and scanning abilities. <p>The report costs $95 Canadian and is
available from Tracy Waddington, The IBC, 181 University Ave., Toronto,
Ontario, Canada M5H 3M7. Tel: (416) 362-2031. An executive summary of the
report is available free. <p>A summary is also available to Village database
subscribers in the Summer 1995 issue of the Driver/Education
newsletter. <a href="http://pde.drivers.com/pde/ARTICLES/restricted/drive-ed1.html">Click here</a> for subscriber access.

<p>
