<html><head>
<title>TOUGHER TESTING, TRAINING - EUROPEAN VIEW</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>TOUGHER TESTING, TRAINING - EUROPEAN VIEW</h2>
<p>Young novice drivers don't evaluate risks as accurately as  older, more
experienced drivers, says Irish safety researcher Dr. Ray Fuller of Trinity
College Dublin's Psychology Department. Novices don't have "mental models"
of consequences of risky driving behaviour to draw on says Fuller, but they
should not have to rely on trial and error experience to develop them.<p>

However, the various training systems in place throughout Europe have not
produced significant differences in novice driver crash rates, says Fuller,
and he suggests that future training focus on such features as hazard
recognition, risk assessment, personal responsibility, and individuals'
perceptions of their own risk taking.<p>

As well, Dr Fuller urges that media campaigns on traffic safety be
evaluated. He suggests that they can made more effective by concentrating
on messages that the young driver can identify with and that assist them in
generating "mental simulations" of the consequences of risky driving, as is
done, for example, by an Irish National Safety Council media advertisement
in which fast driving is seen to result in a car runninginto a child
pedestrian and then overturning.<P>

Dr. Fuller also suggests that Ireland develop a national curriculum for
safe roadway use which would start with primary school education and
continue to early adulthood.<p>

Village database subscribers please <a href="http://pde.drivers.com/pde/ARTICLES/restricted/fuller-9533812137.html">click here</a> for the full text of Dr. Fuller's paper.

<p>
<i>
</i><p>
