<html><head>
<title>NEW TEST TO DETERMINE RISK OF AGED DRIVERS WITH DEMENTIA</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<h2>NEW TEST TO DETERMINE RISK OF AGED DRIVERS WITH DEMENTIA</h2>
<p>Alberta researchers are
developing the firsttest of its kind in Canada to help keep unfit elderly drivers with Alzheimer's or
other dementia off the road.
<P>
The computerized test, which involves a study of 130 elderly drivers with dementia, simulates driving
tasks that require attention, judgment and decision-making - all of which come into play when
performing such functions as merging with traffic and left turns at intersections.
<P>
Researchers, including those at the University of Alberta's Centre for Gerontology, plan to give
numerical scores for performance on the computer portion of the test. Seniors with middling scores
would be recommended for an in-car driving exam. The issue of people with dementia behind the
wheel is the focus of a heated debate as an aging population - particularly the fast-growing 85-plus
group - merges with the increasing prevelance of dementia after age 75.
<P>
A test that would be a strong predictor of driving performance would help physicians who have few,
if any, ways of evaulating the safety risk of a driver with dementia.
<P>
The project is a joint effort with the Northern Alberta Regional Geriatric Program and the Alberta
affiliate of the Canadian Automobile Association. The project is being financed by the Alberta
government and CARENET, the Canadian Aging Research Network at the University of Guelph in
Ontario.
<p>
<i>Toronto Globe and Mail
</i><p>
<img src="/icons/line_sun.gif" alt="-----">
