<h3><A NAME="stud">Students asked to sign agreement</A></h3><P>
At Hartland High School in Livingston County, Michigan, students entering driver education programs are asked to sign an agreement, along with their parent or guardian, which sets out expectations and restrictions for the student's first year of driving. These requirements are somewhat similar to the requirements of graduated licensing programs. Technical assistance for the program is being provided by the Traffic Safety Association of Michigan (TSAM) and the Michigan Department of State. For information about the program contact: Thomas Reel of the TSAM at (517) 487-8811. <P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A>

<blockquote><HR>
</blockquote>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="alcohol">Does DE work for alcohol offenders?</A></H3>

In recent years, educational programs for repeat offenders have become a popular alternative to fines and licence suspensions. This has been due to an assumption that drinking drivers lack knowledge or skills that would enable them to avoid subsequent offences. <P>
Evaluations of educational programs do show increases in knowledge and improved attitudes. However, evidence to show improvements in subsequent offence records has been scarce. One reason for this, it is suggested, is that the effects of the educational programs are long term. <P>
While there is no conclusive evidence of such effects, a unique long-term follow-up study by Dr. Robert Mann of the Addiction Research Foundation in Toronto, Ontario, has produced significant evidence of a positive result from educational programs. <P>
Dr. Mann examined the incidence and causes of death among two groups of impaired drivers, 7 to 13 years after their second conviction. One group had attended a brief educational program, the other had not. Those who had attended the educational program had a significantly lower mortality rate than those who did not. <P>
The lower deaths associated with the educational programs were from accidental and violent causes. There was no difference between the groups in deaths due to cirrhosis and alcohol dependence syndrome. <P>
This report was condensed from an article in <STRONG>Impact</STRONG>, Vol. 4, #4, November 1993. <STRONG>Impact</STRONG> is published by the Traffic Injury Research Foundation, Tel: (613) 238-5235. Fax: (613) 238-5292.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A>

<blockquote><HR>
</blockquote>
<H3><A NAME="private">California: Privatized testing</A></H3> <P>

California has just passed a bill that paves the way towards allowing certain driving schools to conduct California's driver licence road test. The bill passed the assembly on August 29 and was sent to the governor. <P>
If the governor consents to it, the bill will implement a pilot program to study testing by commercial driving schools. It will also impose duties on the Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) to monitor the privatized testing. Tests given by commercial driving schools will be the same as those given by the DMV and the DMV will conduct on-site inspections.<P>
Driving school examiners will be required to have at least 500 hours of instructional experience and may not test students they have previously instructed. <P>
The pilot study will commence on January 1, 1995.<P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A>

<blockquote><HR>
</blockquote>

<H3><A NAME="newtest">California's new test</A></H3>

The California Department of Motor Vehicles is developing a new driving test aimed at improving the state's drivers. <P>
Following recommendations by researcher Dr. James McKnight, the DMV has developed, and is now field-testing, a test known as the Driver Performance Evaluation (DPE). The new test is intended to provide a longer and more comprehensive road test, using routes that reflect the state's complex driving environments, and with scoring criteria that will provide for more objectivity and standardization. It's expected to be a much tougher test that will drive standards for training and education in the coming years. The pilot program began in late May 1994. <P>
Applicants taking the new test will be expected to do freeway driving, and deal with merging traffic, bicycle lanes, and traffic congestion. They will also be expected to identify mechanical equipment on their vehicles and do a pre-drive check test. Failure to carry out these test elements will result in postponement or disqualification. The test will take about 20 minutes.<P>

<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A>

<blockquote><HR>
</blockquote>


<H3><A NAME="whatis">What is driver education?</A></H3>

What image comes to mind when you hear the words &quot;driver education&quot;? According to a &quot;non-scientific&quot; survey, says traffic safety consultant Jack Weaver in a recent newsletter to his clients, most people think of it as &quot;a high school course for young drivers.&quot; <P>
This is a wrong impression, says Dr. Weaver. But it's a view held by 80&#37; of those surveyed, and this included police, traffic judges, even high school teachers. <P>
&quot;The point is,&quot; writes Weaver, &quot;those of us that have been working in the driver and traffic safety education profession for several years have done a damn poor job of public information.&quot; Driver education is much more than school courses for beginners, he says . &quot;It is an education, training and information dissemination program in which all public and private agencies and businesses can and should participate&#138;It is a training and education effort intended to improve the knowledge and skills of every highway and roadway user from the cradle to the grave.&quot;<P>
Weaver prefers the title &quot;Driver and Traffic Safety Education&quot;. This, he feels, reflects the fact that it's multi-program training and education which serves a wide clientele.<P>
Traffic safety groups &quot;are finally realizing the need to synthesize the various elements of driver and traffic safety education into a dynamic public and private force,&quot; says Weaver. <P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A>

<blockquote><HR>
</blockquote>
<H3><A NAME="video">Putting it all on video</A></H3>

Driving school owner Darrell Cyr has been in business in Kansas City for 32 years. He runs, he says, &quot;Kansas's foremost driving school--one of the few schools in the country that can issue an exemption from the state driver's examination upon course completion.&quot; A few years ago Cyr put some of his instructional techniques onto a video he titled <STRONG>Drive to Stay Alive</STRONG> (see <STRONG>Driver/Education</STRONG>, March 1993). Now he's putting his whole program on video. Darrell Cyr's <STRONG>Driver's Training--As It Really Happens</STRONG> takes a 14-year-old student from her first time behind the wheel to final testing for the states driver's examination.<P>
There are eight videos, says Cyr, and &quot;each tape is shot as it really happened--no second takes, no rehearsals.&quot; The tapes were only edited to eliminate repetition. On-screen subtitles are used to keep track of each important point and lesson learned. <P>
For information call 1-800-533-2423. <P>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Table of Contents</A>

<blockquote><HR>
</blockquote>
<H3><A NAME="init">Canada's safety initiatives: Blueprint for the future</A></H3>

The Canada Safety Council is hosting a follow-up to the 'Facing The Challenge 2001' conference hosted by the Canadian Council of Motor Transport Administrators (CCMTA) and the Transportation Association of Canada (TAC) last February in Toronto, Ontario.<P>
The conference, titled &quot;Your Piece of The Puzzle,&quot; will take place in Ottawa, Ontario on March 15, 1995. Its goal is to offer individuals and representatives from associations, government agencies and companies a chance to develop their own strategies within the national agenda for reducing traffic crashes. <P>
During sessions and workshops at the conference, attendees will have the assistance of knowledgeable safety practitioners from national, provincial and local levels of government, and industry will provide sample models for delegates to work from.<P>
During the February conference (see <STRONG>Driver/Education</STRONG>, June 1994) five priorities in road safety were identified. These were: <P>

<UL><LI>To improve driver education and public awareness.<LI>
To promote a higher level of communication and cooperation amongst various road safety stakeholders.<LI>
To improve financial support, particularly by re-allocating funds.<LI>
To improve the quality of road safety data.<LI>
To improve enforcement through efficiency and better allocation of resources.</ul><P>

Among the solutions proposed under the heading of public awareness and education were the following:  <P>

<UL><LI>Stimulating public debate and marketing safety issues by raising awareness of injuries, pain, death and suffering to an emotional level.<LI>
Demonstrating the health costs.<LI>
Promoting alternative transportation.<LI>
Using the media to promote road safety issues.<LI>
Mobilizing communities and public education organizations to organize communication networks through mobile phones&#59; toll free numbers to report dangerous driving or traffic problems&#59; computer bulletin boards&#59; publications.  <LI>
Promoting childhood traffic education from kindergarten through Grade 12.</UL><P>

<STRONG>DRIVER EDUCATION</STRONG><P>

In the area of driver education the solutions suggested were:<P>

<UL><LI>Development of national minimum standards for all road safety educators, programs and driver's tests. <LI>
Self-regulating and monitoring of driving schools<LI>
Cooperative approach between government and driving schools for delivery of driver improvement programs.<LI>
encourage effective incentives to take training and retraining programs (e.g. employer-sponsored).<LI>
Raise the profile of driver education<LI>
Increase program emphasis on human factors, injury prevention, defensive driving, collision avoidance techniques, risk assessment and decision making.</UL><P>

<STRONG>NEW DRIVERS</STRONG><P>

It was suggested that graduated licensing systems be adopted by all jurisdictions, utilizing a uniform model wherever appropriate. Also that:<P>

<UL><LI>Effectiveness be monitored.<LI>
More challenging road tests be established.<LI>
Secondary training programs be encouraged for all new drivers. <LI>
Remedial sanctions for violations of graduated licensing restrictions. </UL><P>

